<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland-Solidarity     09-14 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Solidarity,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition and Authorities To Meet Thursday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity's Lech Walesa appeared to stand
firm Wednesday on the issue of legalizing his federation, on the
eve of a second preparatory meeting with authorities before talks
on Poland's future.
   ``There is no freedom without Solidarity,'' he told reporters
upon arriving in Warsaw from his home in Gdansk.
   Walesa refused to confirm he will be meeting with communist
authorities on Thursday. When pressed for comment on the talks, the
leader of the outlawed free trade union movement replied, ``We will
know more tomorrow.''
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said a meeting of Walesa,
Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak and two or three other
people would take place at noon Thursday to resolve obstacles to
convening the talks.
   Walesa said he planned to remain in Warsaw through Friday before
departing for the southern city of Czestochowa to attend a workers'
pilgrimage over the weekend at the Jasna Gora monastery.
   Elsewhere, members of the official union for transport workers
in Gdynia idled bus and streetcar service in that Baltic port city
of 250,000 for about six hours Wednesday to protest their pay, a
union spokesman said.
   Walesa earlier this month ended a series of Solidarity-led
strikes in exchange for the promise of talks on the federation's
future.
   But the brief Gdynia stoppage was mounted by an official trade
union created after Solidarity was outlawed in 1982.
   Regional official union spokesman Stanislaw Koscielak said the
transport workers want a pay increase of $6 a month which they were
promised last year but never received. Average pay nationwide is
about $100 monthly.
   Koscielak claimed the strike was legal under a 1982 law that
allows strikes after a period of negotiation and arbitration. A
spokesman at the main depot, who refused to give his name, said
drivers began striking at 5 a.m. but went back to work at 11 a.m.
   The official trade union alliance, known by its Polish initials
OPZZ, has been pressing the government to liberalize the laws on
the right to strike. It has complained that denying official unions
the strike weapon undermines their credibility with workers.
   The government acknowledges widespread worker unhappiness. This
year's inflation rate has climbed to 60 percent, with supplies of
consumer goods to stores even more erratic than usual because of
increased exports to offset Poland's $39 billion foreign debt.
</TEXT>
