<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra-Propaganda     09-14 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra-Propaganda,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Covert Operatives Boosted Reagan's Central American
Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House staff report says U.S. experts in
covert intelligence and psychological operations exceeded their
authority in helping rally public support for President Reagan's
Central America policies.
   The House Foreign Affairs Committee staff said Tuesday these
operatives ``conspired, through the staff of the National Security
Council, to use the State Department as a cover for a domestic
operation which went far beyond the legal and ethical scope of
their authority.''
   Individuals and organizations working in the 1983-86 operation
raised and spent money to influence congressional votes and the
U.S. news media, the report said.
   The ``domestic political and propaganda operation'' was run
through the State Department's Office of Public Diplomacy for Latin
America and the Caribbean, known as ``S@LPD,'' according to the
committee's chief counsel, R. Spencer Oliver, and staff consultant
Bert Hammond.
   The office reported directly to the National Security Council
rather than through the normal State Department channels, a system
established over the objections of Secretary of State George P.
Shultz.
   The staff report said many of the activities on behalf of
Reagan's Central American policies were carried out by recipients
of no-bid contracts ``hidden from public view.''
   Some of the organizations with no-bid contracts also were part
of former NSC aide Oliver L. North's secret program to raise money
for the Nicaraguan Contra rebels. North used these fund-raising
efforts along with funds diverted from U.S. arms sales to Iran in
an elaborate scheme to aid the Contras at time when Congress had
banned such aid.
   Reagan, when asked about the report by reporters Tuesday, held
his thumb and forefinger about an inch apart to show how much
attention he thought the study deserved.
   ``One day, I promise you, in a paragraph only about that long,
I'm going to tell you the truth about Iran-Contra, as I did when it
first came to light and which no one is reporting today,'' he said.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater indicated that Reagan
may write more than a paragraph. Calling the allegations ``old
hat,'' Fitzwater said the president plans to tell his side of the
Iran-Contra affair in a book that Reagan will author after leaving
office.
   ``He feels it has been told, but that it just keeps coming up
over and over again and people forget the original answers and the
original investigations,'' the spokesman said.
   The report did not cite any laws or presidential directives that
were violated, and it was not endorsed by the Foreign Affairs
Committee members. It was sent to the panel's chairman, Dante B.
Fascell, D-Fla.
   Hammond said the committee staff has asked the Congressional
Research Service of the Library of Congress to investigate whether
the operation violated laws restricting CIA domestic activities;
government lobbying; and use of appropriated money for domestic
propaganda purposes.
   While many of the activities of the Office of Public Diplomacy
have been reported extensively in the past, the new study
emphasized the role of intelligence experts applying their craft in
a domestic operation, instead of the foreign covert operations for
which they were trained.
   A presidential executive order on intelligence activities says
U.S. covert operations cannot include an effort to influence the
public opinion or public policy of the United States.
   While the transfer of intelligence operatives to domestic
agencies is not improper under the order, the activities they
perform could violate the order, according to congressional
intelligence experts.
   The report said Donald Gregg, a former high-ranking CIA official
who is now national security adviser to Vice President George Bush,
initiated the recommendation that led to the assignment of former
CIA propaganda expert Walter Raymond Jr. to the NSC group that
directed the public diplomacy office.
   Bush, the GOP presidential nominee, has been questioned during
the campaign about his role as chief of a Reagan administration
task force on Central America policy and his association with Gregg.
   Raymond, according to the report, ``was instrumental in
facilitating the assignment of intelligence personnel from the
Department of Defense to S@LPD and the expansion of State
Department resources available to S@LPD,'' the report said.
   ``On one occasion,'' the report said, ``five intelligence
experts from the Army's 4th Psychological Operations Group at Fort
Bragg, N.C.'' were assigned to work with the office, then headed by
Otto Reich, the current U.S. ambassador to Venezuela.
</TEXT>
