<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     09-14 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Aide Wary Of Proposed Labeling Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department wants to change the
rules governing the labels on American hot dogs but is proceeding
over the objections of a White House regulatory official.
   Department officials thought a proposal to allow processors to
include salvaged meat and ground bone in their recipes without
explicitly noting the contents in product labels would be in line
with President Reagan's policy of stripping away some of the layers
of federal regulation.
   The proposal would allow up to 10 percent mechanically reclaimed
meat and tiny bone chips in hot dogs and a number of similar items
without explicitly noting the contents in product labels.
   When animals are slaughtered, most of the red meat is cut or
scraped from bones by hand. But a lot of edible tissue clings to
the bones and gristle, particularly in neck bones, ribs, joints and
other hard-to-scrape places.
   The bones and the attached meat remnants are put through a
grinder and forced through fine sieves. Although most of the bones
are strained out, the resulting mixture still contains bits of bone
about the size of ground pepper.
   Under current regulations, the salvaged meat and bone chips are
allowed in up to 20 percent of the meat portion of these products,
but the labels must state that the products contain the reclaimed
mixture.
   The mixture is known as ``mechanically separated'' meat, or MSM,
although current regulations describe it as MS(S) to acknowledge
the species of animal involved. Thus, salvaged meat from a hog
would be mechanically separated pork, or MSP.
   According to a group of meat processors who asked USDA for the
rule change, no company at present is commercially producing MS(S)
for consumer products because of ``unwarranted negative
connotations'' associated with the term MS(S).
   The USDA plan did not set well with Jay Plager, administrator of
information and regulatory affairs in the Office of Management and
Budget. He told USDA in a letter on Aug. 19 that the proposed rule
change ``does not appear to be consistent with several of the
administration's basic regulatory principles.''
   Plager added: ``Nor does it appear that the potential benefits
to society of this regulation outweigh the potential cost to
society.''
   Christopher Hicks, the USDA's general counsel, replied that
department officials ``do not agree with the conclusions'' set
forth by Plager.
   ``There are compelling reasons for proposing this rule,
including the fact that it may produce benefits to society that
outweigh societal costs,'' Hicks told Plager in a Sept. 6 letter.
   Copies of the letters by Plager and Hicks were provided to The
Associated Press on Tuesday.
   Advocates of the rule change contend that consumers won't buy
products containing the salvaged material if labels inform them
about it.
   The proposal, which began a 60-day rulemaking procedure on Sept.
9, was announced on Monday by the department's Food Safety and
Inspection Service.
   Under various names, MS(S) has been authorized for use in the
meat products since 1978 and has undergone numerous legal
challenges from consumer groups opposed to the salvaged product
itself or labeling requirements.
   According to the plan, which will be open for public comment
until Nov. 8, processors would be able to use MS(S) to comprise up
to 10 percent of the meat in franks, bologna, luncheon meats,
sausage and similar products without stating so on product labels.
   However, the label would have to indicate the percentage of the
Recommended Daily Allowance of calcium that the product contained.
Calcium is a primary ingredient of bone tissue.
   The American Meat Institute, a private association that
represents meat packers and processors, said in a statement that
the use of calcium on labels would be ``a more meaningful and
useful term'' to consumers than MS(S), particularly to those who
have a calcium deficiency and to a few who are allergic to calcium
and should be warned away from such products.
   In its brief statement, the institute said, ``There is no
wholesomeness or safety issue involved'' in the MS(S) proposal.
   But Plager said the assertion that consumers would avoid
products labeled as containing MS(S) had not been documented in the
proposed rule change.
   ``Furthermore, if one accepts the assertion that some consumers
would be reluctant to purchase a product that they know to contain
MS(S), why should this information be omitted from the label?'' he
said.
   Plager said that in seeking ways to carry out less burdensome
food safety regulations, ``We must also provide consumers with
more, rather than less, information about food products so that
they may reach informed market decisions.''
</TEXT>
