<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Reagan     09-14 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Stumping for GOP Ticket in Missouri, Where He Won Big in
1984</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top expected about 10 a.m. EDT with remarks embargoed for
1:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As President Reagan follows Vice President
George Bush into Missouri, he is taking his campaign for the
Republican ticket to a state he carried narrowly in 1980 and
resoundingly four years ago.
   Reagan was flying today to Cape Girardeau, a shipping center on
the Mississippi River, for a rally at Southeast Missouri State
University, and then on to St. Louis to address 1,000 guests at a
$250-a-plate fund-raising dinner.
   ``The general thrust of both of these speeches is support for
the Republican ticket, acknowledgement of the economic successes of
this administration, discussion of the differences between liberals
and conservatives,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
Tuesday.
   ``The first rally speech may focus a little more on the economy
and the second one a little more on military strength,'' the
spokesman said. ``But they will both be traditional political
speeches, covering the themes that the president has discussed in
the past.''
   The president plans one or two speaking forays each week until
the Nov. 8 election.
   GOP candidates who will benefit from the Missouri events include
Gov. John Ashcroft, seeking a second term against Democratic State
Rep. Betty Hearnes of Charleston, the wife of former Gov. Warren
Hearnes; and Sen. John Danforth, opposed by State Sen. Jay Nixon of
Hillsboro as he seeks his third term.
   Both Ashcroft and Danforth enjoy comfortable leads in state
public opinion polls.
   Bush, speaking Tuesday in Jefferson City, the state capital,
pledged, ``We will never go back to the grain-embargo days of those
Democrats, Carter and Mondale, and who knows who else.''
   Reagan took Missouri's 11 electoral votes with 51 percent of the
popular vote against then-President Carter in 1980 and swept the
state with 60 percent of the popular vote against Walter Mondale in
1984.
   Records showed that the only incumbent president to visit Cape
Girardeau previously was William Howard Taft on Oct. 26, 1902.
Reagan will speak at the year-old Show Me Center.
   In St. Louis, the state's most populous city with a metropolitan
area population of more than 2 million, the president will speak at
the Omni Hotel St. Louis at an event for the Missouri GOP Victory
'88 fund.
</TEXT>
