<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shultz-Philippines     09-14 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Philippines,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US-Filipino Impasse on Bases Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new effort to end the impasse between the
United States and the Philippines over the terms of U.S. access to
strategic bases in the Philippines ended with no apparent narrowing
of differences.
   ``There has been nothing to justify my saying that we are closer
together,'' Philippines Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus told
reporters after a 45-minute meeting Tuesday with Secretary of State
George P. Shultz at the State Department.
   The major issue in the talks is U.S. compensation to the
Philippines for use of the bases.
   Manglapus, who also plans meetings with Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci and congressional leaders during his visit, said the two
sides are not far apart on a cash aid figure but that there has
been no agreement on other components of an aid package.
   Manglapus declined to provide details of the aid figures being
discussed but congressional sources and reports in the Philippines
indicated he is asking for about $1.2 billion annually over the
next two years.
   This would represent a sizeable increase over the $180 million a
year to which the Reagan administration has been committed since
1983. In addition to cash aid, the Philippines also is said to be
seeking trade concessions, debt relief and other ``soft
components,'' as Manglapus described them.
   The administration reportedly has offered $360 million yearly in
1989 and 1990 in addition to food assistance and other concessions
for a total of just under $500 million.
   Shultz said last week the Filipino demands were ``out of
bounds,'' adding that ``we will be patient and we will be
persistent'' in efforts to overcome the impasse.
   The State Department had no comment on the meeting with
Manglapus. The talks revolve around the terms for continued
American use of Subic Bay Naval Base and Clark Air Base, two of the
most important U.S. facilities outside the United States.
   The ongoing talks involve other issues, including the presence
of U.S. nuclear weapons at the bases, but most of the attention has
focused on compensation.
   Manglapus said a substantial aid increase is warranted partly to
correct what he suggested was a historical injustice, contending
that the United States used military facilities in the Philippines
for more than 70 years without compensating Filipino authorities.
   In other countries, he said, the United States has provided aid
immediately after establishing military bases.
   Manglapus said American analysts have concluded that the bases
benefit the United States more than the Philippines because ``there
is no external threat to the Philippines today.''
</TEXT>
