<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Pesticides     09-14 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pesticides,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pesticide Safety Bill Moving in House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm lawmakers are moving to impose an
eight-year deadline for the completion of safety research on
hundreds of chemicals that are used to protect crops from damaging
pests.
   The plan, aimed at toughening federal regulation because of
growing concern about potential health hazards, won House
Agriculture Committee apprval Tuesday on a voice vote and now heads
to the House floor.
   Under the legislation, the Environmental Protection Agency would
have eight years to complete its safety reviews of hundreds of
pesticides.
   The agency, working under no deadline, has been finishing
reviews of about two dozen chemicals a year since the mid-1970s
when it took over the job from the Agriculture Department.
   The legislation also would largely end government payments to
chemical companies to buy up supplies of recalled pesticides. Such
payments have totaled $20 million so far.
   Critics say the cost of these ``indemnities'' has caused the EPA
to drag its feet in proceeding with the safety reviews. Under the
bill, chemical companies and the agency would share the cost of
storing and disposing of the pesticides, and manufacturers would
bear the costs of conducting the reviews.
   Lawmakers have been stymied since 1983 in efforts to reauthorize
the 1949 Federal Insecticide, Fungicide and Rodenticide Act
(FIFRA). They had been saying no action was likely until next year.
   Committee approval of the latest bill, however, signaled an
effort to send legislation to the president before Congress
adjourns next month. Few, however, expressed much enthusiasm for
what they called a modest effort in which the lack of far-reaching
features could prove the key to political success.
   Committee aides issued a bill summary headlined ``FIFRA Lite.''
   ``I doubt very much that there's a man on the dais who thinks
that we're doing the right thing, but we're doing what we have to
do,'' Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, told the committee.
   He said recalled pesticides currently in storage should be
burned but that lawmakers lacked the political will to push through
legislation requiring it.
   Agriculture Committee Chairman E. ``Kika'' de la Garza, D-Texas,
said the problem was that no lawmaker wanted the incinerator in his
or her home district.
   Environmentalists were concerned about the absence of any
provision calling for federal regulation of pesticides in ground
water, which represents the basic drinking supply for half of all
Americans. But they said the legislation could be worse.
   ``Like the first law of medicine, they have done no harm,'' said
Rick Hind of the U.S. Public Interest Research Group, an
organization founded by Ralph Nader that has waged a long pesticide
safety battle.
   The group issued a report Tuesday saying a search of EPA records
showed 73 pesticides have been found in ground water in 34 states,
a slight increase over previous reports from the agency.
   ``Putting off action on ground water is better than doing
something awful on ground water, which is what they would have
done,'' said Maureen Hinckle, lobbyist from the National Audubon
Society.
   ``Pesticide regulation in this country is a public health
scandal that affects each and every consumer,'' said Michelle
Meier, Consumers Union counsel for government affairs. ``This clean
piece of legislation shows that Congress is serious about tackling
the problem once and for all this year.''
   Farmers and exterminators use some 2.6 billion pounds of
pesticides in the United States every year. Perhaps 40,000 products
are sold, but they are basically formulations of 656 active
ingredients.
   An outgrowth of World War II chemical warfare research,
pesticides have played a major part in increasing crop yields and
placing better-looking farm products on grocers' shelves. But some
of the chemicals have been found to cause cancer and other severe
health problems in laboratory animals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880914-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-6MilesUpandSleepyIII 2Takes   09-14 0819</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-6 Miles Up and Sleepy III, 2 Takes,0834</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>6 Miles Up and Sleepy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part III: The Search For Solutions _ As Simple As Naptime?</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Airline pilots must fly when passengers want to
travel: early in the morning, late at night, across continents and
oceans, regardless of the vagaries of delays and bad weather.
Despite these grueling schedules, however, dangerous fatigue is not
inevitable. This final story in a three-part AP Extra series, ``6
Miles Up and Sleepy,'' examines ways of coping with sleepiness in
the cockpit.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   One often-proposed solution to the dangers of pilot fatigue is
legalization of a remedy that is obvious and widely practiced, but
forbidden _ naps in the cockpit.
   Passengers may blanch at the idea of their captain snoozing
while they watch a movie six miles above the Earth. But sleep
researchers contend this is a sensible way to cope with the flight
crew exhaustion caused by late-night arrivals, early-morning
departures and time-zone crossings.
   While air travel is generally safe, the experts say it could be
safer still if human frailties were considered in the design of
flight rules, pilot schedules and the planes themselves.
   Some in the flying business, however, are reluctant to
acknowledge fatigue as a concern. The Federal Aviation
Administration has publically voiced skepticism that sleepy pilots
create a hazard in the skies. The airlines seem to fear that
proposed rule changes would make scheduling more difficult, and
some pilots fret that they would lose the large blocks of free time
they now enjoy.
   Industry observers, moreover, contend that one of the most
powerful impediments to change is the very image of the airline
pilot: fit, trim and male, calm, confident and capable. Surely such
a person can deal with a little thing like sleepiness.
   ``There is a widely held belief that mental toughness, good
management or physical fitness will overcome sleepiness. That is
categorically incorrect,'' said Dr. David Dinges, a sleep
researcher at the University of Pennsylvania. ``Your brain still
needs sleep, and you get yoursef into serious trouble when you try
to tough that out.''
   Several approaches are being considered: cockpits that monitor
their operators, medicines that help flight crews sleep when off
duty, schedules that figure in the time of departure and the
direction of travel as well as the length of the work day.
   But one of the easiest and simplest solutions is the nap.
   ``It's common knowledge that people are napping in the cockpit
because they are so tired,'' said R. Curtis Graeber, a sleep
scientist at the NASA-Ames Research Center in California. ``We are
looking very closely at the potential safety benefits of allowing
limited napping in the seat.''
   The U.S. Air Force encourages its crews to nap on long cargo
flights, and some foreign countries, Britain and West Germany among
them, allow sleeping in airline cockpits. Under Federal Aviation
Administration rules, however, napping is considered careless and
reckless operation of the aircraft.
   Yet on the long mid-flight stretches across continents and
oceans, pilots have little to do but monitor their dials. Nature
takes its course. In interviews with The Associated Press, pilots
reported frightening instances of awakening to find their two
colleagues sound asleep as the airliner cruises through the night
skies.
   Graeber proposes that naps be carefully scheduled so each member
of the flight crew anticipates a rest period.
   ``Napping will be very helpful, if it's ever implemented,''
agreed Mary Carskadon, a sleep researcher at Brown University. ``It
makes so much more sense to schedule it in than to all of a sudden
have all three members of the flight crew asleep because no one is
scheduled to sleep.''
   Far more difficult, the experts agree, is improving pilot
schedules. Rules set by the FAA and union agreements dictate how
many hours a day pilots can be on duty and in the air. But the
standards allow myriad permutations of day and night departures and
arrivals that often leave crews out of synchronism with their
internal circadian clocks.
   ``I think pilot scheduling is as good as it can be right now
reflecting what we know,'' said Alan McArtor, head of the FAA. ``As
we understand it better, the scheduling, I think, will reflect
that.''
   McArtor and airline officials are awaiting results of research
now being conducted jointly by NASA, the Airline Pilots Association
and United Airlines.
   Beginning this fall, Graeber and other researchers will fly with
pilots on long, over-ocean routes, monitoring their body
temperatures and brain waves as they fly through the night.
   The resulting advice may not please either pilots or airlines.
   Pilots, often vehement critics of schedules, might find their
flight time spread over a longer calendar period, eliminating the
intense two to three weeks of flying that gives them the rest of
the month off.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
