<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0212EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EndowedCoach     09-14 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Endowed Coach,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$1 Million Gift to Endow Football Coach's Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yale University has endowed faculty
chairs in numerous esoteric fields. Now the Ivy League school's
football coach will join that elite company as the Joel E. Smilow
Coach of Football.
   Yale announced Tuesday that Smilow, a 1954 Yale graduate and
president, chairman and chief executive officer of Stamford-based
Playtex Inc., had donated $1 million to endow the head football
coach's job, the first endowed position in the athletic department.
   ``Excellence in football is not a core objective of Yale or any
other great institution of higher education,'' said Smilow, whose
college football career was limited to intramural touch football.
   ``However, it is my belief that football is an integral part of
the very broad objective of attracting, educating and motivating
persons with the potential to become tomorrow's leaders,
irrespective of the field of endeavor which they choose to pursue.''
   Yale officials would not release the salary of Yale's football
coach, Carmen Cozza, who is entering his 24th season and has
compiled a record of 139 wins, 70 losses and 4 ties. School
officials also would not say how much of the endowment will be used
to finance the position.
   Yale President Benno C. Schmidt said Smilow's gift ``will help
carry forward the glorious tradition of varsity football at Yale.''
   But the gift provoked mild disapproval among some students.
   ``The money could go to something else,'' said junior Elizabeth
Archley. ``I can't see what else Carm Cozza could do that would
warrant such money.''
   Smilow brushed aside the criticism, saying the gift would allow
the university to use money from the coach's salary in other areas.
   As an undergraduate, Smilow broadcast Yale football games as
sports director for WYBC, the college radio station, and said
during a telephone interview that his secret ambition had been ``to
be a Brent Musburger,'' the sports announcer for CBS.
   ``I love Yale and I love football,'' he said.
   Although football is generally considered a more genteel affair
in the Ivy League than in powerhouse leagues like the Southwest,
Southeastern, Big Eight and Pacific-10 Conference, Yale boasts
among its alumni Calvin Hill, who played as a running back for the
Dallas Cowboys after graduating in 1966; and Rich Diana, a 1982
graduate who played for the Miami Dolphins.
   Yale also has more football victories than any other college in
the nation _ 743, followed by the University of Michigan's 684. And
Yale has had 118 players named All-Americans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880914-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Motorcade     09-14 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Motorcade,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Encounters Cheering Students, Unhappy Restaurateur</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TIPTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush has got a hankering to turn back
the clock about half a century so he can be a teen-ager again.
   That's what he told a roadside crowd of school children and
youths who gathered in this rural town to watch his campaign
motorcade go by Tuesday.
   Speaking on his limousine loudspeaker, he told them, ``I must
confess, I wish I was about a junior, maybe a senior in high
school, because I see the next decade strong, and I see the next
decade a challenge.''
   The 300 young people standing on the grounds of Tipton High
School cheered with delight at the vice president's impromptu
remarks and the sight of the long motorcade with security agents
and official looking entourage.
   Two teachers said the high school was notified by campaign
officials about 15 minutes ahead of time that the motorcade would
pass by, so the students, along with some younger children from an
elementary school, came out to see the excitement.
   Bush spoke to them for a few minutes, saying he just wanted to
see the home of the undefeated Tipton High football team.
   Bush said he likes to get out to these local communities to
``understand the heartbeat of the United States'' while ``a lot of
people are sitting back in Washington or some university'' wanting
to ``knock the system.''
   Bush concluded by pledging himself to work for a more peaceful
and prosperous world. He shook hands with the children who surged
forward, and then his motorcade continued down the country road.
   But it was only a few miles before the vice president had an
encounter with the ``you can't please everybody'' department.
   There was another quick stop, this one at a corner convenience
store called Break Time.
   It seems the vice president was getting a little hungry on the
long drive from Jefferson City, where he had a rally, to Whiteman
Air Force Base, where his plane awaited.
   So Bush, his wife, Barbara, and their Secret Service retinue
trooped into the little store to pick up a couple of slices of
pizza and some soft drinks.
   The vice president told the young woman cashier he was starving
as he pulled out his wallet and paid for the food.
   Outside, while Bush briefly shook hands with a few curious
onlookers, a local police officer was informing other members of
the entourage that all was not well at the Butterfield Inn
restaurant next door.
   It seems the proprietor had been told to expect a lunch stop by
the Bush brigade before Bush veered off to the convenience store.
   ``He's got that place all set up for the vice president,'' the
officer said. ``Tell him thanks a lot.''
   Asked later aboard Air Force Two whether he was aware of the
perceived slight, Bush showed surprise, but said: ``We weren't
looking for a big fancy restaurant. I didn't want a fancy meal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
