<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0828,0656</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Norstad and Frei; An AMs separate moved as a0789 on
Hargreaves and a0862 on Norstad.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Roger Hargreaves</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roger Hargreaves, who turned his deskpad doodlings
into the popular ``Mister Men'' and ``Little Miss'' storybooks for
children, died Monday of a heart attack at age 53.
   Combining his doodles with bed-time stories he made up for his
own children, it took Hargreaves just two weeks to find a publisher
and in 1972 his first six stories went on sale. They introduced
young readers to Mister Bump, Mister Strong and Mister Sneezy.
   In 1981, he began a series featuring such characters as Little
Miss Fussy and Little Miss Sunshine. Some 85 million are in
circulation, translated into 22 languages. The stories have more
than 750 characters and spinoffs include a television cartoon
series and childrens' cups and plates, stationery and clothing.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Charlie Palmieri</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charlie Palmieri, a salsa pianist who as a band
leader helped create new forms of Latin jazz, died Monday
apparently of a heart attack. He was in his early 60s.
   Palmieri played with Latin dance orchestras and hotel bands,
including those led by Tito Puente and Mongo Santamaria. In 1959,
he introduced the band Charanga Duboney, a group that was popular
in New York.
   In 1961, Palmieri became musical director of the Allegre
All-Stars, who merged mambos with jazz solos. He also performed
with his own groups and as a guest with other jazz musicians.
Palmieri's most recent album was ``A Giant Step.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Nady Cates</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM (AP) _ Nady M. Cates Jr., the managing editor of
Winston-Salem's former afternoon paper, The Sentinel, died Monday
at the age of 84.
   In 1922, Cates joined with a classmate, Walter Crissman, to
start the first high school newspaper in North Carolina, The
Pointer.
   He began reporting for the Greensboro Record in 1924 and later
worked in High Point. Cates joined the Journal in Winston-Salem in
1930. In 1934, he linked up with The Sentinel, and became its
assistant managing editor in 1941. Cates became managing editor in
1946 and retired in 1972.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Lauris Norstad</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lauris Norstad, a retired Air Force General
and the first airman to serve as commander of NATO forces in
Western Europe, died Monday. He was 81.
   Promoted to brigadier general in 1943, Norstad was involved in
planning fr the Allied invasion of North Africa. He personally went
ashore with the assault forces, earning a Silver Star for gallantry.
   Gen. Dwight Eisenhower, then Army chief of staff, appointed
Norstad director of plans and operations after the war. Later, when
Eisenhower was head of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, he
made him his leading air commander.
   Norstad was promoted to four-star general in 1952. In 1956, he
was appointed supreme commander of Allied forces in Western Europe,
becoming the first airman to head the 15-nation NATO forces.
   Norstad was named president of Owens-Corning Fiberglas
International after he retired from the military.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Hans Frei</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hans W. Frei, a leading Christian
theologian and professor of religious studies at Yale University,
died Monday at age 66.
   Frei earned a bachelor of divinity from Yale in 1945, and
received his doctorate from Yale in 1956. He served as minister of
the First Baptist Church in North Stratford, N.H., from 1945 to
1947 and taught at Wabash College in Indiana and the Episcopal
Theological Seminary of the Southwest before joining the Yale
faculty in 1957.
   Frei was perhaps best known for his book ``The Eclipse of
Biblical Narrative,'' an influential work on the principles of
biblical interpretation. He also wrote ``The Identity of Jesus
Christ,'' and a number of essays on Karl Barth and H. Richard
Neibuhr, two of the 20th century's most important theologians.
</TEXT>
