<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miss America No. 1 in American's TV Heart</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She might not be any match for them on the
field, but Miss America knocked out those big mean football boys in
the television ratings.
   CBS and ABC vainly put up college football games against ``The
Miss America Pageant'' on NBC, but they ended up way downfield in
60th and 62nd places, respectively, while Miss America was No. 1.
   NBC estimates that between 50 million and 55 million viewers
watched all or part of the pageant on Saturday night, giving it a
rating of 22.3 and a 44 share, higher than last year's 20.4 and 42,
according to the A.C. Nielsen Co.
   The highest-rated Miss America Pageant was in 1986. It got a
23.0 rating and a 44 share.
   Each rating point represents 886,000 homes with televisions. The
share is a percentage of sets in use.
   After the pageant, last week's top prime-time shows were:
``Golden Girls'' NBC, ``Baby Boom'' NBC, ``The Cosby Show'' NBC,
``Monday Night Football _ Washington vs. New York Giants'' ABC, the
Bob Hope Special on NBC, ``Full House'' on ABC in its Tuesday time
period, ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC, ``Cheers'' NBC and ``227'' NBC.
   ``Baby Boom'' is a preview of a new show, based on the movie by
that name and starring Kate Jackson as an executive who inherits a
baby. It was slotted after ``Golden Girls'' and before Miss
America. NBC said the ``Baby Boom'' rating was the highest this
season for the network in that time period.
   For the week that ended Sunday, NBC won with an average
prime-time rating of 12.6 to ABC's 11.2 and CBS' 9.3.
   The evening news race was even tighter than usual, but it was an
unusual week because of the Jerry Lewis telethon and football. The
result was ``CBS Evening News'' and ABC's ``World News Tonight''
tying with a rating of 9.5. ``NBC Nightly News'' had a 9.4. Each of
the three got a 20 share. CBS' news was carried by 98 percent of
its stations, 97 percent for NBC and 96 percent for ABC because of
``Monday Night Football'' on the network.
   There might have been some effect from the New York CBS
affiliate's move of the ``CBS Evening News'' to 6:30, opposite
ABC's ``World News Tonight.'' ``NBC Nightly News'' is on its own in
New York at 7 p.m. New York represents about 7 percent of the total
television audience.
   Fox Broadcasting recorded the highest rating yet for its
prime-time series when ``America's Most Wanted'' got a 9.0 and
ranked 43rd among all network shows. Two other Fox shows, ``Married
... with Children'' and ``21 Jump Street'' also landed high enough
in the ratings to out-rank several network programs.
</TEXT>
