<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CandidateStabbed     09-14 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Candidate Stabbed,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>D.C. Council Candidate Stabbed On Election Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A candidate for the District of Columbia
Council was stabbed after allegedly attacking an employee of his
opponent and has been charged with simple assault, while his
assailant faces charges of assault with a deadly weapon, police
said.
   Jacques Chevalier, 33, a Ward 2 candidate in the district's
Democratic Party primary, was listed in fair condition today at
George Washington University Hospital with a stab wound to the
chest, said hospital spokeswoman Karen Johnson.
   Chevalier, who was challenging incumbent John Wilson for the
nomination, allegedly began kicking and punching 41-year-old Louise
Young outside a polling site on Tuesday afternoon, said D.C. police
spokesman Walt Ferguson.
   Harold Sims, 56, then interceded on Young's behalf, and
allegedly stabbed Chevalier, authorities said.
   Ms. Young, an aide in Wilson's office, refused medical
treatment. Police had not determined why Chevalier allegedly
attacked her.
   ``I'd love to know what those two were talking about,'' Ferguson
said.
   Chevalier, a local real estate agent and District native, was
making his first bid for public office, and got just 5 percent of
the vote.
   Wilson, chairman of the council's Finance Committee, received 94
percent of the vote. He is seeking a fourth term on the council.
</TEXT>
