<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     09-14 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials have come up with a way to
lure yuppies out of their Porsches and into buses: a luxury shuttle
that offers cushy seats, videos, wine and bagels.
   The 10-mile service from downtown to Century City is scheduled
to begin next month.
   City Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky, who dreamed up the deluxe bus,
hopes it will ease freeway jams by attracting lawyers and other
professionals wh would rather use the time spent traveling downtown
to catch up on business than on shifting gears.
   ``What lawyers sell is their time,'' said Susan G. Schaefer,
Century City Bar Association president. ``So if half an hour or an
hour of time can be spent working rather than dodging cars, than
that's time well spent.''
   For $7.50 each way, the 18-passenger shuttles will provide
cellular phones, televisions, video casette recorders and facsimile
machines, said Ralph W. Smith Jr., president of APT Transportation,
which won the contract for the route.
   Attendants will serve coffee and bagels in the morning and soft
drinks and wine in the afternoon.
   But you can't please everyone. One lawyer detected a potential
drawback.
   ``It definitely would be nice and less tense,'' said attorney
Joel M. Grossman. ``But my guess is that most lawyers, like me,
would be concerned about the down time waiting for the next bus.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SOUTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman and a scientist want
to put a three-armed robot in chains.
   The robot unveiled Tuesday at a University of Rhode Island
laboratory was billed as the perfect worker for the jewelry
industry. It is so dexterous it can handle delicate gold chain,
solder on parts and delicately twist the clasps on and off.
   ``A person right now who gets tired after an eight-hour shift
can do an average of one (chain) a minute,'' said Philip Datseris,
an associate professor of mechanical engineering.
   The robot can do two or three a minute, stacking them neatly on
a post as it finishes them, said Datseris, who helped develop the
machine.
   The robot will help U.S. jewelry manufacturers compete with
imports, said Albert F. Wiesner III, president of Wiesner
Manufacturing Co. of Providence, the chain maker that funded the
development work.
   ``I had this envisioned in my mind for a couple of years,'' said
Wiesner, who earned a degree in mechanical engineering at Rhode
Island. ``I had the mechanics down pretty well, but I needed help
with the electronics.''
   The university designed much of the electronics, two of the
robot's arms, and the computer program that runs the robot. The
robot's main arm came from Switzerland.
   It has cost about $100,000 so far to develop the machine,
Datseris said. At least six months more is needed before the robot
is ready for patent, said Wiesner.
</TEXT>
