<1ST_LINE>r i PM-CaymanIslands-Glance     09-14 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cayman Islands-Glance,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cayman Islands At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Facts and figures on the British-controlled Cayman Islands:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE GEOGRAPHY _ The three islands _ Grand Cayman, the largest,
Little Cayman and Cayman Brac _ cover 100 square miles. They are
located in the Caribbean Sea about 200 miles northwest of Jamaica.
   The islands' flat terrain is surrounded by clear waters and has
a tropical climate, with a hurricane season between July and
November.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE PEOPLE _ The population of nearly 23,000 is mostly
Protestant and Roman Catholic and is of mixed European and black
African descent. English is the country's official language.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ECONOMY _ The islands' big money-earners are financial
services and tourism. The economy also benefits from shipbuilding,
turtle and shark fishing, coconut farming, and textile and
automobile production. The 1987 per capita income was $9,000. In
1988, the islands could accomodate more than 5,000 tourists at a
time, and at least 480,792 people visited the island in 1987.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ The Cayman Islands were discovered by Christopher
Columbus in 1503 and came under British control in 1670. They
became a colony in 1959 and were administered by Jamaica until a
governor was appointed in 1972. The legislature includes the
governor, three officials and 12 elected members.
</TEXT>
