<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SierraFire 3rdLd-Writethru   09-14 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sierra Fire, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0402,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flames Destroy 46 Square Miles of Timber, 97 Homes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with residents returning to homes, highways reopened,
favorable weather aiding firefighters, detail throughout; no
pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SC2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE WILDWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of residents returned
home Tuesday as state fire officials, helped by nearly 24 hours of
favorable weather, lifted evacuation notices and reopened major
highways where a raging timber fire destroyed almost 100 homes.
   ``As far as I know, we have allowed everyone who wants to return
home to do so,'' state Department of Forestry spokesman Steve
Iverson said.
   At least 97 homes and 60 other buildings were destroyed, and
4,000 to 5,000 other structures had been threatened by the
fast-moving, wind-fanned blaze northeast of Sacramento in the
foothills of the Sierra Nevada.
   In less than 72 hours it blackened more than 52 square miles of
brush and timber north and west of Grass Valley and Nevada City in
a half-moon arc 12 miles long and two to five miles wide.
   The fire had been whipped by gusts of 30 mph and above since
Sunday, but on Tuesday, winds were moderate, temperatures were
about 10 degrees lower and the humidity level nearly double,
Iverson said.
   ``If it holds through the night, we'll consider releasing some
people tomorrow,'' said Iverson, planning chief for the
2,788-member firefighting force. ``We're looking forward to another
inversion layer Wednesday. The temperatures should be moderate.''
   An estimated 8,000 people had been evacuated from their homes in
several communities.
   Iverson said no additional homes were threatened as of Tuesday
evening. But homes inside the fire lines could be threatened if
winds shift or pick up significantly, he added.
   By nightfall Tuesday, firefighters had bulldozed lines around
more than 35 percent of the 90-mile perimeter of the blaze. The
area where it spread thickest on Tuesday _ grasslands in the
deserted eastern sector of Beale Air Force Base _ also burned out
the quickest.
   The fire was stopped more than four miles from the edge of the
main part of the base, home for some of the nation's most
sophisticated spy planes, firefighters said.
   ``It's all out. It's history. There are no problems there,''
said Bill Holmes, a Department of Forestry operations chief.
   Federal fire officials have called this the worst forest fire
season in the West in 30 years, especially considering the fires in
and around Yellowstone National Park. The fires have charred
939,270 acres of the 2.2 million-acre park since June.
   Firefighters there on Tuesday took advantage of a cold spell to
make some headway against the blazes before potentially menacing
warmer weather sets in.
   At one point Tuesday in California, a wall of flames up to 50
feet high surrounded three sides of the forested Grass Valley Group
industrial complex, where sophisticated television graphics are
produced for networks and major stations worldwide.
   About 100 people living nearby were temporarily evacuated but
were allowed to return to their homes before nightfall. The complex
was unharmed.
   That complex, which employs 1,000 people, has been cited as one
of the leading examples of communications and other high technology
industries which have located in rural areas.
   Iverson said California's drought conditions, which accentuated
the volume of highly combustible forest materials, plus unusually
high wind and low humidity, had combined to create an especially
dangerous and unpredictable condition.
   Only seven firefighters were treated at hospitals for minor
burns. No residents were reported injured.
   The blaze, dubbed the ``49er Fire'' because it began along
winding Highway 49, apparently was started by a transient igniting
toilet paper.
   Firefighters also battled several other fires in northern
California, including a 9,000-acre blaze near Healdsburg, about 65
miles north of San Francisco, which destroyed three homes, several
outbuildings and briefly threatened a Pacific Gas & Electric Co.
geothermal generating plant. It was 75 percent contained.
</TEXT>
