<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0697 09-14 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Tells Executives Dukakis Would Take Their Money</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 6th graf pvs, `Later, Bush,' with 2 new grafs of the
vice president's comments to Los Angeles fund-raiser.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush mocked Michael Dukakis as the
governor of ``Taxachusetts' on Tuesday and told business executives
his Democratic rival would pay for federal programs by reaching
``right for the wallet'' and taking their money.
   In a separate appearance in Missouri farm country, Bush also
suggested that Dukakis might oppose selling U.S.-subsidized wheat
to the Soviet Union.
   ``We will never go back to the grain-embargo days of those
Democrats, Carter and Mondale and who knows who else,'' the
Republican presidential nominee declared. Dukakis' campaign has
said that improved trade with the Soviets should be linked with
progress on human rights.
   Bush delivered a breakfast address on economics to the
Executives Club in Chicago and then flew to Jefferson City, Mo.,
for a rally on the state Capitol steps.
   On a hot sunny day, a noontime crowd of thousands of people gave
Bush an enthusiastic welcome. Dukakis also had his supporters _ his
name was spelled out in large red letters across seven windows on
the Capitol's top floor.
   Later, Bush flew to Los Angeles where he attended a $1,000 a
person fund-raiser whose audience included Hollywood celebrities
Bob Hope, Dina Merrill and Arnold Schwarzenegger.
   ``On the issue of peace, my opponent's views are simply beyond
the pale,'' Bush said. ``He does not, I believe, see America as the
leader of the West and it has not, I believe, occurred to him that
if America doesn't lead the free countries of the world, the free
countries of the world will not have a leader.''
   Taken together, Illinois, Missouri and California command 82 of
the 270 electoral votes needed to win the White House.
   In Chicago, Bush told the businessmen, ``The surest way to kill
the recovery is to raise taxes. That will stifle everything from
investment and personal savings to consumer spending. It will clamp
down on growth.
   ``It will invite a recession,'' he said.
   Bush promised anew that he would not raise taxes, that he would
fight trade protectionism and that he would attack the budget
deficit with a ``flexible freeze'' on government spending.
   He did not spell out which programs would be cut and which would
get more money, except to say that Social Security and interest
payments would be exempt from the freeze.
   Bush attacked Dukakis' plan for a federally funded, regional
job-creation and economic development program, which the
Massachusetts governor calls a fund to rebuild America.
   ``All you need to do is to make a small down payment, $500
million, to get those industrial planning technocrats to work in
Washington,'' Bush said. ``My opponent calls this kind of
government `the helping hand.'
   ``Well, where is the helping hand reaching? Right for the
wallet,'' Bush said, slapping his hand on his back pocket.
   ``What will pay for that helping hand? Your money. And who is
being helped? Not you. It's government in Washington picking the
winners and losers.''
   He asked, ``What kind of lasting jobs are going to be produced
by this partnership? Only the kind that endure on the public
payroll.''
   Bush referred to Dukakis' state as ``Taxachusetts,'' prompting
mild laughter in the audience.
   He reiterated his proposal to cut the capital gains tax to 15
percent from the current level of 28 percent. ``I'm being attacked,
saying this is a tax cut favoring the rich,'' Bush said.
   ``Not so. I believe we should cut the capital gains tax again,
not to help the rich as my opponent speciously claims, but to
create more jobs for everybody in this country,'' Bush said.
   The audience applauded loudly.
   Crediting the Reagan-Bush administration with cutting inflation
and interest rates and producing nearly 18 million new jobs, the
vice president said, ``Americans can feel and touch and bank upon
the prosperity brought by the longest running peacetime economic
expansion in our history.''
   Bush also emphasized economic issues in Jefferson City, saying
the average American family is paying $2,200 less in federal income
taxes ``than it would have under the Carter-Mondale-Dukakis rate.
We are going to keep those tax rates down.''
   The vice president listed differences with Dukakis on abortion,
gun control, school prayer and other issues.
   ``I don't believe that we want to turn far to the left in this
country,'' Bush said. ``Let's keep it going the way we've been
going, in the right direction, without going back and turning
things around.''
</TEXT>
