<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0448,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Dukakis Might Revive Grain Embargoes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th graf, `In Los Angeles,' with Bush's
comment at fund-raiser. First event noon EDT; top prospects
uncertain.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush is raising the specter
of a Democratic-imposed grain embargo as he seeks to emphasize an
economic policy chasm between himself and presidential opponent
Michael Dukakis.
   In a pair of campaign stops Tuesday in Missouri, Bush told
supporters he wants to expand American markets abroad, saying,
``American farmers and ranchers can compete with anyone anywhere in
the world if the rules are fair.''
   The Democrats, he contended, are interested only in production
controls and want to ``control the lives of the farmers.''
   Harking back to the grain embargo imposed by President Jimmy
Carter on U.S. exports to the Soviet Union, Bush said, ``I will not
use food as a foreign policy weapon.''
   He cited a July 27 article in the Journal of Commerce that said
a Dukakis aide suggested the Massachusetts governor might
re-examine the U.S. policy of selling government subsidized wheat
to the Soviets.
   ``Can you imagine another president who would leave open the
door of using agriculture products to make political points and
using our producers in that way,'' he said. ``I will not go back to
this grain embargo. Listen, farmers are still trying to recover
from that.''
   Today Bush was courting the ethnic vote in California _ with
Hispanic events in Los Angeles and Fresno and a tour of San
Francisco's Chinatown _ following his day of barnstorming in
Illinois and Missouri.
   In Los Angeles on Tuesday night, Bush was feted at a gala
fund-raiser for the Republican Party's ``Victory '88'' fund, hosted
by California Gov. George Deukmejian.
   ``On the issue of peace, my opponent's views are simply beyond
the pale,'' Bush told the audience. ``He does not, I believe, see
America as the leader of the West and it has not, I believe,
occurred to him that if America doesn't lead the free countries of
the world, the free countries of the world will not have a leader.''
   The $1,000 a person event drew a host of Hollywood celebrities,
including Bob Hope, Dina Merrill and Arnold Schwarzeneggar.
   Bush has been clearly annoyed at allegations that forced the
resignation of seven members of an ethnic coalition and of his
choice to run the campaign activities of the Republican Party. Bush
said Tuesday he neither asked the eight to stay nor encouraged
their departure.
   In a brief conversation with reporters aboard Air Force Two,
Bush refused to say whether he would offer a spot to one of them,
Frederic Malek, in a Bush administration.
   ``I have a lot of confidence in Fred Malek, I don't think he has
one bigoted bone in his body,'' was all he would say when asked
about Malek's future should Bush win the election.
   Bush had named Malek to a top position at the Republican
National Committee, but Malek stepped down when it was revealed
that he had carried out orders from then-President Richard Nixon to
compile a list of Jews among the top officials of the Bureau of
Labor Statistics.
   As to the reports of alleged anti-Semitic and fascist ties by
members of his American Nationalities Coalition, he said:
   ``I don't like the allegations about people and I don't like it
being injected into the campaign.''
   Asked why he did not urge them to stay in light of that
viewpoint, he told the reporters: ``Because then you'd be talking
about this all the time, all the time for the next two months,
obscuring these other questions we're talking about _ defense,
economic policy _ that's why.''
   Bush made the comments before his plane lifted off for Los
Angeles from the Missouri trip.
   At a colorful rally at the Jefferson City state capitol, Bush
promised to give farmers expanded foreign markets.
   ``Agricultural America can compete any place in the world so
long as we give them access to other people's markets,'' he said.
   He painted a rosy economic picture under the Reagan years,
promised to ``strengthen and broaden our economic growth,'' and
said ``the family right in the middle is earning $4,000 more a year
than he would have under those tired Democratic policies.''
   Bush on Tuesday also announced a team of agricultural campaign
advisers, including Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., Agriculture Secretary
Richard Lyng, U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter, and former
American Farm Bureau President Robert Delano.
</TEXT>
