<1ST_LINE>u p AM-WisconsinPrimary 8thLd-Writethru a0467 09-14 0929</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wisconsin Primary, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0467,0949</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engleleiter, Kohl Win Party Contests For Proxmire Seat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8, `With 2,720 ..., and 14th graf, `With 226 .
.., to UPDATE with 93 percent vote totals in Senate races, 100
percent in GOP House race; this version is likely to stand for AMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR L. SRB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican state Sen. Susan Engeleiter beat
former party chairman Stephen B. King in a GOP primary Tuesday for
a chance to succeed retiring Sen. William Proxmire, and Milwaukee
Bucks owner Herbert Kohl won his first bid for public office,
defeating former Gov. Anthony S. Earl in a four-way Democratic
Senate primary.
   ``I am very honored to be chosen as the Republican nominee for
the United States Senate,'' Engeleiter said after becoming the only
woman nominated to the U.S. Senate by a major party in 1988.
   ``I believe there are major differences between me and Herb
Kohl,'' she said. ``I am an average member of an average Wisconsin
family. I understand the concerns of the people out there.''
   Kohl, the millionaire owner of the National Basketball
Association franchise, easily defeated Earl, who lost a bid for
re-election in 1986, as well as former Deputy Attorney General
Edward R. Garvey and Secretary of State Douglas La Follette.
   Kohl said voters wanted ``a qualified non-politician with real
business-world experience and they said they want a senator who'll
be independent of special interests.''
   Earl, who criticized Kohl's extensive use of television ads
during the campaign, said, ``I don't think Herb Kohl would mind if
I say he got the most votes but I got the best votes.''
   With 3,195 of 3,450 precincts, or 93 percent, reporting, Kohl
had 244,085 votes, or 47 percent; Earl had 199,112 or 38 percent;
Garvey had 54,475, or 10 percent; La Follette had 20,221, or 4
percent; and tire dealer Edmond Hou-Seye had 5,139, or 1 percent.
   In Republican voting, with 3,195 of 3,450 precincts, or 93
percent reporting, Engeleiter had 192,485 votes, or 57 percent;
King had 136,110, or 40 percent; and Peter Taylor, who withdrew
from the race, had 8,638, or 3 percent.
   ``It was a family spat,'' King said in calling upon supporters
to back Engeleiter in November. ``We're only going to elect one
U.S. senator from Wisconsin this fall and that senator has to be
Susan Engeleiter,'' he said.
   Democratic Rep. Jim Moody won the nomination for a fourth term
from the 5th District. Moody announced earlier this year he was
vacating the seat to run for the Senate, but dropped out of the
Senate race and re-entered the House race in June when Kohl
announced his candidacy.
   With 226 of 262 precincts, or 86 percent, reporting, Moody had
40,633 votes, or 58 percent; Matt Flynn, former state Democratic
chairman, had 16,805 votes, or 24 percent; Donald Sykes, former
director of an anti-poverty agency in Milwaukee, had 4,664 votes,
or 7 percent; former state lawmaker and perennial candidate Roman
Blenski had 440 votes, or 1 percent.
   Two candidates dropped out of the race when Moody re-entered,
but remained on the ballot. Milwaukee County supervisor Terrance
Pitts had 4,664 votes, or 7 percent, and former county circuit
Judge Frederick Kessler had 2,127 votes, or 3 percent.
   The district has been a stronghold for the Democrats, but
Republicans have tried to mount a legitimate threat.
   With all 262 precincts reporting, Helen Barnhill, a black
businesswoman, won the GOP nomination with 13,513 votes, or 68
percent; environmental activist Janette Marsh had 6,341 votes, or
32 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The scramble for Democratic nomination for the seat held for 31
years by Proxmire, 72, was triggered by his surprise announcement
last year that he would not seek re-election.
   ``I'd be 79 before the end of my next term,'' Proxmire explained
to disappointed Democrats.
   Ironically, campaign spending became a major issue among
Democratic contenders for the right to succeed Proxmire, a
gregarious hand-shaker whose low-budget re-election campaigns and
congressional budget-cutting efforts in won widespread popularity.
   Kohl, 53, a former chain store owner who was making his first
bid for public office, outspent his three opponents combined _ more
than $2 million to approximately $431,000 by Earl, $360,000 by
Garvey and $15,500 by La Follette, as of Aug. 24, Election Board
records showed.
   ``Politics should be people, ideas and leadership, not
multi-million-dollar TV hype,'' said La Follette, who said his
low-budget campaigns more closely resembled those by the
indefatigible Proxmire.
   When he easily won re-election six years ago, Proxmire spent
$145.10, he said, some of it for postage to return contributions.
   Like the 52-year-old Earl, Garvey, 48, sought to bounce back
from a 1986 defeat. Although an underdog, Garvey former executive
director of the National Footbal League Players Association, came
close to upsetting Republican Sen. Robert W. Kasten two years ago.
   La Follette, 48, a three-term secretary of state and former
state senator from Kenosha, lost a 1978 bid for lieutenant governor.
   In the GOP race, King, 47, a former FBI agent and one-time
chairman of the Republican Party of Wisconsin, sought to pin a
liberal tag on Engeleiter, 36, a veteran of 11 years the
Legislature and the Senate's minority leader.
   King once served as an aide to then-U.S. Attorney General John
Mitchell before the Watergate scandal unfolded in the Nixon
administration. He stressed his opposition to a tax increase and
abortion and his support for the death penalty.
   Engleiter, who said she had the backing of a far broader segment
of the party, stressed she had spent much of her legislative career
fighting against increased taxes.
</TEXT>
