<2ND_LINE>AM-Minnesota Primary, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0401,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Durenberger, Humphrey Win Senate Nominations in Minnesota</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 3-4 to UPDATE with later results. May stand for
AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sen. Dave Durenberger and
Democratic-Farmer-Labor challenger Hubert H. Humphrey III won
nomination handily in primaries Tuesday.
   Durenberger, 54, who was first elected in 1978, was opposed by
John J. Zeleniak, 78, of Columbia Heights, a retired physicist, and
Sharon Anderson, 49, of St. Paul, who has run unsuccessfully for
several offices.
   With 94 percent of the 4,086 precincts reporting, Durenberger
had 100,771 votes or 93 percent, to Anderson's 5,000 votes, or 5
percent, and Zeleniak's 2,178 votes, or 2 percent.
   Humphrey, 46, the state attorney general who is the son of the
former vice president and U.S. senator, had 144,250 votes, or 91
percent, against Kent S. Herschbach, 41, of Mendota Heights. The
truck driver and supporter of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche
received 14,609 votes, or 9 percent.
   Humphrey's campaign manager, Joe Tessmer, said the primary
results ``show voter confidence in the Humphrey candidacy.''
   ``There are two polls that count, the first on primary day and
the second on Election Day,'' he said. ``We're happy, that in the
first one that counts, we won and we won handily.''
   Durenberger was in Washington, D.C., where Congress was in
session, and voted by absentee ballot.
   ``The primary vote is an important step in the process,''
Durenberger said in a statement released by his campaign office.
``But I won't get into full-time campaigning until sometime in
October (after Congress adjourns). I always appreciate the people
who get out to vote in the primary, even though it's not as
exciting as the general election.''
   Leon Oistad, Durenberger's campaign manager, said he had seen no
campaign activity by either of the Republican challengers.
   Both Durenberger and Humphrey launched television advertising
campaigns earlier this month, with Durenberger stressing his
foreign policy experience and Humphrey emphasizing his concern for
family and children.
   Humphrey, Minnesota's attorney general since 1983, has trailed
Durenberger in public opinion polls by up to 19 percentage points,
although no independent poll results have been available since May.
Durenberger also has led Humphrey by a 2-1 margin in fund-raising
and his campaign expects to spend about $6.5 million to Humphrey's
$3.5 million to $4 million.
</TEXT>
