<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle     09-14 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nearly A Month After Nomination, Quayle Getting Defense Message
Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle is not exactly a
stand-up comic, but with some punchy one-liners the Republican vice
presidential nominee is getting his licks in against Michael
Dukakis' positions on defense.
   Until recently, Quayle's message was obscured by questions about
his own military posture and it was no laughing matter for his
campaign. But aides were delighted Tuesday at the attention Quayle
got when he delivered some wicked lines that ridiculed the
Democratic presidential nominee and provoked the Dukakis camp into
saying that the young Indiana senator was merely acting his age.
   Nearly a month ago, with his vice presidential campaign only
hours old, Quayle was mired in questions about whether his hawkish
image jibed with another image of him as a draft dodger.
   On Tuesday, Quayle was the GOP ticket's attack man, portraying
Dukakis as weak on defense and inexperienced in foreign policy
matters.
   ``Want to hear a sad story about the Dukakis campaign?'' Quayle
told supporters in a Milwaukee suburb.
   ``The governor of Massachusetts, he lost his top naval adviser
last week. His rubber duck drowned in his bathtub,'' Quayle said,
as the audience roared.
   Later, in Bismarck, N.D., Quayle joked that the Massachusetts
governor's experience in foreign policy was limited to dealing with
the governor of neighboring New Hampshire.
   The jokes got newspaper ink and even some time on the network
news. Quayle's campaign was pleased.
   ``People are now seeing an articulate, humorous individual who
has used his time in the Senate and the House to be an expert on
defense, foreign policy and national security issues,'' said David
Prosperi, Quayle's spokesman.
   Campaign strategists have long touted Quayle's defense expertise
as one of his assets. He has been a member of the Senate Armed
Services Committee for eight years and has been deeply involved in
NATO issues, among others.
   But getting that message out has been difficult.
   A speech last week in Chicago, for example, was supposed to be a
major display of Quayle's ``stuff,'' as Prosperi put it.
   But Quayle tossed out the text, preferring to speak from
notecards and ended up making a confusing statement about offensive
and defensive weapons and evoking novelist Tom Clancy on
anti-satellite testing.
   Quayle's opposition to legislation to make the Veterans
Administration a Cabinet-level department also became a distracting
issue. Some saw the vote as anti-veteran.
   That, together with allegations he pulled strings to get into
the National Guard during the Vietnam War dogged Quayle almost from
the moment he left New Orleans as George Bush's running mate.
   A hawkish conservative in Congress, Quayle denied using his
wealthy family's influence 20 years ago to avoid combat, and
indignantly defended as honorable and patriotic his Guard service.
   Throughout the first weeks of his campaign, Quayle found himself
repeating, ``No rules were broken'' to reporters who questioned him
at almost every stop.
   That has not happened for some time, although Quayle also has
not held a news conference since Sept. 1.
   Aides say they believe he may have succeeded in finally getting
the debate focused on the issues, not his past.
   ``It's a continuation of our strategy that now is starting to
get a lot more attention because all the diversions basically have
blown away,'' Prosperi said.
   The strategy is to portray Dukakis as ``dangerously naive'' on
defense matters, blasting his opposition to the MX and Midgetman
weapons.
   Quayle on Tuesday described the Democratic nominee as ``the most
anti-defense candidate on a national level since George McGovern.''
   He said it was ``shocking'' that Dukakis had found it necessary
to receive defense briefings over the weekend from members of
Congress.
   ``You don't learn what you need to know about the national
security of our nation in one weekend cram course,'' Quayle said.
   He was cheered by the heartily supportive audiences on this
Midwestern swing. The only discordant note came from a group of
disgruntled veterans at a rally in Grand Junction, Colo. For them,
at least, the veterans were still an issue.
   ``What about veterans benefits?'' one asked as Quayle made his
way shaking hands.
   Replied Quayle, ``I'm for them.''
</TEXT>
