<DOCNO> AP880914-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0202EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Kurds     09-14 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Kurds,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Asks Iraq To Allow Check Of Chemical Warfare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar requested that Iraq allow a team of specialists to
investigate claims by the United States and others that Baghdad
used poison gas to crush a Kurdish rebellion.
   Also Tuesday, Secretary of State George Shultz said Iraq is
using such chemical weapons against the Kurds. He said the U.S.
conclusions were based on a U.S. examination of Kurdish refugees
inside Turkey and on ``other evidence which to me seems to be
compelling.''
   ``I feel our evidence is quite convincing,'' he said. ``But
we're not in a position to make that public.''
   Perez de Cuellar conveyed the request of 10 governments for a
U.N. investigation to Iraq's charge d'affaires, Ali Mahmoud
Sumaida, on Tuesday, said U.N. spokeswoman Nadia Younes.
   The nations making the request are the United States, Japan,
Britain, Italy, West Germany, Norway, Sweden, Denmark, Finland and
Iceland, she said.
   Iraq has denied it used gas against the minority Kurds but has
previously acknowledged using chemical weapons against Iran in
their nearly 8-year-old war that led to a cease-fire last month.
   The 1925 Geneva Protocol bans use of chemical or biological
weapons, although their manufacture and stockpiling is allowed as a
deterrent against attack.
   Also Tuesday, a high-ranking Iraqi official acknowledged his
government is moving many Kurds from small villages for security
reasons or to provide better services, but he said it is not trying
to wipe them out or change their way of life.
   Kurdish rebel groups and others have denounced Iraq's policy of
demolishing small villages and relocating their population.
   But the official, Nizar Hamdoon, deputy foreign secretary and
former Iraqi ambassador to the United States, said in an interview
that the government has no intention ``to change the life of the
Kurds.''
   Asked about reports of widespread relocations, he said: ``If
you're talking about the border area, the reasons are mainly
security reasons, so that (rebel) infiltration stops.
   Iraq grants its 2.5 million to 3 million Kurdish inhabitants,
who live mainly in the north, a form of regional autonomy,
including their own assembly and use of the Kurdish language.
   Rebel groups demand wider autonomy or creation of an independent
state. An additional 6 million Kurds live in Turkey, Iran, the
Soviet Union and Syria.
   About 60,000 Kurds, many suffering chemical injuries, recently
fled Iraq to Turkey and said they did so because of chemical
attacks. The Kurds claim Iraq used the chemical weapons as part of
an offensive against the Kurds.
   An investigating team would need Iraq's permission to enter the
country, and failure to cooperate could hurt its international
standing.
   In London, the British Foreign Office said it toughened its
stand Monday partly because of the U.S. State Department evidence
of Iraqi chemical attacks on the Kurds.
   The evidence led the U.S. Senate on Friday to vote for tough
economic sanctions against Iraq. The Senate also suggested the
Iraqi relocation of Kurdish population was connected with
``genocide'' against the Kurdish people.
   The measure still must be approved by the House and signed by
President Reagan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880914-0048 </DOCNO>
