<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NewHampshirePrimary 6thLd-Writethru a0428 09-14 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Hampshire Primary, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0428,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gregg Wins New Hampshire GOP Primary for Governor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with later results. May stand
for AMs. Matter below dash will stand</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMA LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Judd Gregg defeated two rivals in the
Republican gubernatorial primary Tuesday for the right to face
unopposed Democratic candidate Paul McEachern in the race to
succeed outgoing Gov. John Sununu.
   ``This is the first act of a two-act American drama,'' Gregg
said as he declared victory just after 9 p.m. Gregg immediately
launched an offensive against McEachern, whom he painted as a
free-spending liberal.
   ``We will show the people of New Hampshire what deep
philosophical differences there are ... a choice between fiscal
restraint and liberal spending,'' Gregg said.
   Gregg, a four-term congressman, easily outdistanced former
Manchester Mayor Robert Shaw and political neophyte William
Lawrence, a quality-control engineer from Hollis.
   With 266 of 298 precincts reporting, Gregg had 60,234 votes, or
79 percent, to 13,737 votes for Shaw, or 18 percent, and 2,330
votes for Lawrence, or 3 percent.
   Chuck Douglas, a former state Supreme Court justice, won a
bitter contest with former state Rep. Betty Tamposi in a six-way
GOP contest to succeed Gregg in the 2nd District.
   With 151 of 178 precincts reporting in that district, Douglas
led with 47 percent to Tamposi's 41 percent. The remainder was
split among Gregg's cousin, Stephen Gregg of Holderness; state Rep.
Alf Jacobson of New London; Peterborough magazine editor Dennis
Allen; and Milford restaurateur Andrew Tempelman.
   Nashua Mayor James Donchess defeated former state Rep. Barbara
Underwood for the Democratic 2nd District nomination by a 66
percent to 26 percent margin, with Lewis du Pont Smith trailing
with 8 percent.
   City clerks described turnout as dismally low. They blamed rain
and a lack of exciting contests.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Gregg, son of a former governor, entered the gubernatorial race
when Sununu, a national co-chairman of George Bush's presidential
campaign, decided not to seek a record fourth two-year term.
   McEachern, a lawyer, campaigned as a staunch opponent of the
troubled Seabrook nuclear power plant. In 1986, he ran a fairly
close race against Sununu.
   Douglas accused Tamposi, daughter of a millionaire real estate
developer, of using her wealth to try to buy the election. Tamposi,
initially said she would not bankroll her campaign, but ended up
lending it $150,000.
   Though he stopped short of formally endorsing Tamposi, Sununu
sent thousands of letters and made television spots for her.
Douglas won endorsements from nationally known conservatives
including Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, Rep. Jack Kemp of New York and
Sen. Gordon Humphrey of New Hampshire.
   Humphrey created an uproar last week when he said Tamposi
shouldn't run for Congress because she has a 22-month-old daughter
to take care of. Humphrey apologized two days later.
</TEXT>
