<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-IraqTalks     09-14 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq Talks,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Talks Shift to New York, Iraq Balks at Date</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq agreed to recess their stalled peace
talks and resume them in New York, according to a U.N. mediator,
but Baghdad balked at a proposed meeting date this month.
   A U.N. mediator said he hoped to come up with a meeting date
today.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar proposed the
temporary move to New York in the hope of unblocking the
U.N.-mediated negotiations which opened in Geneva almost three
weeks ago.
   The agreement to pick up talks ``shortly'' in New York was
announced Tuesday by U.N. mediator Jan Eliasson, appointed by Perez
de Cuellar last week to oversee the talks in his absence.
   The U.N. chief invited the foreign ministers of the two nations
to meet at U.N. headquarters in New York on Sept. 22, but the Iraqi
delegation announced that Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz could not be
in New York before the first week of October.
   The Iraqis also said they agreed to attend one meeting in New
York only if, before leaving Geneva, a firm date was fixed for
returning.
   The Iraqis' hardline stance was spelled out in a press statement
Tuesday night.
   Eliasson sought to play down the problem, calling the question
of dates a ``technical, secondary issue.'' He told journalists it
could be solved in a ``smooth, undramatic manner'' and indicated he
hoped this could be done by today.
   ``The main thing is the acceptance (by both sides) of a meeting
in New York shortly ... and of the subsequent continuation of the
talks in Geneva,'' he said.
   He told a news conference earlier that both sides ``seem
committed to keep the peace process going.'' He said they also
pledged to continue to observe the cease-fire, which went into
effect Aug. 20 after eight years of fighting and an estimated 1
million dead.
   The Swedish diplomat acknowledged, however, that on ``issues of
substance, there has been little, if any, progress.''
   But he said the essential thing was that the ``peace process is
kept alive.''
   The talks have bogged down over differing priorities. Iran wants
the negotiations to stick to the U.N. cease-fire resolution,
starting with withdrawal of all troops to internationally
recognized borders.
   Iran holds that these borders were delineated in a 1975 treaty
between the two countries. Iraq renounced the accord in 1980
shortly before invading Iran, but Iran says the unilateral
repudiation violates international law.
   Iraq wants the talks to focus immediately on clearing the
Shatt-al-Arab waterway of silt and sunken wreckage. The waterway
provides Iraq with its main outlet to the sea.
   Iraq also wants immediately to discuss freedom of navigation in
the Persian Gulf.
   Iran says these are secondary issues that could be dealt with
after the cease-fire resolution is put into full effect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880914-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0358EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VodkaKilling     09-14 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vodka Killing,0711</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dead Drifter Haunted by His Role In My Lai Massacre</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 7th graf, `On the ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drifter found dead 1{ weeks ago following an
argument with his girlfriend over a bottle of vodka was haunted by
his role in the My Lai massacre during the Vietnam War, relatives
say.
   ``He actually was a casualty of the war,'' said Rebecca
T'Souvas, estranged wife of Robert W. T'Souvas. ``He had such
problems from what was wrong in Vietnam. Nothing was ever right for
him.''
   ``He was just a weak person,'' she said. ``I'm sure it was
because of Vietnam and because of what he had to endure there. But
he was a gentle man and a very good person when he was not under
the influence.''
   Robert T'Souvas, 39, was shot to death Sept. 3 beneath the
Smithfield Street Bridge in downtown Pittsburgh.
   His girlfriend, Kathlynn T'Souvas, 36, who took his last name
even though he never divorced Rebecca T'Souvas, has been charged
with criminal homicide and is being held without bail at the
Allegheny County Jail. A coroner's inquest is scheduled for
Thursday.
   Army Spec. 4 T'Souvas, then 19 and a high school dropout in San
Jose, was a member of one of three platoons that entered the
village of My Lai on March 16, 1968, where, he told an Army hearing
in 1970, he saw about 30 bodies, ``old men, women and children.''
   ``On the way out, T'Souvas saw two small children lying in the
road with their intestines hanging out,'' said his attorney, George
T. Davis of Mauna Lani, Hawaii. ``In an emotional reaction, he took
his M-16 and killed both to put them out of their misery.''
   The Army charged T'Souvas with premeditated murder of two
unidentified Vietnamese with a machine gun. He was one of nine
enlisted men charged in the massacre, in which more than 100
civilians were killed.
   After two soldiers were acquitted at courts-martial, charges
against T'Souvas and the six others were dropped. All were given
honorable discharges.
   Army Lt. William Calley was convicted of killing at least 22
civilians at My Lai. President Richard Nixon reduced Calley's life
prison sentence to 20 years. Calley served three years under house
arrest at Fort Benning, Ga. He was released when his conviction was
overturned by a federal district judge, and he was not returned to
house arrest when an appeals court reinstated the conviction.
   While awaiting trial at Fort McPherson, Ga., T'Souvas lived in
an Atlanta hippie commune, where he met his wife, according to
family members. Both later spent time in jail on marijuana charges
before they moved to California, the relatives said.
   They raised two children and T'Souvas worked in a bakery and at
various jobs before their marriage broke up, Lynn T'Souvas, an
aunt, said.
   About four years ago, he met Kathlynn, a carnival worker.
   ``She liked alcohol and was his drinking companion,'' said his
father, William T'Souvas, of San Jose, Calif.
   Police said the couple's trailer burned down and they left
California in August 1987 for Pittsburgh, where T'Souvas hoped for
a construction job.
   Police said Kathlynn's diary showed they lived in the van, often
parking it near Three Rivers Stadium, as they fished in the rivers,
sold their blood for money and worked part-time in a food kitchen
for the unemployed and the homeless.
   After the van broke down this summer, they built a makeshift
shelter on the banks of the Monongahela River, police said.
   On Sept. 3, police said, the T'Souvases and another homeless
man, David Bozic, 42, spent the day drinking, fishing and using
Bozic's .22-caliber pistol to shoot rats and cans under the bridge.
   While Bozic went to get food, police said the couple argued over
a bottle of vodka T'Souvas held between his legs. Police said the
woman took Bozic's gun and shot T'Souvas once in the head.
   William T'Souvas said he last talked to his son a few days
before the shooting.
   ``I just tried to tell him to put it together and come home,''
he said. ``I sent him some money, but he never came.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880914-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-14 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against the Japanese yen, while
share prices inched up on the Tokyo Stock Exchange Wednesday.
   The dollar closed at 133.45 yen, up 0.38 yen from Tuesday's
close of 133.07 yen. After opening the day's session at 133.47 yen,
the currency was traded in a range between 133.33 yen and 133.65
yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 37.42-point
winner Tuesday, gained 11.51 points or 0.04 percent to close
trading at 27,805.67. The main index gained 99.78 points to move to
27,893.94 shortly after the start of morning trading began, but
then went into a decline to finish slightly above the previous
day's close.
   Exchange dealers attributed the dollar's rise to dollar-buying
by investors who expect the U.S. trade deficit to decrease. They
added the overall market mood was cautious.
   The U.S. Commerce Department was scheduled to announce the July
trade figure later Wednesday in Washington.
   Share prices rose in the wake of a slight overnight gain on Wall
Street.
   ``But the Tokyo trading is quite active, as investors started
buying steel issues that let the (Nikkei) index to rise,'' said an
analyst at Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage firm.
   ``Active trading, despite a wait-and-see mood among investors,
showed the market's strength,'' he said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</TEXT>
