<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ArizonaPrimary 4thLd-Writethru a0510 09-14 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arizona Primary, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0510,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arizona Lawmakers Leading Pro-Mecham Forces</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with House speaker race still
tight; SUBS 14th graf, `In District 1 ..., to UPDATE with Fillmore
nominated; likely to stand for AMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Joe Lane was in a tight battle with
two backers of former Gov. Evan Mecham in early returns Tuesday
from a primary election that the ousted governor vowed would be a
``revolutionary step at the ballot box.''
   Lane, Lloyd Fenn and Warren Shumaker were virtually deadlocked
with 26 of 58 precincts reporting. A fourth candidate, Gerald
Patton, trailed with 14 percent.
   ``If I lose tonight it's Mecham that did it,'' Lane said
Tuesday. ``But I don't think it'll happen. I think I'll win all
right; it might not be an easy one.''
   Mecham, who predicted Monday that Lane would lose either the
primary or general election, said Tuesday night, ``I think we'll be
in for some surprises probably before the night is over. When it's
over there will be quite a number of changes; nobody will get
everything they want.''
   In other returns, Senate President Carl Kunasek was running
ahead of Jerry Gillespie, an ultra-conservative Mecham backer. But
some other senators who voted to oust Mecham were running behind.
   ``I think this is going to be the demise of the Mecham gang
myself,'' Lane, who represents a district in southeastern Arizona,
had predicted Monday. ``But I wouldn't bet any money on it because
I've been surprised once before by the Mecham folks.''
   Kunasek said Monday he was optimistic but added, ``At times I
get very depressed. I'm just resigned to whatever fate they (the
voters) produce.''
   The Mecham supporters were banking on voter dissatisfaction over
the former governor's April 4 Senate impeachment conviction and an
election-year tax hike approved by the GOP-dominated Legislature to
meet a massive budget deficit.
   Mecham predicted Friday that Lane would be defeated and said,
``I think we'll see a bigger change than we've ever seen before
.... I think that is a revolutionary step at the ballot box.''
   One pro-Mecham candidate was his former press secretary, Ron
Bellus, who ran against former Senate President Leo Corbet in
north-central Phoenix. Bellus said he did not know what a
``Mechamite'' was, adding that he represented new ideas and that
Corbet was a ``good old boy'' of Arizona politics. Early returns
showed Corbet with a 2-1 lead over Bellus.
   Sen. John Hays, a rural lawmaker who voted to oust Mecham, was
running ahead of pro-Mecham challenger Shirley Mac-Noye. GOP Sens.
Bill DeLong and Doug Todd, who also voted to convict the former
governor, also had early leads.
   But Sen. Peter Kay of Phoenix and Sen. Jack Taylor of Mesa, both
of whom voted to oust the governor, were running behind their
rivals in early returns.
   Also on Tuesday's ballot were two congressional races.
   In District 1 in eastern Maricopa County, Democrat John Fillmore
defeated rival Thane Read for the right to challenge first-term
Republican Jay Rhodes in November. With 325 of 417 precincts, or 78
percent, reporting, Fillmore had 16,163 votes, or 76 percent, to
Read's 4,971 votes, or 24 percent.
   In southern Arizona's District 5, two-term incumbent Jim Kolbe
easily defeated his challengers.
   With 68 of 360 precincts reporting, or 19 percent, Kolbe had
6,591 votes, or 78 percent, to political newcomer Walt Weber's
1,017 votes, or 12 percent; Alberto Rodriguez, a Mecham appointee
for state liquor superintendent whose controversial nomination was
withdrawn, had 831 votes, or 10 percent.
</TEXT>
