<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0444EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NewHampshirePrimary     09-14 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Hampshire Primary,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gregg Wins New Hampshire GOP Primary for Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMA LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Rep. Judd Gregg said he would
depict his Democratic opponent for governor, Paul McEachern, as a
free-spending liberal in the fall campaign beginning today after
Gregg's victory in a three-way primary.
   ``We will show the people of New Hampshire what deep
philosophical differences there are ... a choice between fiscal
restraint and liberal spending,'' Gregg said.
   McEachern, a lawyer who ran a fairly close race for governor two
years ago, responded that the fight ``is going to be to show the
real Judd Gregg for who he is, as someone who has been voting
against our interests in Congress the last eight years and comes
back and wants us to elect a name to the seat. We're going to elect
a governor, not a name.''
   Gregg, a four-term congressman, overwhelmingly defeated former
Manchester Mayor Robert Shaw and political newcomer William
Lawrence, a quality-control engineer, in Tuesday's primary.
   With 266 of 298 precincts reporting, Gregg had 60,234 votes, or
79 percent, to 13,737 votes for Shaw, or 18 percent, and 2,339
votes for Lawrence, or 3 percent.
   Gregg, son of a former governor, got into the race after Gov.
John Sununu, a national co-chairman of George Bush's presidential
campaign, decided not to seek a fourth two-year term.
   In the 2nd District, where Gregg gave up his House seat, Chuck
Douglas, a 45-year-old former state Supreme Court justice, won the
Republican nomination. Nashua Mayor James Donchess, 39, is the
Democratic candidate.
   While Douglas was endorsed by nationally known conservatives
including Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah and Rep. Jack Kemp of New York,
Sununu sent campaign letters and made television spots for state
Rep. Betty Tamposi.
   Douglas accused Tamposi, daughter of a millionaire real estate
developer, of using her wealth to try to buy the election. She
loaned her campaign $150,000.
   ``It's important that we hold this seat,'' Douglas said after
his victory. ``It's important to the party, to New Hampshire and to
the conservative cause.''
   With 151 of 178 precincts reporting, or 85 percent, Donchess had
11,023 votes, or 66 percent, former state Rep. Barbara Underwood
had 4,297 or 26 percent, and Lewis du Pont Smith had 1,293, or 8
percent.
   Douglas led with 47 percent to Tamposi's 41 percent. The
remainder was split among Gregg's cousin, Stephen Gregg of
Holderness; state Rep. Alf Jacobson of New London; Peterborough
magazine editor Dennis Allen; and Milford restaurateur Andrew
Tempelman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
