<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Haiti     09-14 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Bishop Denounces Killings, Government Says It Regrets
Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Haiti's military rulers expressed
regret over the killing of nine parishioners and fires that burned
down two Roman Catholic churches, but two opposition leaders blamed
the government for the violence.
   Also Tuesday, the church's Radio Soleil reported a militiaman
was acquitted in a November 1985 slaying which fueled public
outrage that led to the eventual ouster of dictator Jean-Claude
Duvalier.
   A bishop meanwhile demanded justice for victims of the church
attacks.
   ``In the name of Jesus Christ, we say stop this destruction. We
condemn ... these criminal acts ... and demand justice for all the
victims,'' the Rev. Joseph Lafontant, auxiliary bishop of
Port-au-Prince, said on Radio Soleil Tuesday night.
   In other violence, Radio Haiti Inter said a group of
unidentified men in civilian clothes attacked Radio Cacique,
pillaging and carrying away its broadcasting equipment Tuesday
afternoon. Radio Cacique often broadcasts opinion.
   A statement from Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy's military regime was
broadcast by radio stations Tuesday, saying the government
``regrets the incidents ... in which the churches of St. Jean Bosco
and Immaculate Conception were burned.''
   Thugs armed with handguns and machetes attacked the congregation
of St. Bosco Church on Sunday during a Mass and burned down the
building. Radio Haiti Inter said three more bodies were discovered
Tuesday in the Port-au-Prince church, bringing the casualty toll to
nine dead and 77 wounded.
   The church's priest, the Rev. Jean-Bertrand Aristide, is an
outspoken critic of the military government and popular among
Haiti's poor. Aristide went into hiding right after the attack.
   Soldiers and police at a compound across the street from the
church watched the assault without intervening.
   On Monday, the Chapel of Immaculate Conception in the capital's
Cite Soleil slum burned to the ground.
   Five men and a woman appeared on government television Monday
boasting they had participated in Sunday's killings and warning
there would be ``heaps of corpses'' at future Masses.
   The six made no attempt to hide their identities and spoke on
the government-controlled network apparently without fear of arrest
or reprisals.
   They said they supported a rival priest, the Rev. Arthur Volel
of the Chapel of Immaculate Conception, but Volel denied such a
link on Tele-Haiti Tuesday night.
   ``The police (are) pursuing the culprits, among whom are the
self-proclaimed perpetrators who appeared on television,'' said the
government communique issued by the information ministry Tuesday.
   The statement said the military government condemned the
attacks, would open an investigation and ``sympathizes with the
families of the victims, the Salesian fathers and the Catholic
Church.''
   Both churches are led by priests of the Salesian Fathers, a
group specializing in vocational training.
   Namphy's government has issued similar statements in the past
following mass killings and other violence. But it has never
followed up with investigations or convictions.
   ``We are confronted by state banditry,'' said Jean-Jacques
Honorat, head of the Haitian Center for the Defense of Human
Liberties.
   Honorat and Sylvio Claude, head of the Christian Democrat Party
and one of Haiti's most popular opposition leaders, blamed the
government for the killing.
   Several witnesses on the scene of the attack against Aristide's
church say they recognized city hall employees among the
assailants, but Mayor Franck Romain denied the charges.
   Romain, Port-au-Prince mayor until Duvalier's ouster on Feb. 7,
1986, returned to that office in army-run elections in January, and
remained after Namphy ousted President Leslie Manigat in a coup on
June 19, ending four months of civilian rule.
   A criminal court in Gonaives meanwhile acquitted Cereste
Saint-Phard because of insufficient evidence after three of six
witnesses failed to appear at his trial, Radio Soleil said.
   Saint-Phard is an ex-member of the feared Tonton Macoutes, a
private militia of terror that kept the Duvalier family in power
for 29 years.
   He was charged with the shooting death of Jean-Robert Cius, one
of three high school students killed by Macoutes during an
anti-government demonstration.
</TEXT>
