<1ST_LINE>r p PM-VermontPrimary     09-14 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vermont Primary,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vermont's Lone Congressman Wins Primary To Seek Open Senate Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER GRAFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. James Jeffords overcame a
conservative challenge in the Republican primary to become the
frontrunner in the general election race for retiring GOP Sen.
Robert Stafford's seat.
   Jeffords easily defeated political newcomer Michael Griffes, who
called himself the real Republican in the race, in Tuesday's GOP
primary.
   Jeffords will face former U.S. Attorney William Gray in the
November election. Polls have given Jeffords a big lead over Gray,
despite Vermont conservatives' complaints over Jefford's lack of
support for President Reagan.
   In 1981, Jeffords was the sole House Republican to vote against
Reagan's tax-cut package; In 1987, he had the second-highest
anti-Reagan voting record among Republicans in the House, as
analyzed by Congressional Quarterly magazine. He opposed the
president on 71 percent of the key votes.
   With 259 of 262 precincts reporting, Jeffords had 30,135 votes,
or 61 percent, to Griffes' 19,163 votes, or 39 percent.
   ``Mike Griffes and his people ran a very energetic campaign. I
commend them for this energy. I'm confident we can all work
together and win as a Republican Party,'' Jeffords told a packed
hall of supporters Tuesday night.
   Former Lt. Gov. Peter Smith easily won the GOP primary to run
for Vermont's lone House seat, which Jeffords is vacating. Four
Democrats sought their party's nomination, and Paul Poirier and
Peter Welch were locked in a close race with 99 percent of the
precincts counted early today.
   Poirier claimed victory, but Welch refused to concede.
   The major party winners will be joined on the November ballot by
Burlington Mayor Bernard Sanders, a socialist who is running a
strong independent campaign for the House seat, and candidates
representing the Liberty Union, the Libertarian Party and the Small
Is Beautiful Party.
   Democratic Gov. Madeleine Kunin, seeking her third term, was
unopposed in Tuesday's primary, as was her Republican challenger,
state Rep. Michael Bernhardt.
</TEXT>
