<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gilbert-FirstPerson     09-14 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gilbert-First Person,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP Photographer Takes Look at Hurricane's Chaos</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos MH1,2,3</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Associated Press photographer Chris O'Meara
traveled to Jamaica with U.S. fire and other relief workers Tuesday
as the island nation struggled to recover from Hurricane Gilbert's
devastation. O'Meara spent 45 minutes Tuesday photographing areas
near the airport. The following is his description:
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The place was pretty hard hit from the
look of things from the air.
   Coming over the western part of the island, you could see the
trees were down, almost like dominoes. It was like a tornado went
ripping through there.
   Before we landed, they let two people hang with harnesses out of
the plane to get pictures of the island. The Red Cross people and
the foreign relief people said they were going to use the footage
to show how bad the island was really hit.
   We finally landed, and there were probably about 12 or 15
policemen and soldiers and some other people there to help out the
fire department.
   There was debris thrown up against the buildings and strewn
everywhere _ ventilation ducts, baggage carts. A couple of big
hangars had their roofs bent back. The terminal was flooded.
   There seemed to be a lot of flooding in the streets still. It
was still raining when we were there.
   Nobody was mentioning any casualties, but they were saying
things like, ``If you think this is bad, you should see the rest of
island.''
   It was getting dark when we left. You couldn't see any lights.
The island was totally dark, and so was the airport. There are no
landing lights at all. It looks very strange at night.
   The people seemed really happy to see the fire department. They
really need a lot there. There's no water, electricty or phones
right now, and no one's really sure when they will be restored.
   Before we left, one woman was pleading with us not to make it
look so bad because of the tourist industry.
   We took back two teen-age boys to Miami. They both seemed pretty
excited about going through a hurricane.
</TEXT>
