<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-WisconsinPrimary     09-14 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wisconsin Primary,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kohl, Engeleiter To Battle For Proxmire Senate Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR L. SRB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionaire basketball team owner Herbert Kohl
and state Sen. Susan Engeleiter won easy primary victories and will
square off in November for the U.S. Senate seat held by Sen.
William Proxmire, D-Wis.
   Kohl, a Democrat, and Engeleiter, a Republican, took early leads
Tuesday and never lost them.
   Kohl, 53, millionaire owner of the NBA's Milwaukee Bucks, who is
making his first bid for public office, ended a political comeback
by former Gov. Anthony S. Earl in a five-way Democratic primary
Tuesday.
   ``The voters of Wisconsin said today they wanted a qualified,
non-politician with real-world business experience,'' said Kohl,
who spent more than $2 million in the primary campaign. ``They said
they wanted someone independent of political action committees who
would not take a penny from any of them.''
   Earl lost the governor's job two years ago to Republican Tommy
Thompson.
   With 98 percent of the vote counted, Kohl had 247,349 votes, or
47 percent, to Earl's 201,334 votes, or 38 percent. Former deputy
attorney general Edward R. Garvey had 54,649 votes, or 10 percent,
Secretary of State Douglas La Follette had 19,830 votes, or 4
percent, and Edmond Hou-Seye, a Sheboygan tire dealer, had 5,107
votes, or 1 percent.
   ``I think Herb Kohl (will) make a very strong and fine
Democratic candidate and outstanding U.S. senator,'' said Proxmire,
72, who is retiring in January after 31 years in the Senate. He
said Engeleiter is ``well qualified.''
   Engeleiter, 36, defeated Stephen B. King, former GOP state
chairman, and Peter Y. Taylor, to become the only woman nominated
by a major party for the U.S. Senate this year.
   She defeated King, 203,925 to 143,980 votes, or 57 percent to 40
percent. Taylor, of Milwaukee, had 8,7090 votes, or 2 percent.
   Engeleiter cited her 13 years in the Legislature and said her
campaign would emphasize her ``middle class values.''
   ``I understand far more than Herb Kohl ever can the needs of
middle-class Wisconsin,'' she said. ``I was raised middle class,
attend public schools and I know what it means to work hard for a
living for my family.''
   Democratic Rep. Jim Moody, the only Wisconsin congressman facing
primary opposition, easily won the nomination for a fourth term
from the 5th District, and will face GOP candidate Helen Barnhill,
a black businesswoman, on Nov. 8.
   Moody announced earlier this year he was vacating the seat to
run for the Senate, but dropped out of the Senate race and
re-entered the House race in June when Kohl announced his candidacy.
   With 100 percent of the precincts reported, Moody collected
47,346 votes, or 59 percent; Matt Flynn, a former state Democratic
chairman, had 19,756 votes, or 25 percent.
   Donald Sykes, the former director of a local anti-poverty
agency, had 5,298 votes, or 7 percent. Roman Blenski, a former
legislator and perennial candidate, had 565 votes, or 1 percent.
   Two candidates who dropped out of the race when Moody entered,
Milwaukee County Supervisor Terrance Pitts and former Circuit Judge
Frederick Kessler, picked up 4,957 votes, 6 percent, and 2,494
votes, 3 percent, respectively.
   On the Republican side, Barnhill had 13,513 votes, or 68
percent, with 100 percent of the precincts reported. Environmental
activist Janette Marsh had 6,341 votes, or 32 percent.
   Moody said he would not take anything for granted in his
campaign against Barnhill. ``She's a very serious candidate,'' he
said. ``I respect her a great deal.''
   Barnhill said her victory Tuesday was ``the first hurdle ... and
we'll be on our way in the morning.''
</TEXT>
