<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-14 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stock Prices Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen, while
stock prices rose slightly in cautious trading in Tokyo today,
traders said.
   The dollar closed at 133.45 yen, up 0.38 yen from Tuesday's
closing. After opening at 133.47 yen, the currency fluctuated
throughout the day, ranging between 133.33 yen and 133.65 yen.
   ``The dollar-yen rate did not move much due to two different
perceptions about the dollar's future,'' said Takamasa Yamazaki of
Daiwa Bank in Tokyo.
   ``But dollar-selling sentiment continued to prevail in the
market as participants waited cautiously for the release of U.S.
trade figure,'' Yamazaki said.
   U.S. trade figures for July are scheduled to be announced in
Washington later today.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues ended trading at 27,805.67, up 11.51 points or 0.04
percent from Tuesday's closing.
   The index rose quickly after the market opened, following a gain
in the Dow Jones industrial average on Wall Street overnight, and
managed to hold on to the gains in moderate to heavy trading.
   Despite a wait-and-see mood due to the upcoming U.S. trade
figures and a Japanese holiday Thursday, volume on the first
section reached the 1 billion share level for the first time since
Aug. 19, traders said.
   But they said few investors were eager to make significant moves
because the holiday would prevent the Tokyo market from responding
immediately to the U.S. trade figures. Thursday is Respect for the
Aged Day, a Japanese national holiday.
</TEXT>
