<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MinnesotaPrimary     09-14 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minnesota Primary,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Durenberger, Humphrey Coast To Victories In Low-vote Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sen. Dave Durenberger and
Democratic challenger Hubert H. Humphrey III claimed their parties'
nominations in primaries that apparently set a record for voter
disinterest.
   ``It's real disappointing,'' said Secretary of State Joan Growe.
The 292,000-voter turnout was about 10 percent of the state's 3.1
million eligible voters _ apparently the lowest since the state
began keepinr records in 1950.
   Growe blamed the lack of voter participation on the absence of
serious challenges to either Durenberger or Humphrey, whose races
topped the ticket.
   Durenberger spent Tuesday in Washington, D.C., where Congress
was in session, and voted by absentee ballot in Avon, Minn.
   With 99 percent of the state's 4,079 precincts, Durenberger, 54,
who was first elected to the Senate in 1978, received 93 of the
vote in the Independent-Republican Senate primary with a 110,052
tally.
   Sharon Anderson, 49, of St. Paul, came in a distant second, with
5,426 votes or 5 percent. John J. Zeleniak, 78, of Columbia
Heights, a retired physicist, was in third place, with 2,388 votes
or 2 percent.
   Humphrey, 46, son of the former vice president and U.S. senator,
received 155,156 votes, or 91 percent, in the Democratic Farm Labor
Senate primary. His challenger, truck driver Kent S. Herschbach,
41, a supporter of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche, received
15,927 votes, or 9 percent.
   Humphrey, a former state senator and Minnesota's attorney
general since 1983, said his primary victory, ``lets us go forward
directly again tomorrow.''
   ``I expect polling to go up and down a little more, and it's
going to close in very soon and it's going to be a horse race, and
I'm going to win,'' he said. ``I like winning elections.''
   Humphrey has trailed Durenberger by up to 19 percentage points
in public opinion polls, although no independent polls have been
released recently. He also has trailed Durenberger by a 2-1 margin
in fund-raising.
   Durenberger expects to spend $6.5 million in his re-election
bid, while the Humphrey campaign plans to spend $3.5 million to $4
million.
   The names of four other U.S. Senate candidates will appear on
the Nov. 8 general election ballot: Derrick P. Grimmer of the Grass
Roots Party, Wendy Lyons of the Socialist Workers Party, Arlen
Overvig of the Libertarian Party, and independent candidate Polly
Mann.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
