<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0527EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-EEC-Arafat     09-14 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EEC-Arafat,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Ends 2-Day Visit To European Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jordan's King Hussein paved the way
for the creation of an independent Palestinian state when he
severed ties with the occupied West Bank, PLO chief Yasser Arafat
said.
   ``We are at a crucial stage,'' Arafat said in a speech Tuesday
to the European Parliament. ``The Palestinian state, the key to
peace, security and development in the Arab region ... is in the
offing.''
   Arafat is likely to discuss creation of a Palestinian state in
meetings today, the final day of a two-day visit, with the Greek
and French foreign ministers.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization chief told socialist
Parliament members that the Palestine National Council, a kind of
parliament-in-exile, would decide on a Palestinian state on the
West Bank. The Palestinian council is to meet next month in Tunisia.
   ``The only option left is the right, realistic and irreplaceable
one _ namely, the Palestinian option, the essence of which is the
independent Palestinian state,'' Arafat said at a closed-door
meeting with the European Parliament's 165-strong Socialist group,
the largest in the 518-member assembly.
   ``This state will have a republican, democratic and multiparty
system; it will abide by the Universal Declaration of Human Rights
and will not discriminate among its citizens on the basis of color,
race or religion,'' Arafat said.
   A test of his speech was released to reporters.
   Arafat said the PLO should represent the Palestinian people at
an international peace conference. Israel has rejected the idea and
refuses to talk to the PLO, which it views as a terrorist group.
   ``It would be possible at the said conference and through the
negotiations which will take place within its framework to discuss
and agree (on) arrangements for international guarantees of peace
among all states of the region, including the independent
Palestinian state,'' Arafat stated.
   Of King Hussein's decision July 31 to relinquish sovereignty
over the West Bank, Arafat said:
   ``The measures ended the European, American and Israeli debate
on Palestinian representation at the international conference. No
one can claim anymore that there is someone else to share with the
PLO the representation of the Palestinian people.''
   The PLO is seeking to form a provisional government or a
government-in-exile for the West Bank and Gaza Strip, where more
than 1.5 million Palestinians live.
   The territories, captured from Jordan and Egypt during the 1967
Middle East war, have been the scene of a Palestinian uprising
since last Dec. 8 in which more than 260 Palestinians and six
Israelis have died.
   Richard Balfe, a British Laborite who attended the session with
Arafat, said the PLO leader spoke in Arabic for about 40 minutes,
then fielded questions for another half hour.
   He said Arafat ``made it fairly clear that the recognition of
Israel was part of the negotiation'' at an international peace
conference.
   Lord Plumb, the Parliament president, met for 20 minutes with
Arafat before the meeting.
   He told reporters his message to the PLO leader was ``Get out of
violence, get into negotiations,'' and added he sensed Arafat was
in Strasbourg ``to move toward condemnation of violence.''
   But in Jerusalem, Avi Pazner, spokesman for Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir, said Arafat's address contained nothing new.
   ``It sounds like a rehashing of all his (Arafat's) ideas, the
main thing being that he still wants the disappearance of the state
of Israel. That's the crux of it ... I don't see anything new,''
Pazner said.
</TEXT>
