<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SierraFire-Evacuees     09-14 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sierra Fire-Evacuees,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeless Fire Victims Struggle With Losses, Grief</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Sierra Fire Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRASS VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rusty Cline, one of the thousands
who narrowly escaped a wildfire, complained of dizziness, searched
for shoes, and cried that the flames that razed her home may have
killed her dog.
   Cline and her son were part of what American Red Cross worker
Elzabeth Quirk dubbed ``the morning of tears'' at an evacuation
center Tuesday in a Grass Valley high school.
   ``The fire raced in on us. We ran for the car, but it beat us
there,'' said Cline, 51, a resident of the tiny community of Rough
and Ready, three miles west of Grass Valley.
   She paused, weeping, then added, ``I couldn't get my dog in the
car. She was too scared.''
   Her son, Lee Griep, 29, had stopped in during a bicycle tour of
the nation that started from his home in Lakewood, Fla. The bicycle
burned in the fire.
   ``I rode out in a firefighter's jeep, we got separated from my
mom's car, and the fire swept right over us,'' he said.
   More than 1,200 fire refugees have passed through the center
since flames erupted Sunday, said Red Cross spokesman James Poole.
   About 70 spent the night on cots in a gymnasium Monday, he said.
Uncounted others slept in vehicles outside, at the homes of friends
or relatives and in motels that were filled up to 30 miles away.
   The estimated 8,000 evacuees have been able to return home, if
they found their homes still standing, authorities said. Nearly 100
houses were gutted.
   Other residents returned home only to be chased a second or
third time by the erratic, stubborn blaze in the drought-parched
hills of timber, oak and brush.
   Among the evacuees were Ed and Kathy Vierra, in their early 30s,
who lived in the open bed of their pickup truck with three young
children.
   ``Of course it's hard, but at least I know where my kids are,
where my husband is,'' she said, waving her hand at her family.
   A 40-foot section of wall at the center was plastered with
hundreds of messages, like ``Call if you need a place to stay'' or
``Just want to know you're all OK, couldn't get through on the
phone.'' Most just pleaded, ``Please call!''
   Nearby were piles of donated clothes and food. A children's
activity area was decorated with their drawings.
   Nurses at the medical station treated everything from scrapes to
headaches.
   Air tankers dropping fire retardant periodically thundered
overhead through the smoke, drowning conversation.
   Occasionally, word came in that another area was safe for
residents. Don Blicht, 56, of Rough and Ready, got that word and
immediately jumped in his recreational vehicle.
   ``We're headed back to see if the house is still there,'' he
said. ``I was hosing down the roof to put out cinders when we had
to leave. We left the chickens and everything.''
   Some of those who lost homes had insurance, those without may
have to depend on government and private aid.
   Cline, who had no insurance on her destroyed home, was asked
about the future.
   ``I have no idea,'' she said. ``I just don't know.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
