<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     09-14 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Front Scatters Rain from New Mexico to Virginias; Gilbert Glances
Keys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A stationary front scattered rain from New Mexico to West
Virginia today and a thunderstorm associated with Hurricane Gilbert
produced rain and winds gusting to 58 mph at Key West, Fla.
   Gilbert, the strongest hurricane in history, was moving slowly
in the western Caribbean with winds up to 175 mph. Its only impact
on the continental United States so far occurred over the Florida
Keys, where the thunderstorm generated stiff gusts late Tuesday.
   The long stationary front dropped heavy rain on parts of New
Mexico, with Clayton getting 1.47 inches in six hours.
   The front also generated showers and thunderstorms over much of
Colorado, and scattered showers over west-central Texas,
southwestern Oklahoma, eastern Kentucky, southern West Virginia and
western Virginia.
   Clear skies prevailed across the rest of the nation. Early
morning temperatures ranged from the 40s and 50s across most of the
northern tier of the country to the 70s from the desert Southwest
and the Rio Grande Valley through the lower Mississippi Valley to
the southern Atlantic Coast. It was in the 80s in southern Florida.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
eastern New Mexico across northern Texas to the central Gulf Coast.
Showers also were predicted for the west-central Plains to the
central Plateau region, with snow at higher elevations in the
Rockies. Showers also were expected near the Canadian border from
New York state to Maine and in Florida.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 50s and 60s from the central
Plateau across the central Rockies to the South Dakota Black Hills
and the west-central Plains; in the 60s in northern Michigan,
northern New York state and northern New England; in the 90s from
the South Atlantic and Gulf Coast states to southeast Oklahoma and
eastern Texas, and the inland valleys of the West Coast states; and
near 100 degrees in the desert Southwest. Highs elsewhere were
forecast to be in the 70s and 80s.
   At 3 a.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 30 degrees at
Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 85 degrees at Homestead, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 72 fair; Boston 59 windy; Buffalo 54 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 73 foggy; Cincinnati 63 foggy; Cleveland
49 fair; Detroit 52 fair; Miami 83 cloudy; New York 62 fair;
Philadelphia 63 fair; Pittsburgh 50 fair; Portland, Me. 50 fair;
Washington 73 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 46 fair; Chicago 59 fair; Dallas-Ft. Worth 74
fair; Denver 48 drizzle; Des Moines 58 fair; Indianapolis 57 fair;
Kansas City 63 fair; Mpls-St. Paul 51 fair; Nashville 75 fair; New
Orleans 76 fair; St. Louis 68 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 59 cloudy; Anchorage 47 fair; Las Vegas 66
fair; Los Angeles 62 fair; Phoenix 79 fair; Salt Lake City 46 fair;
San Diego 67 cloudy; San Francisco 58 fair; Seattle 61 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 43 fair; Toronto 48 fair.
</TEXT>
