<1ST_LINE>r p PM-UtahPrimary     09-14 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Utah Primary,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stringham Beats Oliver In Democratic U.S. House Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Stringham, a retired steelworker,
narrowly defeated businessman Craig Oliver in the Democratic
primary race for the heavily Republican 3rd Congressional District.
   With all 463 precincts reporting in Tuesday's primary, Stringham
had 7,038 votes, or 52 percent, to Oliver's 6,483, or 48 percent.
   Stringham, who is chairman of the Utah County Democratic Party,
will face Republican Rep. Howard Nielson, the only congressman the
district has ever had. Nielson was unopposed for the GOP nomination
for a fourth term.
   ``I'm bouncing off the ceiling,'' Stringham said in victory.
``It was a long night, but we felt all the way along that we were
going to be victorious.''
   He vowed the same result against Nielson on Nov. 8, although
polls show the incumbent, a landslide winner in three previous
elections, with a comfortable lead over both the Democratic
contenders.
   Nielson, 64, remained confident of his re-election prospects as
a self-described ``top fiscal conservative in Congress.''
   ``I think I can win the election without much trouble,'' he said
in an interview from his home. ``But I'm still going to work hard.''
</TEXT>
