<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0612EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NuclearWaste 1stLd-Writethru a0415 09-14 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Waste, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0415,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Study Needed on New Mexico Nuclear Waste Site, Lawmaker Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS to add three grafs after 11th graf pvs, bgng ``WIPP
will, with Energy spokesman saying obstacles may delay opening to
1989; picks up 12th graf pvs, But in.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee chairman is telling
Energy Department officials to ``do your homework'' before pushing
Congress to approve the opening of an underground nuclear waste
disposal facility.
   Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., made the statement Tuesday after his
Government Operations environment, energy and natural resources
subcommittee was told that major questions remain about the Waste
Isolation Pilot Plant (WIPP) in New Mexico.
   The department wants to begin putting waste into the underground
facility next month, but it has not adequately proven that it can
operate it safely, according to witnesses and documents at the
hearing.
   Among those raising questions were the department's office of
safety appraisals, its Brookhaven National Laboratory and an
environmental consultant it hired to review WIPP.
   At the same time, the congressional General Accounting Office
said it would be premature for Congress to approve the Energy
Department's request to pass legislation needed to launch the $700
million project.
   ``There are many uncertainties involving WIPP performance that
must be addressed before DOE can demonstrate that the facility is
suitable,'' GAO's Keith Fultz said.
   Synar called the hearing to look into the department's plan to
place 125,000 barrels of so-called transuranic waste into the
repository 2,150 feet below the ground near Carlsbad.
   Transuranic waste, a byproduct of nuclear weapons production, is
a combination of radioactive material and a wide variety of
hazardous substances. The waste proposed for WIPP represents
approximately half the amount now stored above ground in about half
a dozen states.
   Synar said energy officials should ``go home and do your
homework and then come back and ask us for the legislation. Don't
put the cart before the horse. We're one month away from this
targeted (waste) loading and you can't justify this loading.''
   Jill Lytle, deputy assistant energy secretary for nuclear
materials, told Synar the agency plans to follow environmental laws
governing the disposal of dangerous waste during a five-year test
of the WIPP facility.
   ``WIPP will not endanger the safety and health of the public,''
she testified.
   A department spokesman said in an interview Tuesday night that
the repository is ready to begin receiving waste perhaps by the
beginning the year, but for four obstacles in the way. He said no
date has been set, however.
   ``We won't have an opening date until we have the resolution of
those four items. I think it's too strong to say the opening has
been postponed indefinitely. We're actively pursuing the opening of
WIPP,'' said spokesman Richard Marquez.
   He said nuclear waste containers must be tested, a five-year
plan for use of the facility and a site readiness review must be
performed before an opening date can be set. Congress must also
pass a bill withdrawing the WIPP land from public and mining uses.
   But in a memo written Sept. 2, James Knight, director of the
Energy Department's office of safety appraisals, said the
department's final safety analysis report lacks ``sufficient
information for us to independently conclude that the facility can
be operated safely.''
   In an August letter to Knight, a Brookhaven team that visited
WIPP said facility officials ``have not addressed issues associated
with either adequacy of the (plant's) design or the quality
assurance of the construction phase.''
   Lokesh Chaturvedi, the consultant, said energy officials had not
given him any data about what might happen to stored waste if the
facility was breached by a pressurized brine reservoir that appears
to exist about 800 feet below portions of the WIPP site.
   Chaturvedi, deputy director of the Environmental Evaluation
Group in Albuquerque, and Owen Thompson, a staff member of the
office of safety appraisals, also questioned the need to even put
barrels of waste into WIPP during the five-year test.
   ``The DOE describes WIPP as a research and development facility,
but we have not been able to receive a final plan of research
requiring waste emplacement,'' Chaturvedi said.
   Thompson said that because waste barrels are not expected to
leak during the five years, ``actual repository conditions are not
being evaluated and actual repository performance will not be
demonstrated.''
   The GAO's Fultz said he has been unable to resolve questions
about whether WIPP officials would be able to retrieve waste that
leaked from barrels and where any retrieved waste would be stored.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
