<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ThiokolSuits     09-14 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thiokol Suits,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Consultants Sue Morton Thiokol over Challenger Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two safety consultants sued Morton Thiokol Inc.,
claiming they were fired for attempting to inform NASA about
problems involving solid-fuel rocket motors after the destruction
of space shuttle Challenger.
   Steven Agee of Renton, Wash., and Anthony Laine of Phoenix filed
separate suits Monday in federal court in Chicago seeking
unspecified damages. The suits allege wrongful termination,
defamation and violation of federal racketeering laws.
   Both men were hired as system-safety analysts for the booster
redesign program created after the January 1986 explosion that
killed Challenger's seven astronauts. The accident was blamed on a
faulty seal in a booster rocket.
   Agee, 45, worked at the rocket maker's plant in Utah from
November 1986 until March 1987. Laine started in January 1987 and
was fired the following month.
   Agee's suit alleges he wrote 221 catastrophic ``hazard
analyses,'' or ways that the rockets could fail, that Morton
Thiokol failed to forward to the National Aerospace and Space
Administration, which contracts with Thiokol to build shuttle
rockets.
   Agee's litigation asserts he was defamed when Thiokol falsely
told another prospective employer, the Boeing Co., that he was
fired because he got into a serious fight with one of his
supervisors at Thiokol.
   Laine contends he was ordered to cease an investigation of a
potential hazard in the booster rocket engine and had been told
that safety engineers were only to ``cut and paste old reports''
and not investigate any new potential safety problems.
   Thiokol falsely told NASA that Laine was fired for compiling
``classified information'' that he should not have had, thus
defaming him, the lawsuit indicates.
   The suits also assert that racketeering laws were violated when
Thiokol used the mails and telephones to file false reports with
the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission regarding its
contractual obligations with NASA.
   Morton Thiokol, whose corporate offices are in Chicago, was
named as a defendant along with five of the company's Utah-based
managers and Phoenix-based ARC Technical Services Inc., an
engineering personnel company through which Agee and Laine were
paid.
   Thiokol lawyer Darryl Lee said Tuesday he would have no comment
because he had not seen the complaints.
   Lawsuits filed by another former engineer, Roger Boisjoly, who
warned against the launching of the Challenger, were dismissed last
month by a federal judge in Salt Lake City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
