<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0810EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EasterSentencing     09-14 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Easter Sentencing,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Easter, Sons Ordered to Serve Life in Separate Prisons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother and her three sons have been sentenced
to life in separate prisons for murdering three police officers
during a standoff at a motel.
   Judge Richard P. Hathaway on Tuesday said he wished he could
have imposed the death penalty on Alberta Easter and her sons,
George, Roy and William Lemons.
   First-degree murder carries an automatic sentence of life
without parole. The death penalty is forbidden under Michigan's
constitution.
   The judge sentenced the four to solitary confinement in separate
prisons.
   ``In this way, the defendants will understand the pain of
separation that the victims' families feel,'' he said, his voice
breaking in emotion and fading to a whisper.
   ``The actions on July 9 are a disgrace to the word `family.' I
only wish the victims' families could step forward and sentence the
defendants instead of the court.''
   Easter and her sons were convicted last month of murdering
Inkster Sgt. Ira Parker and Officers Clay Hoover and Daniel Dubiel
during an 11-hour siege in 1987. The trial lasted 14 weeks.
   Hoover, Dubiel and Parker had gone to the motel in the Detroit
suburb to serve a bad-check warrant on Easter and were taken
hostage. When the four surrendered, the officers were found dead of
multiple gunshot wounds.
   Easter and her sons maintained their innocence Tuesday.
   ``Our blood is on your hands. You pray for us and our lives,''
she said.
   ``I am sorry about the loss, but it wasn't our fault. Injustice
has been made legal,'' William Lemons said.
</TEXT>
