<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0468 09-14 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,0758</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cordes Back In West Germany After 20 Months' Captivity in Beirut</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with newspaper reports that
ransom paid and Cordes moved before release. Pickup 5th graf pvs,
``Cordes and...'' Trims.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Hamadi Trial, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Rudolf Cordes, home after
20 months of captivity in the hands of pro-Iranian kidnappers in
Beirut, was flown to an undisclosed location to rest and enjoy a
reunion with his wife and two sons.
   Reporters were given no chance to talk to the 55-year-old
Frankfurt businessman upon his arrival at Cologne-Bonn airport
Tuesday night.
   West German officials, including Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher, have denied making any payments for Cordes' freedom. He
was released by his pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem kidnappers late
Monday night.
   But the mass-circulation Bild newspaper of Hamburg said ``a sum
of millions is believed to have been paid to kidnappers for the
release.'' Bild cited unidentified security sources.
   The newspaper also quoted a source identified only as a
``security expert'' as saying that at least 40 million marks ($22.2
million) were paid for Cordes' release. Bild is known to have good
sources within the government.
   A high-ranking government official described Cordes' long
captivity, the isolation he endured, and his constant uncertainty
over his fate.
   The Los Angeles Times said today Iran apparently arranged for
Cordes to be transferred from captors linked to Mohammed Ali
Hamadi, who is being tried in Germany for hijacking a TWA jet, to
the group that freed the West German.
   Iran apparently arranged the release to regain favor with West
Germany, a vital trading partner and the Western nation with which
it has the closest ties, the Times said, citing unidentified
sources.
   Cordes was abducted in West Beirut in January 1987, three days
before a West German engineer, Alfred Schmidt, was kidnapped.
Schmidt was freed Sept. 7, 1987. The Hamadi clan was believed to
have abducted both men.
   Cordes and his wife, Marlene, touched down at 10:20 p.m. aboard
a twin-engine West German military jet after a five-hour flight
from Syria.
   The federal minister for chancellery affairs, Wolfgang
Schaeuble, was aboard the same plane.
   Schaeuble later told West German television that Cordes was
``feeling better than he had expected.''
   ``But naturally he's very weak. He's probably feeling better now
because of the initial excitement than he will be tomorrow or the
day after tomorrow,'' the official said.
   ``He's been flown to a place where he can find privacy for a
time. He desperately needs quiet, to recover, to work through the
experience.
   ``I don't know where he's going and even if I knew I wouldn't
say,'' the official said.
   Schaeuble said Cordes told him his kidnappers ``treated him
humanely, but the conditions were hard, he was always isolated and
was always chained.''
   Hans Neusel, a state secretary in the federal Interior Ministry,
told reporters at the airport Cordes said there were signs he was
about to be released before it happened.
   ``His hopes increased when he was given new clothes three days
before he was freed,'' said Neusel, who also was on the plane with
Cordes.
   Schaeuble said Cordes could not identify the kidnappers because
they wore masks in his presence.
   The minister, who headed the government's Middle East crisis
staff, reiterated earlier government statements that no deals were
made for Cordes' release.
   Cordes, Beirut manager for the Hoechst AG pharmaceutical
company, was freed in Beirut at midnight Monday by Shiite Moslem
extremists. Syrian officers escorted him to Damascus after his
release.
   Cordes was the last West German hostage in Lebanon, where 17
other foreigners are still missing and believed held captive. The
longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of
The Associated Press, who was kidnapped on March 16, 1985.
   Cordes' captors, a group calling itself the Holy Warriors for
Freedom, said in a statement Monday that they were freeing him in
response to Iranian and Syrian intervention.
   The kidnappers also said his release was linked to Hamadi, a
Lebanese Shiite on trial in West Germany for a 1985 TWA jetliner
hijacking and the shooting death of U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem.
   Hamadi's older brother, Abbas, is serving a 13-year prison
sentence in Frankfurt. He was convicted in April of complicity in
kidnapping Cordes and Schmidt in an effort to force West Germany to
free Mohammed Hamadi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
