<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0846EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LyingOfficial     09-14 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lying Official,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Board President Fired</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city School Board president has been fired
for feeding false information to board members in an effort to
track down leaks to the news media.
   Mayor Kurt Schmoke on Tuesday removed Meldon S. Hollis Jr.,
saying Hollis' credibility had been undermined, but asked him to
remain a board member because he has ``good ideas.''
   Hollis was expected to announce today whether he would accept
the position. The board president said Tuesday he would resign if
the mayor asked.
   Schmoke called Hollis' actions ``a terrible mistake in
judgment.''
   ``My view is that the public can tolerate an official being
wrong on an issue,'' Schmoke said. ``What people generally find
intolerable is an official lying to them.''
   In tape-recorded remarks Monday to a political club, Hollis said
he leaked false information to board members ``to see if they were
lying to me.''
   ``I know who's doing the lying,'' he said. ``I know who it is. I
feed them the lies, then they run out and lie to the press.''
   ``Members of the school board ... tell you they are not
reporting things to the press and ... every time you say something
to 'em, it shows up in the press, only with a spin ... that's far
from accurate,'' he said. ``Then I think that you just do what you
have to do _ you tell them things just to see how it's reported in
the press. Then that way, you can tell who's reporting it to the
press.''
   Hollis said Tuesday he gave out three versions of how candidates
for school superintendent would be interviewed.
   ``I felt justified in taking extraordinary measures,'' he said.
Hollis said leaks were undermining the selection process, because
some candidates threatened to withdraw if their candidacies were
made public.
   Hollis said he had not deliberately misled any board members
``on anything substantial'' and that the story was ``essentially
true.''
   Board member Edward J. Gutman said, ``I think there's something
wrong with the man. The whole thing is getting uglier and uglier.
We are trustees (with) the most important responsibility in the
city.''
   Schmoke, who took office in December and declared that education
would be his first priority, named Hollis board president in his
first week. The mayor replaced Hollis with Joseph Lee Smith, 51, a
board member since 1979.
</TEXT>
