<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0900EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoliceFirepower     09-14 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Firepower,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boston Police Join Trend to Semiautomatic Handguns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston police are switching to semiautomatic
handguns, joining other big city police departments trying to match
the firepower of drug dealers and other criminals.
   Police Commissioner Francis M. Roache announced Monday that 9mm
handguns will replace .38-caliber revolvers as standard-issue
weapons for the force.
   ``The bottom line is the average police officer is going to be
safer, and feel safer, because of these guns,'' said Robert T.
Guiney, president of the union that represents Boston's 1,400
patrol officers.
   The 9mm handgun fires more accurately, reloads more quickly and
carries more bullets, police said.
   Semiautomatic weapons were issued two years ago in Miami. Los
Angeles police will begin providing them in February, and they are
under review in Dallas and Chicago.
   Police in Washington, D.C., were armed this year with 9mm
semiautomatic weapons because of a murder rate double that of last
year. Detroit police and New York City's still use revolvers as
their primary weapons.
   ``We're being outgunned,'' Officer Harry Davis of the Los
Angeles police said Tuesday about the decision to use Beretta
semiautomatic guns next year. ``The criminals, the drug dealers
have more firepower than the police.''
   Boston's police department, the largest in New England with
1,900 members, joins the 1,200-member Massachusetts state police in
switching to the 9mm.
   The 650-member Metropolitan Police Department is making the
switch, and 50 smaller departments in Massachusetts already carry
the weapon.
   ``It's the wave,'' said Gary F. Egan, executive director of the
Massachusetts Criminal Justice Training Council. ``It's gradually
becoming as standard as the .38-caliber revolver once was.''
   The switch has been quicker among the nation's smaller police
and sheriff's departments, the majority of the nation's 19,000 law
enforcement agencies. Smaller departments can make the change more
quickly and cheaply.
   The average 9mm pistol costs about $400. The .38-caliber carries
only one shot in each of six chambers, which must be loaded
individually. Semiautomatic pistols are loaded by inserting a 12-to
17-round magazine into the handle.
   ``You're talking the difference of between 12 seconds to reload
a .38, under the best of conditions, and 2 seconds for a
9-millimeter,'' said Guiney.
   Boston officials said it could take more than a year to complete
the switch. The city must seek bids, select a manufacturer and
train officers to use the weapon.
</TEXT>
