<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeltaPilot     09-14 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta Pilot,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Captain Does Not Provide Clue To Solve Crash Mystery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of Delta Flight 1141 does not hold the
missing puzzle piece that could explain why the plane crashed, a
federal official says.
   Lee Dickinson Jr., a member the National Transportation Safety
Board, said Larry Davis ``does not know why this plane crashed.''
   Davis, one of 94 survivors from the Aug. 31 crash at Dallas-Fort
Worth International Airport that killed 14 people, was released
from Parkland Memorial on Tuesday after talking to NTSB
investigators about two hours.
   The captain was treated for back and facial injuries.
   Dickinson, who briefed the news media by telephone from
Washington on Tuesday, said that Davis seemed to have sharp
recollections of much of the flight but could not help explain why
the plane lost engine power and crashed.
   The captain told investigators that the flight from Jackson,
Miss., to Dallas had been uneventful and that everything seemed
normal again as he waited on the Dallas-Fort Worth taxiway to leave
for Salt Lake City.
   When the plane took off, everything seemed normal until it
climbed into the air, Davis told investigators. Davis heard ``two
loud bangs, or explosions'' but no warning beforehand.
   ``He previously experienced compressor stalls, but nothing like
this,'' Dickinson said.
   Davis, who is on medication but has been taken off morphine,
told investigators he went to full power and simply ``tried to keep
the airplane in the air.''
   One of the last things Davis recalled was that he had failed to
pull the plane out of trouble, Dickinson said. ``He realized they
were not going to make it,'' the investigator said.
   Investigators had hoped Davis might be able to tell them if the
plane's flaps had been set correctly, but he could only tell them
that he remembered they were approved when the crew went through
the preflight checklist, Dickinson said.
   ``We're still very concerned about the position of the flaps,''
Dickinson said.
   One inconsistency the NTSB had been trying to clear up has been
that the cockpit recording captured the crew saying the flaps were
in position for takeoff, but the wreckage showed the flaps in the
wrong position.
   ``He said he does not remember anything in relation to the flap
handle,'' Dickinson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
