<1ST_LINE>u p PM-ReaganHold-for-ReleaseLead a0429   09-14 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan Hold-for-Release Lead, a0429,580</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 1:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits to change category code to `p.' Updates
throughout with Reagan speech</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE GIRARDEAU, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, on a political trip
for his vice president George Bush, declared today that the
national economy is strong and ``what we have seen in the last
eight years is only the beginning.''
   ``We intend to ensure this kind of economic prosperity right
through the '90s and into the next century by guaranteeing the
federal government can never again spend and tax the American
people into another economic nightmare,'' Reagan said.
   The president's remarks were prepared for delivery at a
Republican rally at Southeast Missouri State University in this
Mississippi River shipping center.
   He was to speak later in the day to an expected crowd of 1,000
at a $250-a-plate GOP fund-raising dinner in St. Louis.
   In his Cape Girardeau speech, Reagan said children born today
``will know the brightest future the world has ever seen.''
   ``That bright future is also yours,'' he told his audience. ``It
is your birthright as Americans, and what we have seen in the last
eight years is only the beginning.''
   The national economy has been expanding for more than five years
following the steep recession that marked Reagan's first two years
in office.
   ``Ultimately, the choice before the American people is the
choice between two visions,'' he said. ``It is the choice between
the policies of liberalism or the policies of America's political
mainstream.''
   The president, a former Democrat, said that party's ``liberal
leadership ... has turned a once proud party of hope and
affirmation into one dominated by strident liberalism and
negativism.''
   ``The truth is that when you take a walk down our opposition's
memory lane, it starts to look like a `Nightmare on Elm Street.' If
you want to remember how things really were just a few years back,
think of the year 1979,'' he said.
   ``In that one year, Iran, Nicaragua and Grenada were all lost.
That was the year 1979. Don't we have the right to ask the American
people: If the liberals return to power, what happens in 1989?''
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said in advance of the trip that
Reagan would be giving ``traditional political speeches'' trying to
win support for the Republican ticket of Bush and Dan Quayle.
   The president plans one or two speaking forays each week until
the Nov. 8 election.
   GOP candidates hoping to benefit from the Missouri events
include Gov. John Ashcroft, seeking a second term against
Democratic State Rep. Betty Hearnes of Charleston, who is the wife
of former Gov. Warren Hearnes, and Sen. John Danforth, opposed by
State Sen. Jay Nixon of Hillsboro as he seeks his third term.
   Both Ashcroft and Danforth enjoy comfortable leads in state
public opinion polls.
   Bush, speaking Tuesday in Jefferson City, the state capital,
pledged, ``We will never go back to the grain-embargo days of those
Democrats, Carter and Mondale, and who knows who else.''
   Reagan took Missouri's 11 electoral votes with 51 percent of the
popular vote against then-President Carter in 1980 and swept the
state with 60 percent of the popular vote against Walter Mondale in
1984.
   Records showed that the only incumbent president to visit Cape
Girardeau previously was William Howard Taft on Oct. 26, 1902.
   In St. Louis, the state's most populous city with a metropolitan
area population of more than 2 million, the president was to speak
at an event for the Missouri GOP Victory '88 fund.
</TEXT>
