<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gibraltar-IRA     09-14 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gibraltar-IRA,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Member Made Sudden Movement Before Being Shot, British Soldier
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British soldier said today that he shot an
IRA member because he thought the guerrilla was about to detonate a
car bomb.
   The soldier, one of four Special Air Services soldiers who shot
and killed three unarmed IRA members, testified during an inquest
into the shootings.
   He was identified only as `Soldier A' and was hidden from public
view by a curtain for security reasons.
   The soldier told the inquest he began shooting after ``a sudden
aggressive movement'' by Irish Republican Army member Daniel McCann.
   The British military said it believed the IRA man was about to
carry out a car bombing in this British colony.
   In an intense cross-examination, Patrick McGrory, the attorney
for the families of the three dead men, accused Soldier A of lying.
   ``I put it to you that it (the movement by McCann) didn't
happen. You shot him in the back without any movement whatsoever,''
McGrory said.
   ``There was movement. I'm not blind,'' the soldier responded.
   ``I thought he was going for a button, a switch to detonate the
bomb,'' he said. ``This was my major worry at this stage.''
   The testimony of Soldier A came on the seventh day of the
inquest by Gibraltar Coroner Felix Pizzarello and an 11-man jury
into the March 6 shooting deaths of Sean Savage, 24, Mairead
Farrell, 31, and McCann, 30, by soldiers of the elite
anti-terrorist unit.
   Critics of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
allege the shootings were evidence of an unofficial
``shoot-to-kill'' policy directed against IRA members on missions
against British targets.
   The IRA has acknowledged Savage, Farrell and McCann were members
on active service at the time of their deaths.
   A senior British intelligence officer has testified at the
inquest that the special services men believed the three were
planning to set off a car bomb during a changing of the guard
ceremony set for March 8.
   Neither a car parked in Gibraltar, nor another left on the other
side of the Spanish frontier contained a bomb.
   But Spanish police found a third IRA car loaded with 141 pounds
of Czech-made explosives and a timing device in the nearby resort
city of Marbella two days after the shooting.
   The inquest has no power of prosecution but is to determine
whether the SAS soldiers involved in the shootings acted lawfully.
If the inquest finds they did not, the soldiers could be criminally
charged.
   The seven men who formed the SAS unit that took part in the
operation against the IRA members have only been identified as
``soldiers A through G'' for fear they could become targets of
revenge attacks.
   The IRA is fighting to drive the British out of Northern Ireland
and unite the province with the Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
