<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoliceTrial     09-14 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Trial,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officers Found Guilty in Corruption Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys said they would appeal the conviction of
seven former or current police officers on charges of taking bribes
from bar and restaurant owners to overlook violations and perform
special services.
   ``I think this is a pretty sad day when the Justice Department
can be proud of this kind of prosecution,'' defense attorney Paul
Markham said after the verdict Tuesday, which came on the federal
jury's sixth day of deliberations.
   The defendants were convicted of 55 counts, including
racketeering and extortion. They were accused of accepting more
than $18,000 in bribes.
   ``We take no joy in these verdicts today, but I believe that
they will help to strengthen this department in the long term,''
Police Commissioner Francis M. Roache said.
   Judge A. David Mazzone set sentencing for Oct. 11. The officers
were convicted of two counts of racketeering, each carrying up to
20 years in prison and a $250,000 fine. They also were convicted of
extortion, which carries the same penalty.
   ``I just think it's a sad commentary on the jury system and the
judicial system,'' said Anthony Traini, who represented Kilroe.
   Much of the prosecution's case rested on tape recordings made by
a nightclub manager in which officers discussed payoffs.
   During closing arguments, Special Prosecutor James B. Farmer of
the New England Organized Crime Strike Force said the case was
``about misuse of office for personal gain. It's about each one of
them using their power as Boston police officers to line their own
pockets.''
   Defense attorneys argued that the money accepted from business
owners was nothing more than Christmas and vacation gifts from
people with whom the officers worked closely over several years.
   The four former officers on trial were Thomas J. Connolly,
Francis X. Sheehan, John E. Carey and Peter Boylan. The three
current officers were John F. McCormick, Kenneth J. Nave and
Matthew A. Kilroe.
</TEXT>
