<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MattaTrial     09-14 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Matta Trial,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reputed Drug Lord Convicted of Escape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for a reputed South American
drug lord says he will appeal the man's escape conviction on
grounds he was illegally captured in Honduras, where his arrest
April 5 touched off anti-American riots.
   A federal jury Tuesday convicted Juan Ramon Matta, 43, of
escaping in 1971 from the Federal Prison Camp at Eglin Air Force
Base in the Florida Panhandle. Matta could receive up to five years
in prison at sentencing Oct. 27.
   Defense attorney Martin Stolar said he will challenge the
legality of Matta's arrest at his home in Tegucigalpa, the capital
of Honduras.
   U.S. District Judge Roger Vinson ruled earlier that Matta was
wanted for possible involvement in international drug smuggling and
that previous court cases allowed the government to seize people
outside the United States.
   Matta was wanted for questioning in the 1985 slaying of U.S.
Drug Enforcement Administration Agent Enrique Camarena Salazar in
Mexico.
   No charges have been filed against Matta in that case. But he is
under indictment in three California narcotics cases and one in
Arizona.
   Matta was serving a three-year sentence at Eglin for illegally
entering the United States, fraud and misuse of a visa. He was
accused of slipping out the back door of a chapel at the unfenced,
minimum-security prison during church services.
   Honduran police captured him in a raid by helicopter. Police and
American officials put him on a flight to the Dominican Republic,
and he was flown from there to New York.
   Matta had been living openly in Tegucigalpa since 1986, when he
escaped from a Colombian prison. He had been held on charges
involving the Medellin cartel responsible for 80 percent of the
cocaine brought into the United States.
   His return to the United States touched off rioting in
Tegucigalpa by students, leftists and others that killed several
protesters and ended in the burning of the U.S. consulate.
Demonstrators contended Matta's extradition was barred by the
Honduran constitution.
   Extra security officers were posted for the trial here.
</TEXT>
