<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel     09-14 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspected Collaborator Killed, Eight Palestinians Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians stabbed to death an Arab suspected
of collaborating with the Israelis and dumped his pajama-clad body
on a West Bank street today, police and Arab reports said.
   The death of Adli Thalga, 30, in Nablus, raised to five the
number of alleged collaborators killed in the past 10 days after a
call from Palestinian leaders to ``rid ourselves of collaborators.''
   Also today, eight Palestinians were wounded in the occupied
territories, including a 12-year-old boy shot with a plastic bullet
in Nablus after Israeli troops arrived to close the market area
where Thalga's body was found, the army said.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip town of Khan Yunis, Israeli troops
opened fire on a group of young Palestinians who were throwing
stones in the marketplace, wounding seven of them, the army said.
   The army lifted a curfew from the town of Qalqiliya in the West
Bank after maintaining it for eight consecutive days in the largest
manhunt for Palestinian activists in the uprising.
   The army said about 200 suspected activists were arrested during
the curfew. Telephone lines were cut and residents reported
frequent blackouts and water shortages, Israeli radio said.
   Curfews were in effect today in five West Bank refugee camps and
villages, forcing some 36,000 people to stay indoors.
   Israel radio said masked Palestinian assailants dragged Thalga
out of his house at dawn today and fatally stabbed him. Arabs
living in Nablus said he was a suspected collaborator.
   Seven Palestinians accused of cooperating with Israel have been
killed since the Dec. 8 start of the Palestinian rebellion in the
Israeli-occupied territories. The uprising has claimed the lives of
265 Palestinians and six Israelis.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said today he feared an erosion in
Europe's attitude toward Israel following the European Parliament's
decision to allow PLO leader Yasser Arafat to address the group
Tuesday.
   ``We can't leave the stage open only to PLO propaganda,'' Peres
told reporters at the Ben Gurion International Airport near Tel
Aviv before leaving on a two-day visit to Britain.
   A meeting between Israeli peace crusader Abie Nathan and Arafat
prompted a political storm, with right-wing legislators demanding
Nathan be tried for treason for meeting with an enemy.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said an investigation would be
launched into Nathan's meeting with Arafat in Tunis and called it
``a grave deed and a serious transgression,'' Israel radio reported.
   Nathan, who founded the Voice of Peace radio station in 1973,
presented Arafat with a peace plan calling for mutual recognition
between Israel and the PLO and an end to the Palestinian uprising.
</TEXT>
