<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HoopDispute     09-14 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hoop Dispute,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posh Suburb Puts Moratorium On Basketball Hoop Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeowner who put up a basketball
hoop in his driveway says he won't have to tear it down for now,
because the city has called a time-out on its ban on backboards.
   Bruce Meckler, 33, an attorney, threatened to sue after being
cited for a hoop, backboard and pole in his driveway. He contended
that at least 300 other residences in the city of 30,000 have
front-yard hoops, yet the city has not called foul against them.
   Meckler said City Council on Tuesday night agreed to a
moratorium on enforcement of the ordinance and may repeal it.
   ``We hit a couple of nice jumpers tonight,'' he said. ``If the
city does what I think they ought to do and repeal the ordinance,
it would be a terrific slam dunk.''
   This prosperous suburb north of Chicago is the home of
basketball superstar Michael Jordan of the Chicago Bulls. He lives
about a mile from Meckler.
   ``I think he plans to put a hoop in his house,'' Meckler said.
   Ann Sabol, city buildings coordinator, conceded there are
numerous hoops in Highland Park but said the city calls fouls only
when a neighbor complains.
   Ms. Sabol said, though, that Meckler can fight back with a new
full-court defense known as ``request for a zoning variance.''
</TEXT>
