<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-NuclearTest 1stLd-Writethru a0524 09-14 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Nuclear Test, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0524,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Monitors Soviet Nuclear Test</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with description of blast from
observation post. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``Sophisticated
American...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEMIPALATINSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union today conducted
its first nuclear test explosion to be monitored by U.S. experts.
The blast at a long-secret testing ground shook the earth's surface
and shattered a window.
   The explosion in Soviet Kazakhstan had a force of 100-150
kilotons, the official news agency Tass said, several times more
powerful than the bomb that devastated Hiroshima, Japan, at the end
of World War II.
   The Hagfors Observatory of the Swedish Defense Research
Establishment said it measured the explosion at 50 to 150 kilotons.
   Buried in a hole more than 2,000 feet deep, the nuclear
explosion was felt and heard 2.4 miles away at the forward command
post.
   The ground shook and a low rumble was heard as a reddish cloud
of dust rose above the test site and the earth's surface bucked.
   The blast was not expected to have a noticeable impact at the
observation site about 30 miles from the blast but it shattered a
window in one building.
   ``The radiation situation in the region of the test and beyond
the boundaries of the test site is normal,'' Tass reported after
the blast at 8 a.m. The sparsely populated region is 1,700 miles
east of Moscow.
   Sophisticated American sensors planted just over 10 yards from
the device itself and five seismic sensors each in the United
States and Soviet Union were designed to gauge the force of the
blast.
   The verification techniques were expected to lead the U.S.
Senate to ratify two long-pending treaties limiting the size of
underground blasts.
   ``The goal of the experiment is to bring into practice the most
effective means of control, in order to use them for verifying the
1974 agreement on limiting underground tests of nuclear weapons and
the 1976 agr eement on underground nuclear explosions for peaceful
purposes,'' the Soviet government newspaper Izvestia said.
   ``However, they did not go into effect because the American side
considers the measures of control insufficient,'' it said.
   The Joint Verification Experiment, which included a similar
blast at a U.S. testing range at Pahute Mesa, Nevada, a month ago,
marks a turning point in the two superpowers' nuclear test policies.
   The top-secret experiments always have been off limits to
scientists from the other side, who were forced to rely on data
gathered at great distance to determine the force of underground
explosions.
   Both sides accused the other of exceeding agreed-upon limits,
and the United States balked at ratifying the two treaties from the
1970s until it could monitor explosions close up.
   The Soviets, who have been campaigning for an end to all nuclear
testing, agreed earlier this year to go along with on-site
measurement.
   An American team of up to 40 specialists has been working at the
test site since April to drill a hole parallel to the Soviet test
hole and plant the Cortex hydrodynamic measuring device that the
U.S. government regards as the most sensitive gauge of a nuclear
explosion.
   Giant U.S. Air Force C-5A cargo planes ferried drilling rigs and
monitoring equipment into the sleepy Semipalatinsk airport to
prepare for today's test.
   ``No one thought even a year ago that what is about to happen,
could happen,'' said U.S. team chief C. Paul Robinson told
reporters Monday on his arrival to observe the test.
   He called the experiment ``a real triumph of
confidence-building'' for both sides.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
