<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HarvardResearch     09-14 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvard Research,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Changes Mind on Commercializing Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harvard, in a reversal, plans to set up
companies to help the university make money off professors'
discoveries.
   Eight years ago, Harvard decided against commercial involvement,
saying it could compromise the university's commitment to knowledge.
   Harvard is trying to get corporations to invest up to $35
million that would be used to organize companies around the work of
researchers, mostly those at Harvard Medical School, The Boston
Globe said today.
   If the companies were successful, they would be sold, and
Harvard would get 10 percent of the profits.
   Some academics fear that the profit motive can distort what they
see as their main role _ the search for knowledge _ by introducing
subtle pressures on researchers to spend their time on projects
with commercial potential.
   Harvard President Derek Bok and other university officials said
the plan addresses concerns about mixing business and learning.
``There are few things that matter to me more than trying to strike
this balance,'' he told the Globe.
   The plan's complicated financial arrangement is designed to
allow the university to profit from the work of faculty members
without getting directly involved in commercialization, the
university said.
   Researchers who make potentially profitable discoveries would
not be required to sign up with Harvard's commercial arm if they
preferred to make their own arrangements with private investors.
   In 1980, the university planned to join Harvard biochemist Mark
F. Ptashne in forming a genetic engineering company. Harvard helped
organize the company and find initial investors in return for 15
percent of the company's stock.
   But Bok pulled Harvard out of the arrangement. He said directly
investing in commercializing researchers' work ``could confuse the
university's central commitment to the pursuit of knowledge and
learning.''
   Medical School Dean Daniel C. Tosteson said Tuesday that he was
trying to find a way to augment the school's $350 million research
budget, speed development of useful research and more directly
profit from arrangements that professors were making on their own
with private investors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
