<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Arafat     09-14 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Arafat,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Officials: Arafat's Jewish New Year Wish a `Stunt'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-EEC-Arafat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli officials said today that PLO chief
Yasser Arafat's greeting to Israel on the occasion of the Jewish
New Year was nothing but a stunt and should not be taken seriously.
   Arafat extended wishes for a peaceful new year in the Middle
East at a news conference in Strasbourg, France, where he addressed
socialist members of the European Parliament a day earlier.
   ``To all Israelis and to all Jews, `Shana Tova,' `Shana Tova'''
Arafat said, using the Hebrew expression for ``Happy New Year.''
   ``When I say `Shana Tova,' I mean ... a peaceful new year for
all our children, all our peoples, for the whole of the Middle
East,'' Arafat said, speaking in Arabic with Israeli peace activist
Abie Nathan.
   Arafat also said he was willing to meet with Israeli government
respresentatives at the United Nations.
   Nathan met with Arafat in Tunis this week. He could be
prosecuted when he returns for holding such a meeting, which
violates a 1986 Israeli law banning contacts with terrorist groups.
   Israeli officials dismissed Arafat's greeting as a public
relations ploy. But pro-PLO Palestinians said it showed Arafat
favored a political solution and was seeking peace.
   ``Really it's a stunt,'' a foreign ministry official said.
   ``It's very nice to say `Shana Tova' in front of a group of
journalists, but it would be more constructive if in his speech
yesterday there were some concrete change in policy,'' the official
said on condition of anonymity.
   Addressing Parliament members Tuesday, Arafat repeated his call
for the creation of an independent Palestinian state in the
occupied territories.
   He also reiterated the PLO's insistence that Israel recognize
Palestinian rights to self-determination.
   A spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Arafat's
gesture would not change the right-wing Likud Party's opposition to
holding talks with the PLO. ``We will not be misled by the lip
service of Mr. Arafat and seeming gestures like wishing `Shana
Tova' to our people,'' the spokesman, Yossi Ahimeir said.
   ``We know him very well and we continue in our policy to seek
peace but not to have contacts with Mr. Arafat and his
organization,'' he said. ``With God's help we shall overcome all
our enemies.''
   Israeli leftist Uri Avnery, who has met with Arafat 10 times
since 1982, said the Hebrew greeting showed Arafat sincerely sought
negotiations with Israel.
   ``It is obvious that Arafat is ready to talk to Israelis. Now he
is speaking in a friendly tone towards Israelis and Jews,'' Avnery
said in an interview.
   ``They say new sounds make new music, so now there ... are new
sounds (of Hebrew) in the PLO,'' said Avnery, who first met Arafat
in Beirut during the Israeli invasion of Lebanon.
   Jack Khazmo, the pro-PLO publisher of the Palestinian weekly
Al-Bayader Assiyasi said Arafat's gesture showed he was abandoning
aggression in favor of a political solution in the occupied
territories.
   ``This means the PLO is putting aside the military option. It
means the PLO is willing to knock on the door of peace,'' Khazmo
said.
   As sign of how little credence Israeli officials placed on the
greeting, one government spokesman said: ``You can tell Arafat that
this Israeli official jokingly returns his wishes for peace in the
Middle East.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
