<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen 2ndLd-Writethru a0600 09-14 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0600,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede McALLEN, Texas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with speech given, Bentsen in plane, subbing 3rd graf
and subbing grafs 6-7 Bentsen was ... B-24s.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARLINGEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee
Lloyd Bentsen said today that he and Michael Dukakis were for a
strong defense based on practical weapons and not the ``Buck
Rogers'' dreams of the Reagan admnistration.
   The Texas senator, stumping in his home state where polls show
the Democrats slightly behind, said both he and Dukakis know ``the
first duty of any president is to defend the United States against
all enemies.''
   In a speech at the site of a collection of World War II
airplanes, Bentsen said the Democrats supported the Stealth and B-1
bombers, the cruise missile and other new weapons, including
research and development of strategic defenses.
   ``But ... we are living in the real world _ not some science
fiction movie,'' he said. ``And in the real world, real wars are
still fought with real tanks and guns and fighter planes.''
   ``Under this administration, Buck Rogers has been promoted and
our conventional forces have been neglected,'' allowing the Soviets
to gain in those areas, he said.
   Bentsen spoke in Harlingen where he toured a collection of World
War II military aircraft. He donned a leather flight jacket,
climbed aboard one of the planes and the engine was started up.
   However, he didn't fly any of them. The former B-24 bomber pilot
says he stopped flying after he joined the Senate in 1970. Besides,
the collection does not include any B-24s.
   Bentsen planned to travel this afternoon to an LTV Corp. defense
plant near Dallas for another speech.
   Bentsen's appearances on the defense issue were part of an
overall focus on the topic this week by the Dukakis-Bentsen
campaign. Especially in the South, Dukakis is seen as needing to
convince voters he would have a strong defense policy.
   Vice President George Bush, the Republican nominee, has been
painting Dukakis as a liberal whose opposition to many new weapons
systems, such as the MX and Midgetman missiles, would amount to
unilateral disarmament of the U.S. military.
   Bentsen planned to travel this afternoon to an LTV Corp. defense
plant near Dallas for another speech.
   Bentsen's appearances on the defense issue were part of an
overall focus on the topic this week by the Dukakis-Bentsen
campaign. Especially in the South, Dukakis is seen as needing to
convince voters he would have a strong defense policy.
   Vice President George Bush, the Republican nominee, has been
painting Dukakis as a liberal whose opposition to many new weapons
systems, such as the MX and Midgetman missiles, would amount to
unilateral disarmament of the U.S. military.
   Bentsen planned to keep up the effort as he travels through the
South through Saturday before returning to Washington.
   The campaign schedule included stops in Shreveport, La., and
Memphis, Tenn., on Thursday and in North Carolina and Florida on
Friday and Saturday. The campaign was monitoring the progress of
Hurricane Gilbert in case the storm could threaten any of those
appearances.
</TEXT>
