<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HorsemanCharged     09-14 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Horseman Charged,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ocala Horse Breeder Charged In Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A horse breeder has pleaded innocent
to charges he sold two foals that he claimed were offspring of a
mare who was in fact infertile.
   Celestino DiLibero of Citra was accused in a fraud indictment of
scheming with racing officials to list the foals in the official
thoroughbred registry as offspring of Rare Personality, whose
father won the Preakness in 1971.
   The foals sold for more than $200,000.
   DiLibero entered his innocent plea Tuesday. The others charged
in the indictment, Alfredo Garcia and Ernesto Perez, former
employees of the New York City-based Jockey Club, failed to appear
and warrants were issued for their arrest.
   The three each face up to 20 years in prison and $13,000 in
fines if convicted.
   Ocala horse breeder Jack Winterbotham, who owned Rare
Personality before she was sold to DiLibero, tipped authorities off
to the scheme, said Kathleen O'Malley, an assistant U.S. attorney.
   Winterbotham, who said he sold the mare because she was
infertile, attended an auction in Lexington, Ky., in 1983 and was
surprised to see two foals, supposedly from Rare Personality, on
the auction block. They sold for $140,000 and $75,000.
   Although the parents of Rare Personality were well-known race
horses, the mare born in 1973 never raced. She was the offspring of
the 1971 Preakness winner, Personality, and the mare Rare Treat, a
16-time first-place winner.
</TEXT>
