<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1147EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AmnestyConcert     09-14 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty Concert,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Springsteen Asks 40,000 Costa Ricans To Fight For Human Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 40,000 enthusiastic rock fans
braved heavy rains to cheer Bruce Springsteen and other top stars
as they appealed for human rights in a seven-hour concert.
   Thousands of umbrellas swayed to the music in San Jose's
National Stadium in the first Latin American stop on the ``Human
Rights, Now!'' tour organized by the London-based Amnesty
International.
   ``I ask you to join me and my friends to fight for the respect
of human rights around the world,'' Springsteen, using a
Spanish-language interpreter, said in the middle of his set.
   ``Si!,'' the crowd bellowed in response.
   Also performing were Sting, Tracy Chapman and Youssou N'Dour.
   Authorities reported no major disturbances during the marathon
concert. The Red Cross said it treated two women for slight
injuries, and a raucous group that did not attend the show stoned
an ambulance outside the stadium.
   About 300 Panamanian concert-goers arrived in chartered buses
for the show and chanted briefly against Panama's de facto ruler,
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, who commands that country's army.
   Barry Roberts, chief organizer of the San Jose concert, said 150
private detectives were hired to monitor the crowd.
   The tour began Sept. 2 at London's Wembley stadium and later
appeareAmerican Bank of New York.
   c-commercial rate, f-financial rate, y-official rate, z-floating
rate, r-revised.
