<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-FiresRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0583 09-14 0848</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fires Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0583,0870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weather Helps Firefighters Battle Blazes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with Hodel's comments on fire
policy, Sierra fire comment, Yellowstone weather. Picks up 11th
graf pvs, `The fires ...' SUBS 23-24th grafs pvs, `At Glacier...'
to UPDATE Montana fire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN W. OATIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters battling Western blazes got a helping hand from
weather so cool and wet that a crew was pulled out of the
wilderness near Yellowstone National Park for fear they'd be
trapped by snow.
   ``Things are real calm,'' said park spokesman Greg Kroll.
``We've had some pretty good precipitation.''
   Meanwhile, Interior Secretary Donald Hodel said today the
government's ``let it burn'' forest fire policy will be revised
before next year's fire season.
   To maintain now that the 16-year-old policy is sound ``just
doesn't make sense,'' he said in an interview on NBC's ``Today''
show.
   ``I am confident that before the next fire season, we'll have a
revised policy in place which will take into account these kinds of
conditions,'' Hodel said.
   Fires burned in California, Utah, Oregon, Idaho, Montana, Alaska
and Washington state as the worst fire season in 30 years continued.
   Calmer 5-7 mph winds, lower temperatures and higher humidity
were a blessing to California's Gold Rush country, where a fire has
burned 52 square miles since Sunday and destroyed 97 homes and 60
other buildings. Firefighters had surrounded 90 percent of the
blaze today.
   The thousands of residents evacuated Sunday or Monday were
allowed to return to their homes.
   ``Very little happened last night. The fire really laid down. It
was even hard to find embers in some regions,'' overnight fire
operations chief Bill Holmes said today.
   About 30,000 firefighters battled 32 fires in eight Western
states, said White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater. President
Reagan received a briefing Tuesday from a Cabinet-level team that
toured Yellowstone.
   As of Tuesday, wildfires had charred 4.1 million acres, an area
larger than Connecticut, according to the Boise Interagency Fire
Center, which coordinates firefighting in the West.
   Hodel said today that officials have enough resources. ``What we
need now is some continued help from the weather,'' he said.
   ``If we continue to get the weather break, they're actually on
the fire line right now directly fighting the fire, which is
something they weren't able to do as long as it was so hot, dry and
windy,'' Hodel said.
   At Yellowstone, clouds that have covered the park since Saturday
began to lift today and temperatures reached only 40 degrees, but
officials expected a warming trend that would take temperatures to
the 70s, said park spokesman Steve Iobst.
   ``The fires are still a threat, we are not out of it yet,'' said
fire information officer Sonya Capek.
   Firefighters used the break to strengthen lines. Meanwhile,
about 550 Marines from Camp Pendleton, Calif., the first of 1,200
sent to reinforce the 7,200 firefighters in the park, arrived in
West Yellowstone, Mont.
   The weather was so cool officials began distributing
cold-weather gear donated by residents of Wyoming communities. Few
firefighters had been prepared for the cold and wet.
   Fires have blackened 939,270 acres of the 2.2 million-acre park.
Blazes in national forests and parks surrounding Yellowstone in
Wyoming, Montana and Idaho bring the total to 1.4 million acres.
   In the Bridger-Teton National Forest southeast of the park, a
38,507-acre fire was declared contained and a 225,500-acre complex
of fires was 85 percent contained with full containment expected by
Thursday.
   North of the park, a 93,000-acre fire that threatened Cooke City
and Silver Gate was declared 90 percent contained with complete
containment expected by Saturday.
   A crew was pulled out of the Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness north
of the park, said fire information officer Ted Coffman.
   ``We were afraid if we put a crew in there we might not be able
to get them out if it snowed,'' Coffman said.
   At Glacier National Park in Montana near the Canadian border,
more than 900 firefighters joined by a Canadian ``hot-shot'' crew
had a 31,500-acre blaze 30 percent contained. The fire has
destroyed 21 homes, killed one firefighter and injured six others.
   ``They're expecting hot temperatures up there (in Glacier)
today, up into the mid-80s,'' said fire information officer Les
Mahugh. ``They feel there will be increased fire activity because
of the higher temperatures.''
   Firefighters were to be joined today by 1,400 Army soldiers from
Fort Lewis, Wash.
   Elsewhere in Montana, 1,100 firefighters attacked a 247,000-acre
fire north of Helena, crews demobilized from a fire in the far
northwest part of the state and rehabilitation work began near
Cooke City and Silver Gate north of Yellowstone.
   Controversy has surrounded the Yellowstone fires because of the
Park Service policy of not fighting most naturally-caused blazes.
   Reagan said Tuesday that he had not been aware of the policy but
that Hodel told him it was being rescinded.
   Colorado Gov. Roy Romer said Democratic presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis would join him, Wyoming Gov. Mike Sullivan, Montana
Gov. Ted Schwinden and Idaho Gov. Cecil Andrus on Thursday to
survey fire damage in Yellowstone and discuss policy.
</TEXT>
