<1ST_LINE>u i PM-OlympicProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0555 09-14 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Olympic Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0555,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Hurl Firebombs At Olympic Torch</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with police saying 15 officers injured,
other details. ADDS byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students yelling anti-Olympic
slogans hurled firebombs today at runners carrying the Olympic
torch while riot police battled to disperse the protesters.
   Police said 16 policemen were injured in the fighting at
Kyungwon University on the southern outskirts of Seoul after
students hurled about 50 firebombs at the Olympic torch procession.
   Some of the bombs exploded about 10 yards from the runner
carrying the Olympic torch, eyewitnesses said. None of the runners
or other escorts of the Olympic flame was hit and the procession
did not halt as it passed by the school in a semi-rural area, the
witnesses said.
   Radical students staged peaceful anti-Olympic protests today at
several colleges in Seoul. Protesters burned the American flag and
shouted ``Yankee go home.''
   About 200 students took part in a ``Stop the Olympic Torch
Rally'' at Kyungwon to block the torch as it passed on the road in
front of the school. Faculty members tried unsuccessfully to stop
the protest.
   ``Oppose the dictatorial Olympics,'' students yelled.
   Riot police moved in to block the school's main gate to stop the
students from marching out onto the road. But students rushed to
the school wall and hurled firebombs at the torch procession,
eyewitnesses said.
   Police then stormed onto the campus and troopers and students
battled with their fists, police said. Many of the injured police
were hit by firebombs, they said.
   Police officials would not say if there had been any arrests or
if any students had been injured.
   The Seoul Olympic Organizing Committee said it was unaware of
any attack.
   The torch with the Olympic flame from Greece is due to arrive in
Seoul Saturday to open the Summer Olympic Games. It was being
carried to the western port of Inchon today when the attack took
place.
   Radical students have staged scattered demonstrations against
the Olympics during the past week and battled riot police in
clashes at some Seoul campuses. The demonstrations have been small
and have failed to attract public support.
   The great majority of South Koreans, including most students,
want the Games to be a success.
   The students are demanding the Olympics be shared with communist
North Korea to promote reunification of the divided Korean
peninsula. They also contend the Games are cementing authoritarian
rule in South Korea.
   ``The Olympics are making the rich people richer, the poor
people poorer,'' said a statement today by radical students.
   The Olympic flame is being carried across South Korea by more
than 1,000 torchbearers who each carry it for about half a mile
while being escorted by up to 12 other runners. Police and security
agents have been guarding the procession.
   North Korea has said it will boycott the Olympics because its
demand to co-host the Games was turned down. The International
Olympic Committee has said the Olympics are awarded only to a
single city.
   The two Koreas are bitter rivals and both claim to be the sole
legitimate government on the peninsula. South Korea fears the North
may try to disrupt the Olympics.
   The United States has about 42,000 troops based in the South
under a mutual defense treaty.
</TEXT>
