<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SierraFire 2ndLd-Writethru a0585 09-14 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sierra Fire, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0585,0711</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Officials Prepare To Send Some Firefighters Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with comment from briefing.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``As far ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SC1,SC2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE WILDWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands returned to their homes
as fire officials, heartened by a day of favorable weather, lifted
evacuation orders and reopened all major highways where a fire
ravaged Gold Rush country.
   Calmer winds, lower temperatures and higher humidity Tuesday and
today helped crews as they bulldozed lines around more than 90
percent of the 3-day-old blaze, which gutted nearly 100 homes and
threatened as many as 5,000.
   ``The fire really laid down. It was even hard to find embers in
some regions,'' overnight fire operations chief Bill Holmes said
today.
   ``As far as I know, we have allowed everyone who wants to return
home to do so,'' state Department of Forestry spokesman Steve
Iverson said Tuesday.
   But some of the 8,000 residents evacuated had little or nothing
to return to in the charred foothills of the Sierra Nevada
northeast of Sacramento.
   Rusty Cline, 51, of the tiny community of Rough and Ready was
part of a stream of refugees at a high school evacuation center
Tuesday, which American Red Cross worker Elizabeth Quirk dubbed
``the morning of tears.''
   ``The fire raced in on us. We ran for the car, but it beat us
there,'' said Cline, weeping. ``I couldn't get my dog in the car.
She was too scared.'' Her dog's fate was unknown.
   Preliminary damage estimates were set at about $9 million, but
authorities expected the figure to climb.
   Officials also prepared today to begin relieving some of the
2,800 firefighters who have battled the fire, which consumed more
than 52 square miles of timber and brush or 33,500 acres since it
was started Sunday.
   ``If it holds through the night, we'll consider releasing some
people,'' said Iverson, the planning chief for the firefighting
force.
   Full containment of the fire was expected by Thursday night,
said Jack Placchi, a U.S. Forestry Service spokesman.
   The fire, which apparently was started by a transient burning a
piece of toilet paper, was one of several blackening Northern
California and the drought-parched West, including fires that have
charred nearly 1 million acres of Yellowstone National Park.
   The blaze had been whipped by 30-plus mph gusts through Monday.
But on Tuesday, winds were a moderate 5 to 7 mph while temperatures
were about 10 degrees lower and the humidity level nearly double,
Iverson said.
   ``The fire today cooperated quite a bit,'' he said.
   The one drawback to the weather was an air inversion that forced
the grounding of eight aerial tankers, which had dropped more than
2,000 tons of fire retardant on the blaze Sunday and Monday.
   The swift-moving blaze had threatened 4,000 to 5,000 structures,
but only 97 homes and 60 other buildings had burned.
   Iverson said no additional homes were threatened as of Tuesday
night. But homes in unburned pockets within fire lines could be
threatened if winds shifted or pick up, he added.
   ``There's no nice clear fire line. It's a checkerboard,'' he
said.
   Fire officials reopened state highways 20 between Grass Valley
and Marysville and 49 north of Nevada City. Some restrictions,
however, remained on secondary roads where mop-up operations
continued.
   Flames Tuesday also scorched grasslands in the deserted eastern
sector of Beale Air Force Base, home for some of the nation's most
sophisticated spy planes. But the fire was stopped more than four
miles from the edge of the main part of the base, firefighters said.
   ``It's all out. It's history. There are no problems there,''
said Bill Holmes, a state forestry spokesman.
   The drought, which increased the amount of tinder-dry grass and
bush, created a dangerous and unpredictable condition for
firefighters and residents along with the winds and low humidity.
   But no firefighter suffered a serious injury, Iverson said.
Seven had been treated at hospitals for minor burns and 500 had
checked into first aid stations with cuts, scrapes and sprains, he
said.
   There were no reports of injuries among those evacuated, Iverson
said.
</TEXT>
