<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1236EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon     09-14 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Closes Only Beirut Crossing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lebanese army today closed the only
crossing between Beirut's Christian and Moslem sectors after Shiite
Moslem militiamen took to the streets in west Beirut for the first
time in 17 months.
   The actions came a day after the country's Shiite-Moslem defense
minister was briefly held hostage by Christian militiamen forces,
heightening tensions between Christians and Moslems deadlocked over
the election of a new president.
   The political wrangling has raised fears that fighting will
renew Lebanon's 13-year-old civil war.
   A statement said army commander Gen. Michel Aoun issued the
order to close the mid-city Museum crossing. Only travelers on
their way to or from the airport were exempt.
   A military source said the militiamen belonging to the Amal
organization, headed by Justice Minister Nabih Berri, took up
positions near the crossing and set up a traffic checkpoint.
   ``The command decided to close the crossing in light of Amal's
suspicious move to avoid jeopardizing the lives of civilians,''
said the source, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said Amal's move could result in reciprocal deployment by
militias on the Christian side and lead to clashes.
   Amal's deployment in the Barbir district was the first by the
Syrian-backed militia in west Beirut since the Syrians moved in to
end three years of militia anarchy in February 1987.
   Christian militiamen held Defense Minister Adel Osseiran, a
Shiite, for three hours in east Beirut on Tuesday, police said. The
militiamen demanded the release of Farid Serhal, a Christian
parliamentarian, who they say is held in the Moslem sector for the
past week.
   But Osseiran was released after the army threatened to crack
down.
   Serhal was one of the Christian deputies who boycotted a
parliamentary session to elect a new president Aug. 18.
Syrian-backed candidate Suleiman Franjieh, who was president from
1970 to 1976, was the only serious runner and there were not enough
legislators for a quorum.
   Franjieh's followers have accused the right-wing Christian
Lebanese Forces militia, which is sympathetic to Israel, of
forcibly preventing deputies from attending the session to block
Franjieh's election.
   A statement attributed to Serhal said he was to meet the Sunni
Moslem acting Prime Minister, Salim Hoss, and hold a news
conference in west Beirut on Wednesday. He did not appear.
   Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini, a Shiite Moslem, has set
Sept. 22 as a new date for the election, one day before the
six-year term of President Amin Gemayel expires.
   An unwritten national covenant dating to Lebanon's independence
from France in 1943 stipulates the president must be Maronite
Christian, the prime minister a Sunni Moslem and the house speaker
a Shiite.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
