<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Brezhnev 1stLd-Writethru a0629 09-14 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Brezhnev, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brezhnev Grandson Says Campaign Against Ex-Leader Has Gone Too Far</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to fix typo in Yuri Brezhnev's name and
include Leonid Brezhnev's titles. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``I'm 27...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leonid I. Brezhnev's grandson complained in an
article published today that criticism of the late Soviet leader
had turned into a smear campaign.
   Andrei Brezhnev said his family should not be blamed for the
mistakes made by the late Soviet leader.
   The full-page article in the weekly Moscow News was a rare
public defense of the man who served as Communist Party chairman
and president in the Soviet Union from 1964 until his death in 1982.
   Under Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the official press
carries almost daily articles and letters criticizing Brezhnev for
everything from the slump in the economy to his large collection of
medals.
   Brezhnev's son-in-law, Yuri Churbanov, is on trial in Moscow on
charges of bribe-taking and abuse of office as a top Interior
Ministry official under Brezhnev.
   Andrei Brezhnev said the disgrace of his grandfather was hurting
him. He is the son of Yuri Brezhnev.
   ``I'm 27 years old, and my independent life is only beginning,
but I already feel that my surname ever more frequently has become
a stumbling block in the most varied situations,'' the younger
Brezhnev wrote. ``I am just like everyone, but many don't want to
see anything in me except my surname.''
   Brezhnev's grandson said he agreed with much of the criticism
appearing now in the Soviet press of the former Soviet president
and Communist Party chief, but that relatives should not share the
blame.
   He recalled that under Soviet dictator Josef Stalin, relatives
were arrested or shot simply because of their family ties with
criminals.
   ``If you read now about the crimes of the 1930s, we remember the
words: `A son should not answer for his father,' then why do we
forget them when speaking about the present day?''
   Andrei Brezhnev also said some criticism was unjustified because
it blamed his grandfather for mistakes made by aides.
   Legends and rumors arose about Brezhnev's family, he said,
because ``the private life of our leaders, their family
irregularities and problems remain outside the direct attention of
society, outside `glasnost.'''
   Glasnost, Gorbachev's policy of openness, has generally not been
extended to reporting on the inner workings of the top government
and party organizations or the personal lives of leaders.
   ``First and foremost Brezhnev himself became a victim of the
absence of glasnost,'' Andrei Brezhnev said.
   He said his aunt, Brezhnev's daughter Galina, helped bring down
the family name because she was ``uncontrollable'' and didn't
respect the law. She is married to Churbanov.
   In its edition last week, Moscow News published an article by
historian Roy Medvedev saying that Brezhnev was revived from
``clinical death'' in 1976. However, the article said the leader
was left senile and so weakened that he had difficulty performing
simply protocol duties for the last six years of his rule.
   Medvedev also said that politically, Brezhnev ``didn't so much
move ahead himself as he was moved ahead by others.'' Medvedev also
criticized Brezhnev as a poor speaker and a vain, weak man.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880914-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   09-14 0854</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0894</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   Sept. 9
   Las Cruces (N.M.) Sun-News on Pentagon spending:
   The Pentagon still can't seem to get a handle on how much money
to spend.
   It seems that some defense contractors have been hiding
information that would bring down prices on weapons purchased by
the Pentagon. As a result, the Pentagon has spent millions of
dollars more than it needed to for the weapons.
   Officials at the Pentagon have had some success halting
overpricing. But contractors still aren't complying with a 1962 law
requiring contractors to disclose relevant information about
contracts.
   But the contractors aren't entirely to blame. It boils down to a
case of mismanagement within the Pentagon.
   It's always easier to be easy with someone else's money _ in
this case ours. Despite the improvements and efforts by Pentagon
officials to clean up the contracts, more improvements obviously
are needed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 12
   The Daily Astorian, Astoria, Ore., on ``the imperial Congress'':
   The most dangerous trend in our government is the entrenchment
of the House of Representatives. We have allowed the creation of a
permanent class of lawmakers. ...
   It is well understood in the political community ... that a
House member who gets past his first re-election (has) ... got a
seat in Congress for life. And at the end of the line, he will get
a pension on the order of $76,000 per year. And free health care.
...
   It does the country no good to have a defeat-proof Congress. Is
there any mystery why the boys and girls on Capitol Hill have
ceased to make substantial law and pass only humongous, unwieldy
statutes that contain all sorts of surprises?
   The Senate used to be known as the most exclusive club in the
world. But that title clearly now belongs to the House of
Representatives.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 7
   The State, Columbia, S.C., on political prisoners and hostages:
   Again a rumor has surfaced that Swedish diplomat Raoul
Wallenberg is alive and being held in a Soviet prison camp. ...
   Wallenberg, who saved thousands of Jews from the Nazis during
World War II, disappeared in the Soviet prison system after the
war. The Soviet government has maintained that he died of a heart
attack in 1947 at the age of 35.
   But over the years, numerous witnesses have reported that he was
still alive. Most recently, Swedish businessman and novelist Kenne
Fant said he has been researching the Wallenberg case and has
information that he was alive in December 1986.
   But Wallenberg is only one example. Thousands of other political
prisoners and hostages are confined in Soviet gulags, Central and
South American jails and Middle East terrorist hideouts.
   It is far too easy, after 40-odd years, to forget about the
likes of Raoul Wallenberg. ...
   But this country and other free nations cannot afford to forget
these men and women _ prisoners, not for their deeds, but for their
beliefs. They have no one else to speak and work for their release.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 7
   The Central Maine Morning Sentinel, Waterville, Maine, on the
Pledge of Allegiance as a campaign issue:
   Vice President George Bush has a real crowd pleaser in his flag
pledge speech, but as an issue, the Pledge of Allegiance is a
spurious one.
   Indeed, by the time the November election date rolls around it
largely will be forgetten.
   When they look beyond the histrionics, voters will find that it
isn't a question of whether George Bush or Michael Dukakis is the
more patriotic. Both have served their country, and the patriotism
of neither is in doubt. ...
   Laws or no laws, court decisions or no court decisions, 99
percent of the American people proudly recite the Pledge of
Allegiance. ...
   Forcing the other one percent to say it against their will
wouldn't make them patriotic.
   There are plenty of real issues for Vice President Bush and Gov.
Dukakis to talk about and debate. Let's get on with them.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 12
   The (Baltimore) Sun on the presidential campaign:
   With two months to go until election day, George Bush has jumped
into a lead over Michael Dukakis that dismays Democrats and has
Republicans talking of another sweep.
   With voters so volatile, all of this could change _ especially
in the crucial fortnight between the end of the World Series and
Nov. 8. ...
   Dukakis prides himself on being a marathoner who likes to stay
in stride and not be deflected off path. His aides are counting on
Bush gaffes and Dan Quayle's liabilities to turn the polls around.
...
   What marathoner Dukakis seems not to realize is that he is now
in a 60-day dash. His proclaimed coolness on TV may serve him well
in the debates, but Bush's hot one-liners, served up daily against
photogenic backdrops, are what are being run and re-run on nightly
news shows. ...
   It may be too early for Dukakis to sprint, but he had better
step up his pace and run a smarter race if he wants to stay
competitive.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
