<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   09-14 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0806</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: stay competitive.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 9
   Fairmont (Minn.) Sentinel on making English the official U.S.
language:
   A recent report by the Center for Immigration Studies indicates
that a record number of immigrants will be coming to America in
this decade.
   This latest report estimates that between 1981-1990, more than
10 million immigrants will have crossed America's shores.
   This will mark only the second time in one decade that the
number of new arrivals has surpassed 8 million since 1820, when the
government began keeping such records.
   The recent tidal wave of immigrants ... has given additional
impetus to a growing national movement to make English the official
language of our country.
   So far, 16 states have passed legislation designating English as
the official language; three other states will have the issue on
the ballot in November. We support this effort.
   If America is to remain a melting pot for people from all the
nations, then English should be the only language, for documents,
ballots and all official communications.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 13
   Springfield (Mo.) News-Leader on the woodland firefighting
policy:
   As the dusty ashes of forest fires in Yellowstone National Park
descend on the Ozarks like a mist, the debate is heating up over
what went wrong.
   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel promises an end to the ``let it
burn'' policies that have guided the National Park Service since
1972.
   The ``let it burn'' policy was intended to clear out fallen
timber and revive forests.
   Instead, 883,000 acres have been lost in Yellowstone alone.
   This is one time when both the environmentalists and the federal
government had better come up with a better idea.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 12
   Wellington (Kan.) Daily News on gullible collectors:
   Antiques, coins, fine art, handicrafts and stamps are among the
collectibles that are ``good investments'' only for those who have
studied and know their markets.
   Those who don't, depending instead on stories of spectacular
prices at auctions and superficial overviews, are easy prey for
promoters eager to exploit their desire for easy wealth.
   For example, the Anthony dollar is being promoted as a ``worthy
family heirloom'' at more than $150 a set of 12.
   In fact, Anthony dollars are worth $1. More than half a million
of these coins, rejected by the public, lie uncirculated in
government vaults.
   Better Business Bureaus and trade organizations try to protect
the unsophisticated, but the greedy and the gullible keep biting,
looking to get rich quick.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 12
   Los Angeles Herald Examiner on stopping gang violence:
   For the estimated 70,000 gangsters, mostly young men and boys
under 20, mostly inhabitants of the region's poorer sections, the
gang is a clan _ a supplement to, or a replacement for, family
ties. ...
   Most hard-core gang members are unskilled school dropouts. ...
Most live in poor, racially segregated neighborhoods, where wages
are low and unemployment, drug addiction and crime are high. ...
   The gang offers what they can get nowhere else: protection and
complete acceptance, no diploma required. ...
   Firepower and ruthlessness have increased. Once gangs used
chains, stilettos and the occasional zip gun or revolver to fight
rivals or abet crimes. Today, legal and illegal rapid-fire pistols
and rifles of immense force have become the weapons of choice.
   Gang killings were once rare. From the 1940s until 1977, there
were only about 100 for all of Los Angeles. Since then, there have
been more than 3,100. ...
   Children must ... be the prime target of the community's effort
to rid Los Angeles of gang violence. Simply put, we must cut gangs
off from the flow of new soldiers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 9
   Yakima (Wash.) Herald-Republic on school curricula:
   William Bennett may be a lame duck, having decided to depart his
post in several weeks, but the Reagan administration's outspoken
education secretary is without peer in diagnosing what ails the
public schools.
   In his final report to the nation, Bennett challenged grade
school educators to upgrade their curricula and improve the
preparation of students entering high school and college.
   Although the secretary praised elementary schools for improving
their class offerings, nonetheless he urged educators to expose
their students to much stronger doses of English, math, science,
history, geography, fine arts and, yes, foreign languages in the
nation's 81,000 elementary and junior high schools. ...
   Bill Bennett is detested by many in the educational
establishment for his uncompromising pursuit of classroom
excellence.
   Fortunately, his common sense recommendations are supported by
most Americans who understand the time has come after years of
mediocrity for higher academic standards. The very future of the
United States depends upon it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
