<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   09-14 0870</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0907</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: upon it.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 12
   The Syracuse (N.Y.) Post Standard and Herald Journal of the
Yonkers desegregation case:
   It's time for Yonkers to get on with its life. The wounds from
the city's bitter battle over court-ordered housing desegregation
will take some time to heal, but no one will be served by keeping
them open out of spite. ...
   Last month, after the council balked at an agreement to build
200 units of low-income housing and 800 subsidized middle-income
units, (U.S. District Court Judge Leonard Sand) imposed fines that
threatened to bankrupt the city.
   On Saturday (Sept. 10), two members of the city council changed
their votes on the controversial housing plan in the face of $1
million-a-day fines and the prospect of laying off city workers.
That made the vote 5-2 in favor of the proposal. ...
   Now that the ugly fight is over, let us hope the people of the
city can work together to make the housing plan succeed _ that
Yonkers can be added to the growing list of communities where
people have found that black and white can live side-by-side and
enrich the quality of life for both.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 7
   Saginaw (Mich.) News on the media and Dan Quayle:
   News organizations are reporting news about news organizations,
and commenting on it, more than ever.
   The introspection reached a peak when the Dan Quayle story
became two stories _ one focusing on his decision to join the
National Guard rather than sign up for the Vietnam War, the other
examining whether or not reporters went ``too far'' in probing the
Republican nominee for vice president. ...
   The public relies on the media for information, and citizens
should be privy to the decision-making process involved in
publishing a newspaper or preparing a broadcast. ...
   (But) news organizations can eliminate the need for a
story-by-story media catharsis if they stress a consistent,
back-to-basics approach that relies on the fundamental concepts of
journalism. ...
   If reporters keep their opinions to themselves and show less
arrogance, they can cover the important stories _ and Quayle's
background indeed is important _ without so much public backlash.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 9
   The Daily Journal, Elizabeth, N.J., on Dan Quayle:
   It's not that (Sen. Dan Quayle) chose to avoid combat by joining
a stateside National Guard unit. It's not even the fact that he
used family pressures to get him to the front of the enlistment
line.
   It's the senator's subsequent hawkish support of the military
and his showy patriotism that make him suspect.
   The young senator might have recovered lost respect had he
responded to the embarrassment with grace.
   Instead he was flippant. ``If I had known then I would be
running for the vice presidency now, I certainly would have chosen
a different course,'' he said at one point.
   To a convention breakfast audience, he offered a mock salute and
his National Guard name, rank and serial number in attempt to laugh
the whole thing off.
   Is a man who reacts so awkwardly to what is, essentially, a
less-than-major crisis, the man we would trust in a time of
national emergency?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 8
   The Commercial Appeal, Memphis, Tenn., on mail solicitation:
   You take the official-looking envelope from the mailbox and your
heart skips a beat. It's from the Internal Revenue Service and
surely couldn't be good news.
   Look again. It's from the Internal Review Service, which is not
a government agency. It's nothing more than a company looking to
make a buck by wrapping its services in government-like mailings.
   Your reaction is similar to that by elderly citizens who learn
the official-sounding Social Security Protection Bureau is not the
Social Security Administration.
   Rep. Frank McCloskey (D-Ind.) says such firms often solicit
funds for services that are available free from the federal
government.
   Now, a bill sponsored by McCloskey has passed the House. It
would require warning labels on such envelopes, making it clear
that the mailings do not contain government documents. ...
   Any company that would prey on the unsuspecting should be made
to come clean, on the outside of the envelope.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 9
   The Reporter, Fond du Lac, Wis., on the NFL drug policy:
   The National Football League's substance abuse policy is
continuing to take its toll and, frankly, we're glad to see it.
   Images created by drug-popping role-model NFL superstars are not
the ones most parents want their children to see. The league's
moves to stop drug abuse and to show that it has undesirable
consequences are laudable. ...
   This is the third year of the NFL's drug testing program. Teams
of first-time offenders are notified by the league's drug office.
Second-time offenders draw minimums of 30-day suspensions and
third-timers can be banished for life although they can petition
for readmission after a year.
   To players drawing the salaries paid in the NFL today, even a
30-day suspension can be expensive. A year can be devastating.
   But it should be. These overpriced players who so eagerly seek
professional help in negotiating their salaries could use a little
help in spending them as well.
   A year back at more mundane earning levels goes a long way
toward restoring reality to their lives.
</TEXT>
