<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     09-14 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Demand Interim Government; Strikes Lead To Shortages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100,000 shouting protesters
Wednesday told leaders of the authoritarian government to resign or
die and demanded that an interim administration lead Burma back to
democracy.
   The student-led protesters flooded all main Rangoon streets to
reject the ruling Burma Socialist Program Party and its 26 years of
repression and ruinous economic policies. They rejected President
Maung Maung's plan for multiparty elections.
   ``Step down fascist BSPP government!'' and ``Give us an interim
government!'' shouted the demonstrators, who included Buddhist
monks and government employees.
   ``You run or we will kill you!'' the marchers shouted, thrusting
fists in the air. ``If they don't fall, make them fall!'' they
chanted.
   All shops and offices were closed Wednesday. Crowd estimates
ranged from 100,000 to 1 million.
   State-run Radio Rangoon urged workers to return to their jobs.
Many employees nationwide struck Aug. 8 to demand democracy, and
food and other commodities have since been in increasingly short
supply.
   Strikes shut down the country's two oil refineries making fuel
scarce and forcing the army to use reserve stocks. Foreign
embassies have turned to the black market and are paying $16 for a
gallon of gasoline, sources said.
   A Western diplomat in Rangoon said the marchers, accompanied by
marching bands, included about 100 uniformed policemen and pilots
and stewardesses whose pro-democracy strikes have grounded all
commercial flights since last week.
   The diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, said several
thousand demonstrators gathered outside the U.S. Embassy, a
favorite rallying place, and listened to strident speeches by
protest leaders.
   Diplomats said they had no indication the authorities would
yield to demands for an interim government.
   Demonstrations and pro-democracy strikes also continued in major
towns nationwide, including Mandalay, Taunggyi, Moulmein and
Bassein, but details were not available. Western diplomats have
said protesters have taken control of the administrations of about
40 towns.
   After weeks of demonstrations, Maung Maung's government
announced last weekend that it would end one-party rule and hold
the first multiparty elections since 1960 as early as late October.
   But demonstrations have continued. On Tuesday, opposition
leaders told the five-member election commission they would accept
no polling organized by the current government.
   Aung San Suu Kyi, former Brigadier General Aung Gyi and former
Defense Minister Tin Oo declared they would not support or
participate in government-organized elections and reiterated their
demand for an interim government.
   They also complained that holding the elections in three months
or less would be unfair because the opposition would not have time
to form parties and raise funds, state-run Radio Rangoon reported.
   On Monday the three issued their first joint statement, a letter
to Maung Maung calling for an interim government.
   The Western diplomat said the opposition leaders were expected
to announce Thursday the names of people they want in the
transition government.
   ``There has not been a groundswell of support for any one
opposition leader as there was in the Philippines when people were
shouting, `Cory, Cory,''' the diplomat said, speaking anonymously.
He was referring to the February 1986 popular uprising that swept
President Corazon Aquino to power.
   ``So far the students have been concentrating on scrutinizing
the abuses of the regime and not the relative merits of the
different opposition leaders,'' he said.
   Burma's last multiparty elections, on Feb. 6, 1960, swept former
Prime Minister U Nu to power over an army-backed party. He was
toppled in the 1962 coup led by Ne Win, who crushed dissent and
pursued rigid socialist policies that made resource-rich Burma into
one of the world's poorest nations.
   Massive protests began after Ne Win resigned July 23 and the
party named hardliner Sein Lwin his successor. Sein Lwin resigned
after rioting in which at least 112 people died in Rangoon, and on
Aug. 19, Maung Maung became Burma's first civilian leader since Nu.
</TEXT>
