<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     09-14 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>India Announces Cease-Fire To Allow Rebels to Surrender</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India on Wednesday announced a five-day
ceasefire in Sri Lanka to allow Tamil rebels fighting for an
independent homeland to surrender their arms and take part in local
elections.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Aftab Seth made the announcement to
reporters in a government statement. The cease-fire was to begin at
7 a.m. Thursday.
   India has stationed an estimated 47,000 troops in Sri Lanka's
northern and eastern provinces to enforce an accord aimed at ending
the Tamils' 5-year-old separatist war with the Sinhalese-dominated
government. The campaign has claimed at least 8,500 lives.
   The cease-fire comes five days after the merger of the two
Tamil-dominated provinces and an announcement by the Colombo
government that the election of a combined provincial council would
be held soon. A date for the polls has yet to be announced.
   ``At this juncture it is therefore of the greatest importance
that all Tamil groups in Sri Lanka use this historic opportunity to
come forward and participate in the forthcoming provincial council
elections,'' the Indian statement said.
   ``The government of India hopes that all Tamil groups will ...
come forward and join the mainstream of life and play an effective
role in ensuring the welfare of the people of the northeastern
province,'' it said.
   ``All groups wishing to participate in the elections must lay
down their arms and support the Indo-Sri Lanka agreement,'' the
statement said.
   In Colombo, a senior government official said the announcement
was sudden.
   ``Nobody knows what is going on because this is an Indian
decision,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
``Everybody obviously welcomes the cease-fire, but it will have to
be studied before any official comments can be made.''
   None of the Tamil groups commented on the announcement.
   The India-brokered peace accord stipulates the surrender of arms
by the insurgents in exchange for limited autonomy in the provinces.
   The rebels briefly accepted the July 1987 accord, but reneged on
it last fall, claiming it did not meet their aspirations.
   India, which sponsored the accord because of the sympathies of
its own 60 million Tamils, sent troops to Sri Lanka last October to
force the Tamils to surrender.
   At least 575 Indian soldiers have been killed in hit-and-run
attacks by the rebels, and more than 1,700 have been wounded. India
claims its soldiers have killed more than 1,500 rebels and captured
1,300 others but says the Tamil movement is still far from finished.
   The accord also has been criticized by the Sinhalese, the
majority in Sri Lanka. They say the accord grants too many
concessions to the Tamils. Sinhalese extremists have vowed to kill
anyone who supports the accord and have been blamed for at least
500 deaths since July, including members of the governing United
National Party.
   The Sinhalese also have opposed the merger of the northern and
eastern provinces, saying that while the north is Tamil-dominated,
the eastern province is multi-racial.
   Sinhalese extremists have killed at least 26 people since Monday
in an apparent reaction to the merger announcement.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people, and
the Sinhalese make up 75 percent. Tamils, who are mostly Hindus,
claim they are discriminated by the mainly Buddhist Sinhalese, who
control the island's military and government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
