<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Mecham'sRevenge Bjt   09-14 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham's Revenge, Bjt,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate President, House Speaker among Losers in Arizona Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five months after lawmakers ousted Gov. Evan
Mecham from office, voters have given him a measure of vengeance by
rejecting seven Republican legislators who helped impeach and
convict him.
   ``We stand at the dawn of a great awakening in Arizona,'' Mecham
supporter Jerry Gillespie said Tuesday night after defeating Senate
President Carl Kunasek in the GOP primary by 6,548 votes to 5,610
votes. ``The people of this state have begun the process of
regaining control of their state government.''
   But the results of the voting hardly constituted a sweep by the
pro-Mecham forces. Republicans who opposed him had little
difficulty gaining nomination in areas outside of his traditional
strongholds of rural Arizona and some parts of suburban Phoenix.
   Overall, 35 GOP legislators faced primary challenges, and 27 of
those advanced to the general election. One of the losers was Rep.
Gary Giordano, a conservative and a Mecham supporter who lost his
north Phoenix seat to a moderate.
   Tuesday's primary was the first legislative election since the
Republican-controlled House impeached the ultra-conservative Mecham
in February and the GOP-controlled Senate convicted him in April of
obstructing justice and misusing funds. That automatically
installed Democrat Rose Mofford, the longtime secretary of state,
in his place until 1990.
   Among those losing a bid for renomination was House Speaker Joe
Lane, who started the impeachment process last fall. Mecham backers
Lloyd Fenn and Warren Shumaker captured both GOP slots in his
district.
   ``I'm not sure next year's going to be very much fun for anyone
down at the Legislature,'' Lane had said Tuesday night as the
results became clear.
   Without the impeachment proceedings, ``I believe the speaker and
the president of the Senate would have been re-elected,'' Mecham
said Wednesday in a telephone interview from his Glendale home.
   But he also said the real issue in the primary was the
incumbents' votes for higher taxes, approved after he was removed
from office to remedy a budget deficit.
   The other casualties were pro-impeachment Sens. Peter Kay of
Phoenix and Jack Taylor of Mesa, along with pro-impeachment Reps.
Bob Hungerford of Phoenix, Bob Broughton of Mesa and Don Strauch of
Mesa.
   ``It's a `Mecham factor' if you ask me,'' Taylor said. ``But
I'll tell you, if I was asked to vote again tomorrow, I'd vote to
impeach him.''
   Mecham, asked about the implications for his own political
future, replied: ``I've said many times that the result of the 1988
elections was not a vote on whether I should run in '90 or not.
That decision will be made by me sometime in the middle of next
year.''
   In southeastern Arizona's 5th Congressional District, two-term
GOP incumbent Jim Kolbe handily defeated his challengers, including
former Douglas Mayor Alberto Rodriguez, whose nomination for state
liquor superintendent Mecham withdrew when Rodriguez came under
investigation in a decades-old slaying. Kolbe had 38,169 votes, or
78 percent, to political newcomer Walt Weber's 5,855 votes, or 12
percent; Rodriguez had 5,077 votes, or 10 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
