<DOCNO> AP880914-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0605 09-14 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0605,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Lists Weapons Systems He Would Keep</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 new grafs after pvs 7th graf bgng, ``We're not,
with Dukakis remarks at Annapolis; SUBS pvs 8th graf bgng, Dukakis
accused, to reword for transition; deletes last graf as outdated.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis today endorsed a long list of weapons sstems he said made
sense for America's defense and would bring cohesion to Pentagon
priorities after eight years of Reagan administration waste and
mismanagement.
   ``We've got to have leadership in the Pentagon that will take
charge of our defense policy,'' Dukakis said in a speech at
Georgetown University. ``And we've got to have a president who will
keep faith with the men and women we ask to defend freedom and
liberty around the world.''
   While endorsing a number of weapons programs, Dukakis also
reiterated his opposition to several favored by Reagan and
Republican presidential nominee George Bush, including the
rail-based MX missile, and he expressed anew his concern that the
B-1 bomber would be unable to perform the job for which it was
designed.
   Dukakis said he favored continued research on a strategic
defense system but at about $1 billion a year, far below what
Reagan wants to spend on the so-called Star Wars system. Dukakis
also said that while he agreed in concept with the Midgetman
missile he was not convinced the costly program was needed to
modernize the land-based U.S. nuclear deterrent.
   Dukakis repeated his promise to make improved conventional
forces his top defense priority if he is elected and said he
favored rapid development of new tanks and anti-tank weapons, the
Advanced Tactical Fighter, the SS-21 Sea Wolf fast-attack submarine
and new weapons to fight Soviet submarines.
   He also reiterated his backing of the Trident II submarine-based
missile system, the Stealth bomber and advanced cruise missiles.
   ``We're not going to have a laundry list of weapons systems,''
Dukakis said. ``We're going to have a strategy for keeping America
strong.''
   Later, at a rally in Annapolis, Md., before heading home to
Boston, the Democratic nominee taunted Bush for refusing to agree
to a presidential debate originally scheduled for tonight in the
Maryland capital.
   ``If George Bush isn't ready today after more than seven and a
half years as vice president of this country, how can we expect him
to be ready on Jan. 20, 1989?'' Dukakis asked. ``Lloyd Bentsen and
I are ready.''
   He jokingly suggested that the reason Bush refused to come to
the home of the U.S. Naval Academy was ``that his idea of a naval
exercise is throwing his campaign advisers overboard.'' That was a
reference to the recent resignation of six officials of a pro-Bush
ethnic campaign organization who allegedly had pro-Nazi or
anti-Semitic ties.
   At Georgetown University, Dukakis accused Bush of playing
politics by convincing Reagan to veto a defense authorization bill
recently passed with bipartisan support in Congress and said the
veto had prevented an expanded role for the Coast Guard in the war
on drugs and long-overdue pay and benefit increases for military
forces.
   ``My friends, we can't play politics with our national
security,'' Dukakis said.
   He promised to work diligently toward new arms control measures
and a nuclear test ban treaty with the Soviet Union but also said
he would demand significant cutbacks in Soviet conventional forces
in Europe and call for the dismantling of the Soviets' SS-18
missiles.
   Despite spending billions on defense, Dukakis said the Reagan
administration has done little to improve the nation's security.
   ``The fact is that the Republicans promised in 1980 to make our
land-based missiles invulnerable and, today, after another $25
billion and eight years of Republican mismanagement, our ICBMs are
more vulnerable that they were in 1980.''
   Dukakis said he was committed to the traditional triad of U.S.
defense policy: land-, air- and sea-based strategic capacities. But
he said Bush had shown no cohesion in his priorities and has failed
to discuss the Pentagon procurement scandal.
   ``We have what you might call a new type of Republican triad
today: waste, duplication and fraud,'' he said.
   Dukakis also said that as commander-in-chief he would not shy
away from using military force if necessary.
   ``We'll use force when it's necessary to protect our territory,
our citizens or vital interests; to meet our treaty commitments,
and to deter or respond to terrorist attacks,'' he said.
</TEXT>
