<2ND_LINE>PM-Rapture, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0620,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Barricades Self In House After Hearing About `Rapture'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with deadline passing. PICKS
UP 9th graf pvs, `Chavis was ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GIBSONVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An armed man who barricaded himself in
a house for more than 30 hours, convinced the world was coming to
an end as prophesied in a religious booklet, was overpowered by
police and arrested today, authorities said.
   Ricky Odell Chavis, 27, fired shots at passing motorists and a
police officer, but no one was injured, police said.
   ``He was messed up real bad on religion,'' said Chavis' aunt,
Joy Cassell.
   She said two door-to-door missionaries for the Jehovah's Witness
sect apparently convinced her nephew he needed to ``get right''
because Tuesday would be the day that God called true believers to
heaven.
   Edgar C. Whisenant predicted in his booklet ``88 Reasons Why the
Rapture Will Be in 1988,'' that Jesus would ``rapture the church''
and take the faithful to heaven by sunset Tuesday.
   Whisenant said Tuesday he still believed the ``rapture'' was
imminent and revised the moment to 10:55 a.m. EDT today. That
deadline passed without apparent incident.
   Chavis was arrested after negotiators got him to step outside
his back door shortly after 2 a.m. today, said police dispatcher
Susan Garinger. Sheriff's deputies then lobbed concussion grenades
at Chavis, stunning him, she said.
   Chavis was charged with assaulting a police officer with a
deadly weapon and terrorizing the public.
   Few preachers seemed to take the Whisenant book seriously.
   ``There are maybe a few concerned. There's a lot of interest,''
said the Rev. Richard D. White, pastor of the 2,000-member First
Baptist Church in Franklin, Tenn.
   ``We have difficulty with the book. The scripture is very clear
that that's not something known to man. It's known only to God.''
   Others said it didn't matter that the predictions were wrong.
   ``My awareness has been quickened and I'll never be the same,''
said Helaine Parker of Mount Juliet, Tenn. ``If people mock us, I'm
still happy because mockers are another biblical prophecy that will
come true in the last days.''
   A Duke University theologian said he won't be surprised if there
are more predictions of a Second Coming.
   ``Every time they predict and it doesn't come to pass ... they
don't get embarrassed by that. They just reload. And they say `We
miscalculated,''' said James Efird, professor of biblical
interpretation at Duke's Divinity School.
   About 1 million copies of the book have been circulated
throughout the nation, with about two-thirds sold for $2 and the
rest given away, said the Rev. Bob Doom, who runs a Christian
bookstore in Asheville, N.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
