<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1406EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChurchBombingRemembered Bjt   09-14 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church Bombing Remembered, Bjt,0703</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death of Black Girls in 1963 Church Bombing Shocked Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sunday school lesson that morning 25
years ago was on forgiving love, but racial hatred that had gripped
Birmingham for months erupted in a dynamite explosion that tore
into the church and killed four black girls.
   The blast at the 16th Street Baptist Church on Sept. 15, 1963,
seared the conscience of Alabama's largest city, which had become
known as a segregationist battleground, and helped bring to it a
quarter-century of change.
   The bombing, which is to be marked in a service Thursday night,
came at a time when some city leaders already were trying to find a
way toward racial harmony.
   Less than a year earlier, the city government had been
reorganized to replace the powerful, three-member commission with a
nine-member city council. One of those commissioners, Eugene
``Bull'' Connor, had gained national notoriety when he ordered that
dogs and fire hoses be used against civil rights demonstrators.
   The bombing followed a series of blasts that had occurred since
the 1950s, although no one had died in the earlier explosions.
   The church, near the local office of Martin Luther King's
Southern Christian Leadership Conference, was often used for
rallies by blacks seeking changes in what King had called the most
segregated city in the country.
   The Rev. John Cross, pastor of the church at the time, said at
least three bomb threats had been made before the bombing,
prompting all-night watches at the church for a while.
   ``We had just about relaxed the protection of the church,'' he
said. ``It looked like everything was working with ease. We thought
peace would prevail.''
   J.L. Lowe, who directed the church orchestra, said church
members ``said surely nobody's going to bomb the church while there
are inhabitants.''
   But at about 10:20 a.m. Sunday, Sept. 15, an explosion tore
apart the side entrance to the building. A bomb had been placed
beneath concrete steps near the window of a basement restroom.
   Addie Mae Collins, Cynthia Dianne Wesley and Carole Robertson,
all 14, and Denise McNair, 11, were in the restroom preparing for a
special youth program. They were killed and two other girls were
injured.
   King, himself later the victim of an assassin's bullet, preached
at the combined funeral of three of the blast victims.
   The deaths touched off donations from around the country that
totaled $500,000, money used for the funerals and for repairs to
the church.
   Fourteen years later, a jury convicted Robert Edward Chambliss,
a retired automobile mechanic and Ku Klux Klansman, in the death of
Miss McNair, whose father, Chris McNair, now is a Jefferson County
commissioner. Chambliss died in prison in 1985 after serving eight
years of a life sentence for murder.
   Today, the only reminders of the blast at the 16th Street
Baptist Church are a plaque and memorial nook downstairs and
another memorial in the sanctuary with pictures of the four girls.
   ``If the bombing was meant to stop or deter the civil rights
movement, it did not,'' said the Rev. Fred Shuttlesworth, a founder
of the movement in Birmingham and now a pastor in Cincinnati.
   ``We pick up the pieces, we bury our dead ... but we keep our
faith and keep on moving. I think these things do more solidifying
and bring about more determination than if they did not happen.''
   Today, Richard Arrington is in his third term as Birmingham's
first black mayor, the City Council has six blacks and three
whites, and long gone are the ``whites only'' signs at drinking
fountains, bus stations and restaurants.
   After the explosion, Cross, whose 4-year-old daughter was cut on
the forehead by flying glass, appealed to a crowd gathered in the
street to go home and pray.
   ``God, forgive them, for they know not what they do,'' he said.
   The Sunday lesson that morning, Cross said, had been about ``a
love that forgives. That's what we really had to practice for the
next several weeks and months and years _ and even now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
