<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1414EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FetalTissue Bjt   09-14 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fetal Tissue, Bjt,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researcher Urges Use of Fetal Transplant Tissue to Treat
Parkinson's Disease</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swedish doctor who has transplanted brain
cells from aborted human fetuses to patients with Parkinson's
disease said Wednesday the procedure is so promising it would be
unethical not to make it available to desperately ill people.
   Dr. Lars Olson, professor of neurobiology at Karolinska
Institute in Stockholm and one of the few people in the world to
have transplanted human fetal tissue, also told a National
Institutes of Health advisory committee the technique has been used
in Mexico, China, England and Cuba.
   There are no known cases of fetal tissue being transplanted as a
treatment for Parkinson's disease in the United States, but several
animal studies have suggested the procedure can be effective.
   Eugene Redmond Jr., professor of psychiatry at Yale University
School of Medicine outlined his work with green monkeys. With a
video tape, he showed remarkable improvement in monkeys in which
Parkinson's was induced and then treated with brain cells taken
from healthy monkeys.
   One of the questions the committee specifically has been asked
to answer is whether animal studies have been numerous and
successful enough to warrant going forward with similar
experimental treatment on humans.
   When one of the panel members directed that question to Olson,
he replied: ``The animal data ... are so promising we have
approached a point where I believe it is unethical not to do this
in human studies.''
   The special NIH advisory committee was appointed at the
direction of Dr. Robert E. Windom, the federal government's
assistant secretary for health, after he denied permission for NIH
scientists to proceed with human fetal tissue transplants without
formal consideration of moral and ethical questions raised by the
emerging field of research.
   Even before the group could hold its first meeting, however, it
was learned last week that a White House official has drafted a
proposed executive order that would ban all such research.
   Most of the opposition comes from people and organizations
opposed to abortion in general. They maintain that allowing such
research could encourage more abortions.
   The advisory committee devoted its first daylong session to
scientific issues and will turn to legal and ethical considerations
Thursday before draftings its recommendations on Friday.
   The matter then goes to a standing NIH advisory committee Dec. 1
for final recommendations to NIH Director James B. Wyngaarden.
   Despite the focus on presentations by some of the nation's top
researchers who say fetal tissue transplants hold potential for
treating diabetes, Alzheimer's and many other diseases, it was
clear the scientists and doctors were well aware of ethical
considerations.
   For example, there have been instances of women in the United
States expressing a desire to become pregnant just to produce a
fetus that would be aborted to treat a relative with Parkinson's
disease.
   ``There are rumors that this has been done in East Germany,''
said Thomas J. Gill III, chairman of the pathology department at
the University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine. ``I think this is
ethically unacceptable.''
   Olson made no claims of dramatic improvements for the two
patients he implanted with fetal brain cells eight months ago.
   ``There have been no adverse effects,'' he said. ``It appears
that we are seeing minor positive changes in the patients.''
   He pointed out that both patients, women in their 50s, have been
suffering from severe Parkinson's for 15 years and he was
optimistic that the marginal improvement seen so far will intensify
as the implanted brain cells mature.
   Parkinson's, which causes a loss of muscle control, is caused by
a shortage of cells that produce a brain chemical called dopamine.
It is these dopamine-producing cells that are transplanted from
fetuses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
