<HEAD>Hostages Taken At Recruiting Station</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS typo in lead to make quote read `peace in Lebanon.;
COMBINES pvs urgent series.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman took 11 hostages at a military
recruiting station today but freed them unharmed hours later after
two radio stations agreed to air a statement asserting his goal was
``peace in Lebanon.''
   He surrendered moments later, shortly before 2 p.m. No one was
injured.
   The unidentified gunman, who had described himself as ``a local
person of Lebanese descent,'' was armed with an AK-47, an automatic
rifle that is standard issue in Communist countries, said police
Lt. C.M. Schesventer.
   Police negotiated by telephone with the man, who had claimed two
armed companions, but police learned from freed captives there was
only one gunman.
   The 11 captives _ nine military personnel and two civilians _
included a high school senior enlisting in the service, said
Schesventer.
   Hostages began coming out, alone and in twos, about every 10
minutes shortly after radio stations WRNL-AM and WRXL-FM twice
aired a message at the gunman's demand around noon, said Marianne
Jennings, news director at the stations.
   ``There is a hostage situation at Tuckernuck Square Shopping
Center,'' the statement read. ``There have been no injuries.
Negotiations are proceeding. The hostage-takers have so far been
cooperative. They're holding an undetermined number of people. The
hostage-takers' goal is peace in Lebanon.''
   The U.S. Armed Forces Recruiting Center is in a shopping center
that includes 30 stores. All were evacuated.
   Local and state police carrying automatic weapons ringed the
area. The shopping center is in a heavily developed commercial
strip.
   Sands said police received a call at 9:15 a.m. about a
hostage-taking at the recruiting center, which houses
representatives of several military branches.
