<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1442EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JapanTrade     09-14 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan Trade,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rice Industry Acts to Counter Japanese Import Curbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American rice farmers complained Wednesday
that their crops are being frozen out of the Japanese market and
asked for government help including trade retaliation if needed.
   ``The time has come for the government of Japan to take the
steps necessary for us to compete in our market,'' Sen. David
Pryor, D-Ark., told a news conference at which the action was
announced.
   Groups representing rice producers and millers asked U.S. Trade
Representative Clayton K. Yeutter for assistance on grounds that
Japanese refusal to permit rice imports amounts to an unfair trade
barrier.
   Yeutter has 45 days to decide whether to take the case. If he
did so, the next step would be to engage in talks with the Japanese.
   If that failed, the government would seek relief under the
97-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). Failure to
get results after two years of GATT negotiations would require
retaliation under the new trade law approved by Congress and signed
by President Reagan this summer.
   Japan is the American farmer's best customer. It bought more
than $5.5 billion worth of U.S. agricultural products last year and
is expected to account for $6.9 billion in purchases this year,
more than any other country.
   Many of these goods, such as corn, are not grown in quantity in
Japan. It has imported only a tiny trickle of rice, maintaining
restraints in an effort to protect its farmers from foreign
competition.
   California, Texas and other American producers, engaging in
high-tech, large-scale farming, can grow rice at far below the
costs of Japanese counterparts and, if all trade restraints were
swept away, could be expected to command a substantial share of the
Japanese market in short order.
   Industry officials said rice priced at $300 a ton in the United
States would cost $2,500 in Japan.
   They told the news conference, however, they have no intention
of trying to wipe out Japanese rice farming.
   ``We are not looking for an opportunity to flood the Japanese
market,'' said J. Stephen Gabbert, president of the Rice Millers
Association. The group filed the trade petition in a joint effort
with the Rice Council for Market Development, a growers group.
   The petition seeks to gain 2.5 percent of the Japanese rice
market in the first of a four-year phase-in and expand to 10
percent, or 1 million tons, by the fourth year.
   Senators from rice-producing states were on hand to push the
petition, with Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., declaring that the
industry had tried to get the Japanese to import American rice
voluntarily.
   ``As always the response has been a virtual stone wall,'' said
Wilson. ``And that is not good enough.''
</TEXT>
