<HEAD>Reagan Campaigns for Bush in Missouri</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 new grafs after pvs 9th graf bgng, ``When the,''
with Reagan deleting phrase from speech text, praising trade
deficit figure.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE GIRARDEAU, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, campaigning for his
vice president George Bush, blamed Democrats Wednesday for
``economic and foreign policy nightmares.''
   Reagan praised his own record in office during a speech prepared
for a campaign rally at Southeast Missouri State University, and he
envisioned a return to high inflation and other economic problems
as well as a loss of American prestige if the Democrats win in
November.
   ``America has traveled such a remarkable distance in the last
eight years that the memory has faded of the economic and foreign
policy crises that we faced when Vice President Bush and I took
office,'' he said in the latest in a series of out-of-town forays
Reagan will make to promote Bush and Republican candidates for
Congress.
   ``The truth is that when you take a walk down our opposition's
memory lane, it starts to look like `Nightmare on Elm Street,''' he
said.
   Reagan, who won roughly 60 percent of the popular vote in
Missouri in his race against Democrat Walter F. Mondale, was
traveling later in the day to St. Louis to speak at a $250-a-plate
fund-raising dinner. White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
the expenses for the trip from Washington were being paid by the
state and national Republican parties.
   In his speech, Reagan brought back a familiar refrain _ that
Democratic Party leaders harbor gloom-and-doom views of America's
future in the world _ although he never mentioned the name of
Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   He did say that in 1979, the nation was facing double-digit
inflation and interest rates at home while being faced with the
seizure of the American Embassy in Tehran, Iran, and the Soviet
incursion into Afghanistan.
   ``Don't we have the right to ask the American people: If the
liberals return to power, what happens in 1989?'' he asked.
   ``When the American people saw that under the other fellows, the
economic misery index was soaring off the charts, they wanted a
change, and who did they call? George Bush and me _ the
malaise-busters.''
   Fitzwater told reporters that during the flight from Washington
that the president decided not to use the ``malaise-busters''
phrase because ``he said he was just uncomfortable with the
language.''
   Reagan hailed the Commerce Department's report Wednesday that
the U.S. merchandise trade deficit fell in July to $9.5 billion,
the lowest level since December 1984.
   ``When America goes into the market to compete, we plan to
win,'' he said. ``Others may talk, but we deliver.''
   ``Today, we have peace and prosperity,'' Reagan said. ``And the
liberals are trying to pretend those economic and foreign policy
nightmares they gave us never happened.''
   Several state Republicans, including Gov. John Ashcroft, hoped
to benefit from Reagan's fund-raising appearances. Ashcroft is
seeking a second term against Democratic State Rep. Betty Hearnes
of Charleston, the wife of former Gov. William Hearnes.
   Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., is opposed by State Sen. Jay Nixon of
Hillsboro as Danforth seeks his third term.
</TEXT>
