<HEAD>Study Says Airline Computer Reservation Systems Cut Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By Aciated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five airline-owned computer reservation
systemsLAN FRAM=
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Asso used by travel agents to book passengers are so dominant</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   that they are stifling competition in the air travel industry, a
congressional report said Wednesday.
   The study concluded that the reservation systems are generating
profits ``exceeding those that could reasonably be expected to be
earned in a competitive market.''
   It also chided the Department of Transportation for failing to
take steps to eliminate the ``anti-competitive features'' of the
computer reservation industry.
   ``DOT has a statutory responsibility to protect competition in
the airline industry,'' said the report, which was written by the
General Accounting Office, Congress' nonpartisan investigative
agency.
   The computer systems whic budget deficit, Brady praised both the
administration and Congress for their efforts, which have whittled
the deficit from $220 billion in 1986 to an estimated $150 billion
this year.
   ``I do think we can grow our way out of this,'' he said, adding
at another point, ``I see no reason at this moment why taxes have
to be raised.''
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., urged Brady to offer more than
``platitudes'' on the budget. Brady declined to recommend
specifics, but promised to present Congress with new ideas for
reducing the deficit by the end of the year.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, the chairman of the Finance
Committee and the Democratic vice presidential candidate, gave
Brady a warm endorsement, even though Brady is a close adviser to
Bush.
   ``Nick Brady is a friend and former colleague and in my opinion
is a man who is well qualified to be treasury secretary,'' Bentsen
said. ``It's a big job, a tough job, but you're used to tough
jobs.''
   In his latest government assignment, Brady headed a presidential
task force that studied the causes of the October stock market
crash. His report called for greater regulation over some aspects
of the markets and was met with a cold shoulder by the
administration.
   Brady said market reforms put in place since the crash have been
``on the right track,'' declining to criticize the administration
for not doing everything his commission advised.
   ``I'm not sure we were 100 percent right. We did our work in 60
days,'' he said.
   On another matter, Brady said federal savings and loan
regulators have as much as they can spend for now on S&L rescues
and he said he saw no reason, for now, for a taxpayer bailout of
the industry.
   Brady's great-grandfather founded electric utilities that later
became part of Consolidated Edison Co., and his grandfather started
a precursor of Dodge Motor Co., now a division of Chrysler Corp.
The family also founded Purolator Co.
   Brady, 58, is co-chairman of Dillon Read & Co., an old-line Wall
Street investment firm, which he joined in 1954 after receiving a
master's degree in business from Harvard University.
   In 1982, he represented New Jersey for eight months in the
Senate by appointment, filling the seat of Democrat Harrison A.
Williams Jr., who had resigned following his conviction in the
Abscam influence-peddling scandal.
