<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeSillers     09-14 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DeSillers,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing Set Friday On Motions In DeSillers Estate Flap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The savings and loan where Maria DeSillers kept
some donations for her son's medical care should have frozen the
funds after the boy died, the estate's curator contends in court
documents.
   Nearly $690,000, including $1,000 from President Reagan, was
donated to pay for liver transplants for 7-year-old Ronnie, who
died in April 1987 while awaiting his fourth liver transplant at
Pittsburgh's Children's Hospital.
   After his death, Coral Gables Federal Savings and Loan did not
block Ms. DeSillers from withdrawing of some $200,000, which
legally belonged to the boy's estate, curator Karen Gievers alleged
in motions filed Tuesday with Dade County Probate Court.
   ``With the widespread national media attention that Ronnie got,
the (savings and loan) should have realized that he had died,'' Ms.
Gievers said.
   Ms. Gievers said her motions asked for court permission to bring
a lawsuit against the savings and loan over the issue. A hearing
was scheduled Friday before Probate Judge Francis Christie.
   Karl Steene, director of marketing for Coral Gables Federal,
declined to comment Tuesday.
   Ms. DeSillers and her attorney, Frank Johnson, did not return
phone messages seeking comment. In the past, the have contended
that she had the right to the money because some of the donations
were intended just for her personal expenses.
   The money withdrawn by Ms. DeSillers was used to buy a used BMW
for $13,500, jewelry, clothing and other items. Christie signed a
court order last month authorizing the seizure of disputed
property. The car was seized, but the other items have not yet been
taken.
   Money used to buy the car, and the value of other property and
assets recovered during the ongoing legal battle, will be deducted
from the amount Ms. Gievers hopes to obtain from Coral Gables
Federal.
   If Coral Gables Federal is forced to pay the difference to
Ronnie's estate, the savings and loan could in turn sue Ms.
DeSillers, the curator said.
</TEXT>
