<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Hostage     09-14 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Hostage,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Ransom May Have Been Paid For Hostage Release</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hamadi Trial, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ransom of $22.2 million may have
been paid to release a West German hostage despite a round of
denials from his employer and government officials, a newspaper
reported Wednesday.
   The Hamburg-based mass-cirulation daily Bild said the money was
deposited into Arabian bank accounts to secure the freedom of
Rudolf Cordes, who arrived home Tuesday night after 20 months of
captivity.
   Cordes, 55, Beirut manager for the Hoechst AG pharmaceutical
company, was released by his pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem kidnappers
late Monday night. He was first taken to Damascus, Syria.
   Wolfgang Schaeuble, who heads the federal government's Middle
East crisis group, strongly denied that money was paid for Cordes'
release.
   ``There were no deals. There were no conditions,'' said
Schaeuble.
   ``The release was secured through talks and the help of Iranian
and Syrian officials,'' he said, echoing earlier comments by
Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher and Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   Schaeuble also said the government made no concessions in the
case of Mohammed Ali Hamadi, who is on trial in Frankfurt on
charges of murder and air piracy in the 1985 hijacking of a TWA
jetliner.
   Justice Minister Hans Engelhard also said the government ``from
the first moment on made it clear that there would be no deals, no
release in exchange for the West German hostages.''
   Cordes and another West German, Alfred Schmidt, were kidnapped
in Beirut in January 1987 after Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt
Airport.
   Schmidt was released on Sept. 7, 1987.
   Hamadi's older brother, Abbas, was convicted by a Duesseldorf
court for his role in the kidnappings, which were designed to
pressure the government into releasing Mohammed Hamadi.
   But Bild, citing unidentified security sources, strongly
suggested a ransom was paid.
   ``Despite all denials by the West German government and the
Hoechst company, a sum of millions is believed to have been paid to
kidnappers for the release,'' Bild said.
   The newspaper quoted a source identified only as a ``security
expert'' as saying that millions of dollars were paid for Cordes'
release.
   ``Such money is paid discreetly via front men into Arabian bank
accounts,'' Bild quoted a ``security expert'' as saying. ``In
Cordes' case there has been talk of at least 40 million marks
($22.2 million).''
   The newspaper is known to have good sources within the
government in Bonn.
   The Frankfurt-based Hoechst company also denied that any money
was paid and declared as false a magazine report that it had hired
a private detective to deliver the money.
   Hoechst spokeswoman Felicitas Feick said: ``Our company had
nothing to do with this man. No money was paid for Mr. Cordes'
release.''
   The Hamburg-based Stern magazine, in a telex to news media, said
a man it identified as Werner Mauss was hired by the company to
conduct negotiations and deliver money to the hijackers.
   After his arrival at Cologne-Bonn airport Tuesday, Cordes was
immediately flown to an undisclosed location. He remained in
seclusion Wednesday.
   Schaeuble told West German television that Cordes was ``weak but
in good health.'' He said Cordes told him that he was kept isolated
and chained during most of his captivity.
   ``He was moved often and was in a continuous state of
uncertainty. He told me he received few letters from his
relatives,'' Schaeuble said.
   Cordes was the last West German hostage in Lebanon, where 17
other foreigners are held captive. The longest held is Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press.
Anderson was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
