<DOCNO> AP880914-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1533EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ThirdWorldProtectionism     09-14 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Third World Protectionism,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Concessions For Third World Unjustified, Treasury Chief Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting Treasury Secretary M. Peter McPherson
spoke out strongly Wednesday for ending Third World trade
concessions that he said perpetuate poverty instead of promoting
growth.
   ``Less developed countries can gain much more by negotiating as
true trade partners ... than as special pleaders'' in trade talks,
he said in a speech to the American Enterprise Institute, a
business and public policy research organization.
   McPherson attacked the reliance of developing countries on
waivers of international trade rules allowing them to use ``import
substitution'' and non-reciprocity policies to protect infant
industries.
   He said that during the current Uruguay round of world trade
negotiations, the United States will step up opposition to
``special and differential treatment'' for such countries under the
rules of GATT, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   The Uruguay round, launched at the 1986 world economic
conference at Punta del Este, Uruguay, is scheduled for a review
session in December at Montreal.
   Import substitution amounts to protection and ``the old theory
that trade protection promotes development is bankrupt, yet GATT
still echoes this theory,'' McPherson said.
   The accumulation of ``special exemptions and arrangements for
developing countries through GATT's history has effectively removed
less developed countries from obligations under GATT principles of
nondiscrimination, transparency and reciprocity,'' he asserted.
   A 1955 GATT decision allowing poor countries with balance of
payments (BOP) problems to restrict imports temporarily has been
misused to the point that ``the BOP waiver is used to provide
lasting cover for import substitution policies,'' he said. ``Some
of those quotas have been in place for decades.''
   ``Rather than a strategy for economic development, import
substitution is a strategy for economic decline,'' McPherson
asserted. He said the concessions promote inward-looking policies
that reduce export capacity, worsen balance of payments and income
distribution and depress wages.
   Not only the free trade city-states of Singapore and Hong Kong
but also Turkey and Mexico are examples of economies that have
prospered under outward-oriented trade policies, McPherson said.
   After it ``reversed course and began to liberalize trade'' in
1980, Turkey's annual rises in export growth jumped from 5.5
percent to almost 20 per cent, he said. ``No economy, not even
Taiwan has performed better.'' Turkish manufactured goods, 2
percent of exports in 1965, account for 56 percent today, he said.
</TEXT>
