<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hurricane-Preparations     09-14 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane-Preparations,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Says Federal Agencies Coordinating Efforts In Case Of
Disaster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon has agreed to dispatch
active-duty military personnel and equipment from at least one base
in Texas to assist with evacuations along the Texas coast as
Hurricane Gilbert moves closer to the United States, Sen. Phil
Gramm said Wednesday.
   He said the Army was setting up a ``crisis action center'' in
Washington to coordinate the effort, and that active duty personnel
and equipment would be called up from Fort Hood in Killeen and
possibly Fort Bliss in El Paso.
   Trucks, helicopters and bulldozers and an undetermined number of
military personnel will be sent to the coast to assist the Texas
National Guard with the evacuations, said Gramm, R-Texas.
   ``They're willing to commit whatever is needed to get the job
done,'' Gramm said, as the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration labeled Hurricane Gilbert the strongest hurricane
ever in the Western Hemisphere.
   ``I'm pleased we're getting organized,'' Gramm said. ``If it
turns out to be disaster it has the potential to be, an early
coordination effort could be the difference betwen saving lives and
not.''
   Gramm also announced Wednesday that the Army Corps of Engineers
had opened an emergency office in Galveston to handle flood control
and emergency construction along the coast.
   ``This puts a lot of resources at our command,'' Gramm said.
   Gramm said he had also been talking with officials from the
Housing and Urban Development Department, the Small Business
Administration, the Farmers Home Administration, the General
Services Administration and the Federal Emergency Management
Administration about emergency shelter and communications needs.
   ``We asked each to go ahead and begin their preparations,''
Gramm said. ``The idea is the better organized we are in advance of
the potential dangers of the hurricane, the less we will have in
terms of property damage and personal injury.''
</TEXT>
