<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WisconsinSenate     09-14 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wisconsin Senate,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Spending Seems Assured in Race for Proxmire Seat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Includes highlights of Tuesday's other primary results.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Primary victors Herbert Kohl and state Sen.
Susan Engeleiter launched a campaign Wednesday for the seat of
retiring Sen. William Proxmire that promises to be the most
expensive race in Wisconsin history.
   ``It's going to be like `Brewster's Millions,''' said Michael
Grebe, a Republican national committeeman, referring to the Richard
Pryor movie in which a man must give away a large amount of money
in a short time.
   Kohl, owner of the Milwaukee Bucks basketball team, defeated
former Gov. Anthony S. Earl and three other Democratic candidates
Tuesday after spending $2.1 million, most of it on TV ads. He had
raised $3.6 million for the primary, $3.2 million of it his own
money.
   In the general election, Kohl ``will spend enough to get his
message across, just as he did in the primary,'' said his
spokesman, Steve McKay.
   Kohl credited his ``Nobody's Senator but Yours'' slogan for his
victory and said the vote showed people wanted ``a qualified
non-politician with real business world experience.''
   Engeleiter, the only woman nominated by either party for a
Senate seat this year, spent $1.2 million to defeat Stephen B.
King, former state party chairman, in the GOP primary.
   She said she expects to spend $3.5 million in the general
election, a shade over the state record of $3.4 million spent by
Sen. Robert Kasten in his re-election campaign in 1986.
   Yet Engeleiter plans to make an issue of Kohl's wealth,
according to campaign manager Jill Hanson, by portraying the choice
as between a 36-year-old mother of two and a bachelor millionaire.
   The talk of big money was noted with regret by Proxmire, who
reported spending just $145.10 on is last campaign in 1982.
   ``People are allowed spend that kind of money,'' he said. ``They
do it in every state. I think it's a shame. It's too bad.''
   But Proxmire, who endorsed Earl in television commericials
before the primary, was quick to support Kohl, saying he will
``make a very strong and fine Democratic candidate and an
outstanding U.S. senator.''
   With 99 percent of the votes counted, Kohl had 248,092 votes or
47 percent, to Earl's 203,195, or 38 percent. Former deputy
attorney general Edward R. Garvey had 55,083 votes or 10 percent,
Secretary of State Douglas La Follette had 20,145 votes or 4
percent, and Edmond Hou-Seye, a Sheboygan tire dealer, had 5,147
votes or 1 percent.
   Engeleiter swamped King 209,973 to 148,345 votes, or 57 percent
to 40 percent. Peter Taylor, of Milwaukee, had 9,260 votes, or 3
percent.
   Here are highlights of other primary voting Tuesday:
   VERMONT _ Republican Rep. James Jeffords defeated conservative
Michael Griffes in a Senate primary. Jeffords will face Democrat
William Gray, a former U.S. attorney, for the seat of retiring GOP
Sen. Robert Stafford.
   NEW HAMPSHIRE _ Rep. Judd Gregg, son of a former governor,
defeated two challengers for the GOP nomination for governor. He
will face Democrat Paul McEeachern for the job being given up by
Gov. John Sununu.
   ARIZONA _ Seven Republican legislators who voted to impeach or
convict Gov. Evan Mecham last spring lost in primaries to his
ultra-conservative backers.
   MINNESOTA _ Republican Sen. Dave Durenberger won the nomination
for a third term and Attorney General Hubert H. ``Skip'' Humphrey
III won the Democratic nomination to oppose him.
</TEXT>
