<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryConstruction     09-14 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Construction,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves $8.8 Billion Measure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted 386-26 approval Wednesday of a
bill appropriating $8.8 billion for military construction projects
in the year beginning Oct. 1.
   It approved a compromise House-Senate version of the legislation
and sent it to the Senate for final congressional consideration.
   The compromise is an increase from the $8.3 billion construction
budget for the current fiscal year but is below the $9.7 billion
sought by President Reagan.
   The measure includes $65 million for the final stage of
construction of a national test facility in Colorado for Reagan's
Strategic Defense Initiative, also known as Star Wars. The $100
million project will be used to test SDI components.
   The bill doesn't contain money for construction of a
railroad-based version of the MX nuclear-tipped missile. Reagan
sought $31 million. Congress decided to leave the decision on the
future of the rail-based MX weapon up to the next administration.
   The measure provides $173 million for construction projects as
part of the Navy's new home porting program, which involves
building new bases around the nation's coasts. The Navy sought $191
million for the program.
   The bill also has $50 million to build a closed incinerator at
Tooele Army Depot in Utah to destroy obsolete and aging chemical
weapons. The Army is building new chemical weapons.
</TEXT>
