<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MrsLetterman 1stLd-Writethru a0719 09-14 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mrs Letterman, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0719,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Who Claimed To Be Letterman's Wife Gets Probation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf, `Superior Court...' to CORRECT to Leavitt,
sted Levitt.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of setting up housekeeping
in David Letterman's home while he was away, taking the talk show
host's Porsche for a spin and posing as his wife was placed on two
years' probation today.
   Margaret Ray, 36, of no certain address, was granted accelerated
rehabilitation on charges of burglary and auto theft. The form of
probation is available to first-time offenders and does not require
the defendant to enter a plea.
   If the defendant completes probation, the charges are stricken
from his or her record.
   Superior Court Judge Edward Leavitt ordered Ray to remain a
psychiatric patient at Fairfield Hills Hospital in Newtown and have
no personal contact with Letterman. Ray was twice found incompetent
to stand trial on the charges.
   ``It's good news,'' she said after sentencing.
   Ray was taken into custody in May after she was stopped at the
New Jersey entrance to the Lincoln Tunnel to New York City driving
Letterman's sports car, police said.
   Ray, whose 3-year-old son was in the car, didn't have any money
and allegedly told the toll collector, ``I'm Mrs. David Letterman
and this is David Jr. Don't you think David Letterman is good for
the toll?''
   Police said she had broken into and set up housekeeping in
Letterman's New Canaan home several days earlier.
   Letterman's attorneys had sent a letter to the court agreeing to
accelerated rehabilitation, said Assistant States Attorney Robert
Hall. The letter was not made public.
   Authorities initially decided not to press charges at
Letterman's request. But Ray returned to the talk show host's house
soon after being released in New Jersey and was arrested by New
Canaan police, authorities said.
   In August, a judge said Ray was at last competent to stand trial.
</TEXT>
