<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ElectedHispanics     09-14 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elected Hispanics,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NUmber of Hispanic Officeholders Increasing, Gains Expected in
1992</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hispanics hold a record 3,360 elected offices
across the country, most of them at the local level, the director
of an organization that tracks Hispanic officials said Wednesday.
   The House of Representatives has 11 Hispanic members and the
Senate has none, but Harry Pachon, national director of the
National Association of Latino Elected and Appointed Officials,
said big gains are possible in 1992 when congressional districts
are reapportioned based on the 1990 census.
   Although Hispanics make up 19.4 million, or 8 percent, of the
country's population, they hold fewer than 1 percent of the 490,000
elected offices nationwide, Pachon told a Capitol Hill news
conference.
   Pachon, however, called the gains made by Hispanics into elected
positions ``dramatic progress. It's not just rhetoric, it's an
increasing reality.''
   The number of Hispanics holding office increased 1.3 percent
this year, less than the 4.2 percent increase logged in 1987. But
that increase reflected the 1986 elections, while this year's
figures largely reflect local elections held between August 1987
and this past August, Pachon said.
   At the same time, the number of Hispanic women elected to office
increased by 5.7 percent this year, to 626 or 18.6 percent of the
total.
   Pachon said most of the elected Hispanics are Democrats, except
in Florida, where most are Republican.
   The association said the largest gains were made in the
Southwest, with Texas accounting for a record-high 1,611 Hispanic
officials. Texas has the nation's second largest Hispanic
population, estimated by the Census Bureau at 4.1 million or 23.1
percent of the estimated nationwide total.
   New Mexico had the second-highest total with 595 Hispanic
officials. Overall, the state has 543,000 Hispanics, or 2.8 percent
of the national total.
   California has the largest Hispanic population in the country _
6.6 million or 33.9 percent of the nationwide Hispanic population _
and 466 hold elective office.
   ``With 6 million Hispanics in California, you think there would
be a half dozen (in Congress),'' instead of the current four, said
Rep. Albert Bustamante, a San Antonio Democrat and chairman of the
Congressional Hispanic Caucus.
   Many California Hispanics, however, are not eligible to vote,
Bustamante said, adding that the situation would change in the 21st
century when their children can vote.
   ``All of these kids are going to vote and there is going to be a
tremendous upsurge. The 21st century will make a tremendous
difference,'' Bustamante said.
   New York, with a Hispanic population of 2.1 million, or 11
percent, had 68 elected Latino leaders, the report said, fewer than
states with smaller Hispanic populations like Arizona, with 237
elected of officials, and Colorado with 157.
   The report said Hispanics hold one governorship, Bob Martinez of
Florida, and there are 229 Hispanic mayors, 120 state legislators,
319 county office holders, 1,106 municipal officials and 1,226
school board members.
   Other states with double-digit numbers of elected Hispanics were
Florida, 50, New Jersey, 44, Illinois, 28, Connecticut, 15, and
Washington, 12.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
