<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1756EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Patients-AIDS     09-14 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Patients-AIDS,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cook County Patients May Get To Refuse Treatment by AIDS Virus
Carriers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patients at Cook County Hospital would have the
right to refuse treatment by workers who carry the AIDS virus under
a proposal praised by some in the medical community as an advance
in patients' rights but criticized by others as misinformed.
   The recommendation was approved Tuesday by the County Board's
Health and Hospitals Committee. It is expected to be endorsed by
the full board next week, becoming the first such policy for a U.S.
hospital, officials said.
   It would cover all hospital workers who ``routinely provide
direct patient care,'' including doctors and nurses.
   Cook County Hospital Director Terrence Hansen said the proposed
policy is an effort to increase patients' rights, but others in the
medical profession blasted the proposal Wednesday.
   ``Our reaction is one of dismay,'' said Dr. Lonnie Bristow,
speaking for the American Medical Association. ``There has been no
case in this country of a patient contracting the AIDS virus from a
health-care worker.
   ``It is important to keep in mind that the disease is not
transmitted by casual contact,'' Bristow, a member of the AMA's
board of trustees, said from his Berkeley, Calif., office. ``The
likelihood of transmission from a health-care worker is very
small.''
   The proposed policy ``is not offering (patients) any additional
protection. It implies people should be worried,'' he said.
   ``This is a policy based on fear and it will do no one any
good,'' said Dr. Renslow Sherer, who works in the AIDS prevention
service at Cook County Hospital. ``This is an ill-conceived and
ill-advised policy.''
   ``The fact that no other hospital has taken this action means
the hospitals don't see this as a major problem,'' said Ann Guild,
director of medical staff affairs for the Illinois Hospital
Association.
   ``It's not supported by scientific evidence that something like
this is necessary,'' Guild said.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome destroys the body's defenses
against disease, leaving a person prey to life-threatening
infections and certain cancers.
   AIDS has struck more than 72,000 people in this country since
1979 and killed more than 40,000 of them, according to the national
Centers for Disease Control.
   The virus that causes the incurable and fatal disease is
believed to be spread through sexual intercourse, shared hypodermic
needles and from infected mothers to their infants before or during
birth.
   The resolution was passed by the committee over the objections
of Cook County Hospital's House Staff Association, which represents
doctors at the institution, the Chicago Women's AIDS Project and
several other community organizations.
   Dr. Stonewall McCuiston, president of the House Staff
Association, said the policy ``would wrongly give the impression
that there is a high incidence of AIDS and HIV cases among County
Hospital Workers.''
   However, board member John Stroger said it is a case of a
patient's right to know.
   ``Doctors at County have told me they wouldn't let members of
their families be treated by a certain doctor at the hospital
(because they fear he has AIDS), but then they turn around and come
out for doctors' rights,'' Stroger said.
   Neurosurgeon Alan Bouffard, a Cook County doctor who died of
AIDS-related diseases in May, was stripped of his medical
privileges at the hospital in February 1987 by the county board,
which cited concerns about the spread of the disease.
   A year later, a federal judge ordered him reinstated, but
required him to wear double gloves for certain procedures.
</TEXT>
