<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MalibuHermit     09-14 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Malibu Hermit,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents of Posh Malibu Mourn Hermit Known as `Malibu Joe'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MALIBU, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this celebrity enclave want a
memorial to honor the memory of a not-so-rich or famous inhabitant
_ a hermit known as Malibu Joe who spurned most offers of help.
   Joe, whose last name was believed to be either Castello or
Costello, died Sept. 4, six days after he was found severely beaten
and robbed. He was 96. He told police before he died that he
couldn't remember who had attacked him, and there have been no
arrests.
   Flowers and cards have been placed around the tiny
shrub-surrounded area behind a gas station that Joe called home.
   ``Malibu's devastated,'' said G.G. Gundry, a resident. ``If he'd
died of old age, people would be sad but not as upset as they are
now. When someone is murdered like that, it makes you realize the
world is changing.''
   Actress Ali MacGraw is among the locals who have joined i a
drive to build a memorial. More than $1,400 has been raised toward
installation of a bench and permanent plaque in his honor.
   Malibu Joe's body is still at the coroner's office. Authorities
say residents have expressed interest in paying for a funeral if no
kin comes forward.
   ``There is a possibility we will have a memorial service at
Malibu Bluff Park. We're trying to something together,'' said
Malibu Times editor Gil Peters.
   Malibu Joe refused handouts, leading local real estate agent
Louis Busch to once declare that if Malibu ever incorporated, Joe
should be mayor because ``nobody can get to him _ if you try to
give him even a dollar, he gets very upset.''
   But Joe would occasionally accept items left at his spot.
   ``He wasn't considered a transient or a bum by us. He was a
classic fixture in the community,'' said Peters. ``There was a
certain pride in Malibu Joe that isn't typical with the usual
street people. For some reason, he turned himself into a folk
hero.''
</TEXT>
