<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Threat,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Acquitted of Strangling AIDS-Stricken Roommate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who strangled his former roommate
because he threatened to infect him with the fatal AIDS virus by
biting him was acquitted of murder Wednesday.
   Dale David Dalton of Laguna Beach bowed his head in Orange
County Superior Court when the jury announced its verdict after
three days of deliberations.
   Dalton, 34, was charged with first-degree murder in the 1987
strangulation of Edward Ihling in the Laguna Beach home they once
shared.
   Dalton testified that he strangled Ihling with a shirt in
self-defense after the man lunged at him with his teeth bared,
threatening to infect him with AIDS.
   Deputy District Attorney Richard King alleged, however, that
Dalton was planning to shoot Ihling because he had told Dalton's
boss that he was a homosexual and drug dealer.
   ``I'll start over again,'' Dalton said outside court. ``I'm just
glad this whole thing is over.''
</TEXT>
