<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Greenspan-Banks     09-14 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greenspan-Banks,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Chairman Will Go Along With Ban on Big Bank-Securities Mergers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan
told Congress Wednesday he sees no need for a blanket ban on
mergers of the biggest banks and securities firms, but will go
along with such a ban to win passage of legislation permitting
banks to underwrite securities.
   Bills passed by the full Senate and House Banking Committee
would permit bank holding companies to underwrite many securities.
But both bills, in provisions aimed at blocking the creation of
financial giants, forbid the merger of the 15 largest securities
firms with the 15 largest banking companies.
   However, Rep. Peter Rodino, D-N.J., chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee, which is reviewing the bill, said he may offer
an amendment to bring the bill in line with antitrust law, which
focuses on the power of merged firms in specific regional or
product markets.
   Rep. Hamilton Fish, R-N.Y., ranking minority member on the
Judiciary subcommittee on monopolies, said the largest banks and
securities firms currently represent little more than 1 percent of
their current markets.
   Greenspan told subcommittee members that he and fellow Fed
governors ``see no threat to the system if those (merger)
activities were to take place.'' But he said they did not believe
it was wise to press the issue for fear of hurting chances for
repealing the Glass-Steagall Act, which separated commercial from
investment banking in 1933.
   He also said he thought such large mergers unlikely. Large banks
are more likely to purchase several small securities firms or start
up a securities division on their own, he said.
   Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., sponsor of the Senate bill and
chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, is strongly in favor of
merger limits.
   However, Comptroller of the Currency Robert L. Clarke, whose
office regulates nationally chartered banks, said ``arbitrary
prohibition on certain mergers is not ... appropriate.'' He urged
the subcommittee to strike the size limits from the House bill and
allow regulators to judge each merger individually for its effect
on competition.
   Greenspan branded a number of other provisions in the House bill
as anti-competitive, including: a ban on corporate stock
underwriting; the prohibition of banks and securities affiliates
from sharing corporate names, logos, premises or advertising, and a
restriction on banks ability to sell insurance.
</TEXT>
