<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0713,0797</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Arrives in Lesotho After Unscheduled South African Stop</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs with shootout detail; PICKS up 7th pvs:
South Africa...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS REDMONT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MASERU, Lesotho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II arrived in this tiny
kingdom Wednesday just 20 minutes before a bloody shootout between
police and gunmen holding a busload of nuns and children on a papal
pilgrimage.
   Four people reportedly died.
   John Paul was to fly from Botswana to Lesotho today but bad
weather forced his chartered jet to make an unscheduled landing in
South Africa, the target of his criticism during his southern
Africa tour.
   The pope arrived in Lesotho eight hours behind schedule and just
20 minutes before the tense hostage drama was played out.
   Police said gunmen hijacked the bus carrying with about 70
people Tuesday, drove it to the British High Commission, or
embassy, compound and demanded to meet the pope. Authorities said
the hijackers began firing after they tried to drive the vehicle
through the closed gates of the embassy compound.
   Three hijackers and a hostage, a young woman, were killed in a
gun battle with police, authorities said. Eleven other passengers
were wounded, the rest of the hostages were rescued, and one
hijacker was arrested, police said.
   The hijackers held police at bay through Tuesday night while
demanding to meet John Paul and Lesotho's king, Moshoeshoe II, a
government official said.
   John Paul, meanwhile, had intended to bypass South Africa on his
tour of five neighboring, black-ruled nations.
   But his flight from Botswana to Lesotho was diverted because of
bad weather, and he spent three hours at Johannesburg's Jan Smuts
Airport before heading overland in a police-escorted convoy to
rain-soaked Lesotho, about 270 miles away.
   Members of Lesotho's military council greeted the pontiff at the
border, but crowds along the route into Maseru were sparse because
of the wet, chilly weather.
   John Paul did not kiss the ground in Johannesburg, as he
customarily does the first time he visits a country, and made no
public statements there. He conferred privately with Foreign
Minister Pik Botha.
   South Africa said it sent special police units into Lesotho, at
the government's request, to assist if necessary in dealing with
the hijackers. Lesotho is surrounded by South Africa.
   Robin Cartwright, pilot of the pope's chartered Air Zimbabwe
Boeing 707, earlier circled over Maseru, Lesotho's capital, for 30
minutes before deciding to divert the flight because of low clouds
and malfunctioning radio beacons at the airport.
   The pope's spokesman, Joaquin Navarro, said John Paul was
reading a book of philosophy when he was told of the problem,
looked up, and said: ``This was not on the schedule.''
   At Jan Smuts, Botha greeted the pope and accompanied him into a
VIP lounge while security forces deployed inside and outside the
terminal.
   ``We consider it a privilege to assist the Holy Father,'' said
Botha, who ordered 100 meals and several bottles of wine for the
entourage and had lunch with the pope.
   Botha said he briefed John Paul on the hijacking and discussed
the political situation in southern Africa.
   South Africans were deeply involved in logistical arrangements
for the papal visit to Lesotho. Hundreds of thousands of South
Africans had been expected to cross the border to see the pope
during his scheduled 48-hour visit, but the bad weather sharply
reduced the flow of arrivals and huge tent villages set up to
accommodate pilgrims were virtually empty.
   A hard, freezing rain fell as King Moshoeshoe and other
officials waited at the airport for hours before the announcement
that the pope would come by road.
   Rain normally is considered a sign of good luck in Lesotho, but
officials said the downpour was a disaster, disrupting the pope's
schedule and wrecking entrepreneurs' hopes of profiting from the
expected large crowds.
   Lesotho was to be the third stop on a 10-day trip also taking
the pontiff to Zimbabwe, Botswana, Swaziland and Mozambique. The
aborted flight began in Botswana.
   The Vatican has said the pope was advised by South Africa's
Catholic bishops that this was not an appropriate time for him to
visit their racially divided nation.
   South Africa's Catholic bishops have been active in the
anti-apartheid movement, particularly since 17 major black
opposition groups were banned in February.
   The white-controlled government has blamed the bishops for the
pope's decision to omit South Africa from his official itinerary.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
