<HEAD>Clews Back On FTC Payroll While Probe Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carter Clews was back on the Federal Trade
Commission payroll Wednesday while the agency looked into the
matter of letters he sent that were critical of Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   Clews left the commission last week after being given a choice
of resigning or being fired, following criticism that the letters
may have violated the Hatch Act which bans political activity by
federal workers.
   But Clews later said he was being fired without due process that
he would seek reinstatement.
   Commission general counsel Robert Paul met with Clews Wednesday
and said that the press aide was now being treated as an employee
of the commission.
   Clews will be on administrative leave, with pay, until Paul
completes an investigation and reports to Commission Chairman
Daniel Oliver, the counsel said.
   A final decision probably will be up to Oliver and the other
commissioners.
   The dispute developed after letters were sent out questioning
statements Dukakis had made about the commission and offering the
services of commission members to respond. Some letters to
newspapers included a postscript critical of Dukakis.
   At least one set carried the name of Anna Davis, public affairs
director for the agency, although she contended that wasn't her
signature. Clews, however, said that she signed and approved the
letter.
