<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 2005EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HotdogNumber     09-14 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotdog Number,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Asks That Comments Be Submitted In Writing, Not By Phone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department said Wednesday it
erred in giving out a telephone number for people to call offering
comments on a proposal to allow a mixture of salvaged meat and bone
in hotdogs without stating the ingredients on labels.
   A terse ``correction'' notice by the department's information
office said that all comments should be submitted in writing by
Nov. 8.
   Dave Warren, USDA press chief, said agency officials were ``not
prepared to take oral comments, so they'll have to be in writing.''
   The proposal was announced by USDA on Monday. It would allow
processors to include a mixture of salvaged meat, including small
bits of bone, to be used in up to 10 percent of the meat content of
hotdogs and similar items without showing the ingredients on
product labels.
   The salvaged product, designated as MS(S), or mechanically
separated (species, such as pork or beef), is made by grinding up
ribs, neckbones and other hard-to-carve parts of slaughtered
animals and forcing the mixture through sieves.
   Most of the bone particles are screened out, but some _ about
the size of ground pepper flakes _ remain in the mixture.
   Current regulations permit the MS(S) to comprise up to 20
percent of the meat portion of hotdogs, bologna and other sausages,
but the labels must state the contents.
   Processors, who asked for the exemption from the labeling rule,
said they can't sell consumers on the idea of having such a mixture
in hotdogs under the present labeling requirement.
   The written comments can be sent by Nov. 8 to: Policy Office,
Attn: Linda Carey, Hearing Clerk, Food Safety and Inspection
Service, U.S. Department of Agriculture, Room 3171-S, Washington,
D.C. 20250.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
