<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Diplomat     09-14 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Diplomat,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Demands Answers After Expulsion Of Cuban Envoys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders on Wednesday demanded an
explanation of a mysterious shooting incident that led to the swift
expulsion of the Cuban ambassador and a junior envoy, who allegedly
fired on a British security team.
   ``The Foreign Office remains mute in the face of allegations and
counter-allegations about a cloak-and-dagger intrigue which makes
James Bond read like a railway timetable,'' said the Labor Party's
foreign affairs spokesman, George Foulkes.
   The abrupt expulsion of the two diplomats and the government's
refusal to comment on a host of allegations triggered charges that
officials were trying to cover up an intelligence operation.
   Foulkes urged Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher to explain ``the
secret spider's web of espionage'' and the extent of involvement by
MI5, Britain's counter-espionage agency.
   The Foreign Office stuck to its position that Third Secretary
Carlos Manuel Medina Perez behaved improperly by opening fire
Monday afternoon in a London street, and said the circumstances
behind the shooting were irrelevant. Both Medina and Cuban
Ambassador Oscar Fernandez-Mell were expelled and left Tuesday.
   British government sources acknowledged Tuesday that Medina was
being trailed by ``security agents.''
   Officially, authorities said Medina fired at a group of three
men and a woman, slightly wounding one man. Police have interviewed
the wounded man but refused to identify him and say the case is
closed.
   Cuba's communist government said one of the men allegedly
trailing Medina Perez was Florentino Azpillaga Lombard, a former
Cuban diplomat who they say defected to the United States and is
working with the CIA.
   Cuba said he was trying to force Medina to defect.
   Reaction in Cuba was uniformly harsh.
   ``Scotland Yard amazed the world by saying that the case is
closed before being opened,'' said an editorial in the Cuban
Communist Party newspaper Granma, which was broadcast by radio and
monitored in Miami.
   ``It is not a surprise because what happened in London was one
of the more calamitous joint operations of the CIA and the British
Secret Service,'' it added.
   The editorial charged the British government, Secret Service and
the CIA ``have been caught with their hands in the cookie jar.''
   The affair highlighted what former British Foreign Secretary
David Owen said was routine surveillance of communist diplomats
suspected of spying.
   ``The more I hear about this Cuban so-called diplomat, the more
likely I think it is that he was under surveillance, and quite
rightly so,'' said Owen, foreign secretary in a Labor government
before Mrs. Thatcher's Conservative Party won power in 1979.
   Owen added that an attempt to get Medina to defect would be
``not uncommon.''
   ``There's nothing wrong with that ... the fundamental issue is
that we're not having people opening fire in the streets of London
and than claiming (diplomatic) immunity,'' he said.
</TEXT>
