<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Carlucci-Philippines     09-14 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci-Philippines,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Prepared To Move Bases If Pushed, Carlucci Warns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci bluntly
warned the Philippines' foreign secretary on Wednesday the United
States is prepared _ if pushed _ to move its military bases from
that island nation, according to Pentagon officials.
   The officials, who insisted on anonymity, said Carlucci went out
of his way during a closed-door meeting with Foreign Secretary Raul
Manglapus to stress America's support for the Philippine government
and President Corazon Aquino.
   But the defense secretary, troubled by an impasse over the
future of the Subic Bay Naval Base and Clark Air Base, told
Manglapus the United States was not bluffing over the issue of
monetary compensation ``and that there are other alternatives which
have been found to be militarily and economically feasible,'' said
one source.
   ``The secretary told him we understand the Philippines'
financial problems,'' the official continued, ``but that there are
limits for us, too.
   ``We are pretty well stretched to the edge of our limits here.
There is very little flexibility left. And Carlucci told him that
while it would be extremely unfortunate for both countries, we are
prepared to look elsewhere.''
   The sources characterized the discussions at the Pentagon as
designed to reinforce a message delivered earlier this week by
Secretary of State George P. Shultz by stressing for the first time
the Pentagon ``really is prepared to move those bases if it has
to.''
   ``We don't want to, but we will and more importantly, can,''
added one official.
   The sources said the leading candidate selected by military
planners and Carlucci as an alternative for the bases is Guam, an
island that is farther away from Asia but which offers the
advantage of being a U.S. territory.
   Manglapus came to the Pentagon on Wednesday for one-on-one talks
with Carlucci after consulting with Shultz on Tuesday. Following
his visit to the State Department, he told reporters: ``There has
been nothing to justify my saying that we are closer together.''
   The major issue in the talks is U.S. compensation to the
Philippines for use of the bases. Manglapus has declined to provide
details of the aid figures being discussed, but congressional
sources and reports in the Philippines indicate he is asking for
about $1.2 billion annually over the next two years.
   This would represent a sizeable increase over the $180 million a
year to which the Reagan administration has been committed since
1983. In addition to cash aid, the Philippines also is said to be
seeking trade concessions, debt relief and other ``soft
components,'' as Manglapus described them.
   The administration reportedly has offered $360 million yearly in
1989 and 1990 in addition to food assistance and other concessions
for a total of just under $500 million.
   Shultz said last week the Filipino demands were ``out of
bounds,'' adding that ``we will be patient and we will be
persistent'' in efforts to overcome the impasse.
   Manglapus has argued a substantial aid increase is warranted
partly to correct what he suggests is an historical injustice,
contending the United States used military facilities in the
Philippines for more than 70 years without compensating Filipino
authorities.
   In other countries, he said, the United States has provided aid
immediately after establishing military bases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
