<1ST_LINE>r w AM-North-Diaries     09-14 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North-Diaries,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Insists North Comply With 5-Month-Old Subpoena</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee voted
11-8 on Wednesday to insist that former Marine Lt. Col. Oliver L.
North comply with a subpoena it issued five months ago demanding
that he produce hundreds of pages of classified diary pages.
   The documents are sought by a Foreign Relations subcommittee
investigating international narcotics trafficking.
   North and his attorney, Brendan L. Sullivan, have resisted
producing the diaries which North maintained as an official on the
staff of the National Security Council. He was fired from that job
amid disclosures he had been involved in the secret sale of U.S.
arms to Iran and in the diversion of part of the proceeds to
Nicaragua's Contra rebels.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., the subcommittee chairman, sought the
subpoena after noticing heavily censored references to narcotics in
copies of the diaries obtained by the congressional Iran-Contra
committees.
   He said they were relevant to his panel's investigation because
of references to narcotics, to apparent links to the Contras and to
the investigation itself.
   The full committee issued the subpoena last April 26 on a 17-1
vote.
   On Wednesday, Kerry said the committee had met some of
Sullivan's objections, narrowing the scope of the subpoena to
sections of the diaries containing references relevant to the
subcommittee's probe and not insisting on receiving all 2,048 pages.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., continued to object to the decision to
pursue the subpoena, saying it was unfair when North is facing
trial in U.S. District Court here on charges growing out of the
Iran-Contra affair.
   Some senators expressed doubt that the committee can obtain the
subpoenaed documents by the time the 100th Congress adjourns next
month.
   Kerry, urging his colleagues not to accept further delay,
referred to Sullivan and said: ``Delay plays into the hands of a
very clever counselor and plays into the hands of those who want to
see all of this disappear.''
</TEXT>
