<1ST_LINE>r w AM-YouthReports     09-14 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Youth Reports,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coalition Cautions That 12 Million At-Risk Youth Threaten US
Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will have a ``soup-kitchen
workforce'' unable to take part in the technological job market of
the future unless it upgrades the critical skills of at least 12
million at-risk youth, according to reports released Wednesday.
   ``If we don't (upgrade their skills) we will continue to
increase the polarization between those at low income levels and
those at the high income levels,'' said Larry Brown, chairman of
the National Youth Employment Coalition.
   He warned that such a situation would add ``pressure put on the
social fabric of this nation which has not been seen since the
early '60s.''
   Brown, who is also president of Washington, D.C.-based 7001
Training & Employment Institute, was one of five representatives
presenting his organization's report at the coalition's press
conference, called to focus attention on ``America's Forgotten
Future: A Close-Up Look at Solving the Problems of At-Risk Children
and Youth.''
   ``At-risk'' youth are those between 14 and 24 years of age who
may be members of low income or welfare families, teenage parents,
dropouts, lack basic educational skills or have criminal records
which place them at risk for education and employment failure, the
coalition said.
   Although each report pinpointed a particular aspect of programs
designed to help youth overcome these social and economic problems,
all agreed that the problem of ill-prepared youth was one that
would come back to haunt the nation.
   Shioghan Nicolau, president of the Hispanic Policy Development
Project in New York, called for a fundamental restructuring of
middle and secondary schools to emphasize job skills and
responsibility early on.
   In ``Too Late To Patch,'' his group provided a basic primer to
successful programs for ``fast-growing '' Hispanic at-risk
populations in New York, Florida, Illinois, Texas and California.
   ``Budget priorities have virtually forced (program operators) to
emphasize the cheaper'' options, Nicolau said, noting the lack of
proper supportive services like day care and one-on-one counseling.
   Psychologist Kenneth B. Clark echoed the consensus of the
experts in a report entitled ``America's Shame, America's Hope: 12
Million Youth At Risk,'' cited at Wednesday meeting.
   ``We could not give the states of this nation a passing grade
for what has been done for youth at-risk up to now. We would have
to hand out an F. _ Still failing but at least beginnng to pay
attention in class,'' Clark's report said.
   As to the ``federal government's stewardship fo the problem we
can think of no approporiate grade _ `Absent' is the school term
that comes most readily to mind, '' the report added.
   ``We have the ways to teach poor kids. We do have the technology
and if we don't find the will, as Dr. Clark suggests, we going to
have a soup-kitchen labor force in a post-industrial economy,''
said George B. Autry, president of MDC, Inc., a non-profit Chappel
Hill, N.C.-based research group which commissioned the Clark study.
   The other reports released included:
   _ ``A Practitioner's Guide: Strategies, Programs and Resources
for Youth Employability Development'' from Public@Private Ventures,
a Philadelphia-based non-profit group which develops, researches
and manages youth training programs.
   _ ``Vanishing Dreams: The Growing Economic Plight of America's
Young Families,'' from the Children's Defense Fund, a youth
advocacy group.
   _ ``Believing Once Again: Solutions Addressing the Plight of
Challenged Youth,'' also from the 7001 Institute.
</TEXT>
