<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drugs-Customs     09-14 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drugs-Customs,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Drug Effort Still Beset By Bureaucratic Infighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bureaucratic infighting means the
administrative system being set up by the Customs Service to
oversee the federal government's anti-drug effort won't be the
centralized operation sought by Congress, a congressional watchdog
agency said Wednesday.
   The report by the General Accounting Office led two key senators
to question whether the Customs Service should spend any more money
on the system. Customs has already spent $42 million and is seeking
another $8 million.
   Six federal agencies have a role in the federal government's
increasing efforts to stem the flow of illegal drugs into the
United States.
   Two years ago, as part of an anti-drug bill, Congress ordered
the Customs Service to develop a centralized command-and-control
system to improve coordination among federal agencies.
   For example, the Customs Service and the Coast Guard now operate
separate facilities along the southern U.S. border for overseeing
planes and ships used to track drug traffickers.
   But the Drug Enforcement Agency and the Coast Guard have both
dropped out of the wide-ranging system originally envisioned by the
1986 law, the GAO noted, meaning the intent of the legislation may
not be fulfilled.
   The GAO report also noted that there are increasing
congressional demands to make the Defense Department the chief
coordination agency in the anti-drug effort, which would mean the
Customs program would be outdated.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Investigations
subcommittee, said, ``The GAO study raises serious questions
regarding the adequacy of the Customs program and whether Congress
should continue to fund it.''
   ``The GAO report highlights a series of concerns raised by a
number of senators that the Customs project has been fatally flawed
from its inception,'' said Nunn.
   Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., chairman of the Senate Budget
Committee, said, ``We were led to believe that this command and
control system would coordinate, not complicate, our drug programs.
We're throwing fuel on a fire that is out of control if we barge
ahead with this system.''
   Customs officials did not immediately return telephone calls
seeking comment. But the GAO report quoted Customs officials as
agreeing with the study's conclusions.
</TEXT>
