<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IndianFunds     09-14 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indian Funds,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bureau Signs Contract On Management Of Trust Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bureau of Indian Affairs signed a contract
Wednesday to turn over management of $1.8 billion in trust funds to
private management for the first time.
   The new manager, Security Pacific National Bank of Los Angeles,
will take over accounting, receipt and disbursement of funds for
300,000 separate accounts from the bureau and the Treasury.
   The contract runs for a year, but may be renewed annually four
times. If the bank remains manager for five years, it will be paid
$21.2 million. The government would pay about $1 million to convert
its accounting system to the bank's specifications, which will take
about a year.
   To keep on managing the accounts in-house would cost the
government $25 million over the same period, said bureau spokesman
Carl Shaw.
   ``Where we'll really gain is in the electronic transfer of
funds,'' Shaw said.
   Checks being mailed from office to office now can take several
days, during which money is not earning interest. The bank-operated
system should enable receipts to start earning interest much
sooner, Shaw said.
   The bureau may invest trust funds only in government securities
or federally insured accounts in banks and savings and loan
associations. The bank will not make actual investment decisions,
only recommendations to the bureau, which retains legal
responsibility for the investments.
   The bureau had planned to award the contract to Mellon National
Bank of Pittsburgh, but following complaints from tribes that they
had not been adequately consulted and from the Treasury and other
banks that specifications had been too narrowly drawn, the bureau
re-opened competition for the contract in March 1987.
</TEXT>
