<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-14 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Showers Remain over the Central Plains</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Rain continued to drench the Plains on Wednesday, and Gulf Coast
residents were told to begin preparing for high tides in advance of
Hurricane Gilbert.
   Rain showers Wednesday afternoon reached from Nebraska across
Kansas, Oklahoma, Colorado and Wyoming.
   Skies were cloudy over much of New England, the northern Plains,
the northern Rockies and the southern coast of California. Skies
were generally sunny over the remainder of the nation.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
about three-quarters of an inch at Grand Island, Neb., and Dalhart,
Texas.
   Hurricane Gilbert plowed across Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula
toward the Gulf of Mexico coast of Texas at about 15 mph, with
maximum sustained winds of about 160 mph.
   Tropical storm winds extended 250 miles from the center to the
north, and 200 miles from the center to the south.
   Tides up to 4 feet above sea level were possible by sunrise
Thursday on the Texas coast. Galveston County officials recommended
evacuation of Bolivar Peninsula, which has about 3,000 residents
northeast of Galveston Island.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 46
degrees at Riverton, Wyo., to 96 degrees at Yuma, Ariz. The low
temperature for the nation Wednesday morning was 23 degrees at
Elko, Nev.
   The national weather forecast for Thursday called for rain
showers in the central Plains, western Iowa and Missouri, the lower
Mississippi Valley and the Florida Panhandle. Cloudy skies were
expected over the upper Mississippi Valley and the remainder of the
northern Plains, the Texas Gulf Coast and the northern Pacific
Coast.
   High temperatures in the 50s were predicted for northern Maine
and 60s in the remainder of New England across inland New York and
Upper Michigan, northeast Minnesota, the central Rockies and the
northern Pacific Coast. Highs in the 90s should extend from the
lower Atlantic Coast across the Gulf of Mexico states, and the
southern Plains, with 70s and 80s elsewhere, except 90s to about
105 degrees in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
