<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--Dukakis-Mass     09-14 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Dukakis-Mass,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Announces $67 Million State Surplus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
announced Wednesday that the state finished last fiscal year with a
$67 million surplus.
   The Massachusetts governor said $25 million had been expected
and was already credited to the books for the $11.6 billion fiscal
1989 budget, $26 had to be earmarked under law for a ``rainy day''
account, and the rest may be used to fund some programs that were
conditionally vetoed because of budget problems.
   One critic said Dukakis achieved the surplus by cutting back on
human services spending late in fiscal 1988, which ended June 30.
Another, the Republican House minority leader, said any surplus
would be the product of tax and fee increases, government borrowing
and a ``raid'' on the pension fund.
   Dukakis has campaigned on his record as a fiscal manager.
</TEXT>
