<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 2055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti     09-14 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishop, Political Foe Doubt Army Rulers Will Punish Killers,
Arsonists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ A bishop and an opposition leader
expressed doubt Wednesday that Haiti's military rulers will live up
to their promise to punish thugs who massacred nine parishioners
and burned down two churches.
   ``We call on God to help us surmount this bloody, ferocious
dictatorship,'' Bishop Willie Romelus of the western town of
Jeremie said on the Roman Catholic Church's Radio Soleil.
   Serge Gilles, co-leader of the leftist Patriotic Unity Bloc,
said Sunday's massacre ``happened under the very nose of the army
and police, and they did not intervene to prevent the bloodshed.''
   The government said Tuesday night it ``regretted'' the massacre
at St. Jean Bosco Church, when two dozen hoodlums killed nine
people at Mass and wounded 77, then burned down the building as
soldiers watched from an army compound across the street.
   Radio Haiti Inter said thugs burst into the state-run general
hospital Tuesday searching for a survivor of the church massacre, a
32-year-old woman, saying they wanted ``to finish her off.''
   The unidentified woman and her daughter, then still in the womb,
were wounded Sunday when an assailant stabbed them with a skewer.
Doctors saved both. The gang left without finding the woman, the
station reported Wednesday.
   Authorities also promised to find and punish those responsible
for burning down another church late Monday night.
   ``It is difficult to have confidence in the promises of the
military government,'' Gilles said.
   Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy's government has issued statements of
regret in the past following mass murders and political
assassinations but no convictions resulted.
   Five men and a woman appeared on state television boasting they
took part in the massacre, which they said was directed at the Rev.
Jean Bertrand Aristide, an outspoken critic of the army. They
threatened ``a heap of corpses'' if Aristide holds future Masses.
   The six made no attempt to hide their identity and spoke on the
government network without apparent fear of arrest or reprisals.
   Romelus, Aristide's uncle and the most radical of Haiti's 10
bishops, said, ``If the leaders of the government are not
responsible shouldn't they have arrested them (the six)
immediately?''
   He said the military government ``deplored and condemned and
promised to arrest only after other countries made their
declarations.''
   The Inter-American Commission on Human Rights of the
Organization of American States accused the government of allowing
the massacre.
   ``The police stood by during the attacks,'' said a statement
issued by OAS offices in Washington and Port-au-Prince. ``Since
there is a military post very near the church the commission can
only conclude that this attack was perpetrated at least with the
acquiescence of the government.''
   The commission had sent a fact-finding mission to Haiti last
month.
   Namphy returned to power after ousting the 4-month-old civilian
government of President Leslie Manigat on June 19. Namphy
previously headed a junta which ruled this impoverished Caribbean
nation for two years following dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier's
flight into French exile.
</TEXT>
