<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 2058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh     09-14 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Rises, Health Official Calls For More Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flood waters receded Wednesday but the
death toll kept climbing, and health officials called for
international shipments of water-treatment chemicals and medicines
to stop a killer epidemic of diarrhea.
   Health Secretary Manzurul Karim on Wednesday said there have
been 319,860 official cases of diarrhea and 168 diarrhea-related
deaths since Aug. 27. On Tuesday, officials reported 283,703
official cases and 150 deaths.
   Karim said pharmaceutical companies were working overtime to
manufacuture medicines to battle the outbreak of diarrhea caused by
floodwaters filled with sewage.
   ``Bangladesh does not need foreign doctors but will welcome
limited quantity of medicines from the friendly countries,'' he
said at a news conference.
   ``Bangladesh needs 75 million water purification tablets out of
which it will produce 25 million units locally. We have instructed
local companies to produce various life-saving drugs in double
shifts,'' he said.
   Mohamed Elnaggar, a World Health Organization representative in
Dhaka, said most cases of diarrhea are not being reported to the
hospitals.
   What is believed to be the worst flooding in Bangladesh history
has caused 1,804 deaths from drowning, snake bites, collapsed
buildings and diarrhea, according to daily reports in Dhaka
newspapers. Officials reports, routinely lower, put the death toll
at 899 as of Wednesday.
   The monsoon flooding has affected more than 30 million people in
three-fourths of this country, which is roughly the size of
Wisconsin.
   The real number is impossible to ascertain, given Bangladesh's
unwieldy bureaucracy and communications that were poor even before
the floods.
   Meanwhile, the Flood Control Center said Wednesday that water
levels in all major rivers were falling fast.
   In Dhaka, authorities were pumping water from the main
commercial district of Motijheel and some residential areas. But
the pumping was causing new flooding in some areas where water had
begun to recede.
   Jay F. Morris, deputy director of the U.S. Agency for
International Development, signed an agreement in Dhaka Wednesday
to provide $20 million in wheat to Bangladesh, the U.S. Embassy
said here.
   ``This agreement represents an acceleration of our proposed
level of $60 million for financial year 1989 to provide the
government of Bangladesh needed flexibility to respond to food
shortage that may occur over next few months,'' Morris said in a
statement.
   ``Shipment of remaining $40 million worth of foodgrains will be
determined once the full extent of crop loss due to the flooding is
known,'' he said.
   The United States in the last two weeks committed nearly $154
million in flood aid to Bangladesh for meeting the emergency caused
by the flooding, the statement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880914-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 2026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Brezhnev 1stLd-Writethru a0747 09-14 0808</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Brezhnev, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,0828</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brezhnev's Grandson Criticizes Smear Campaign, Debate Sharpens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADD 4 grafs detailing Brezhnev-Khrushchev dealings. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leonid I. Brezhnev's grandson said in an article
published Wednesday that growing criticism of the former Soviet
leader has turned into a smear campaign that is hurting him and
other family members.
   But a second article by a well-known journalist indicated the
attacks on Brezhnev, centered on the bribery trial of his
son-in-law, Yuri Churbanov, is not about to stop.
   The journalist, Fyodor Burlatsky, also shed some light on how
Brezhnev assumed power from Nikita S. Khrushchev in 1964.
   The two articles sharpened the debate over the 1964-1982 period
when Brezhnev was in power. An investigation of the Brezhnev era
has overtaken the re-evaluation of Josef Stalin's repression as the
major historical topic under review in the Soviet press.
   Criticism of previous leaders, under way on a large scale in the
more open atmosphere of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms, is
nevertheless traditional in the Soviet system, and often gives
citizens an indirect clue about where the leadership wants to take
the country.
   ``I'm 27 years old, and my independent life is only beginning,
but I already feel that my surname ever more frequently has become
a stumbling block in the most varied situations,'' Andrei Brezhnev
wrote in the weekly Moscow News.
   ``I want to be just like everyone, I am just like everyone, but
many don't want to see anything in me except my surname,'' he said.
   He said much of the current criticism of Brezhnev for bringing
in a period of stagnation and corruption, is justified, but that
his grandfather also was a victim of the political system and is
being unfairly blamed for mistakes of his aides.
   The younger Brezhnev said tales of the family's corrupt and
opulent lifestyle while his grandfather was in office were partly a
result of the lack of information Soviets have about their leaders'
private life, and partly a result of the actions of his aunt,
Brezhnev's daughter Galina, who he described as ``uncontrollable.''
   Churbanov, charged in a trial that opened Sept. 5 with fostering
a huge network of bribery and corruption in the republic of
Uzbekistan, is married to Galina.
   The younger Brezhnev said he went to a normal school and did not
associate with the children of high party officials.
   The sharp criticism of Brezhnev continued Wednesday on the pages
of the authoritative weekly Literary Gazette.
   Burlatsky, who was ousted from his job in the International
Department of the Communist Party Central Committee during
Brezhnev's years, said Brezhnev was a weak man who knew only how to
work the giant party and government apparatus.
   Soviet society must find out ``how it could happen that in such
a difficult period in the history of our motherland, and in the
world's history, that the weakest of all leaders who reached this
position in Soviet, and perhaps in prerevolutionary times, was at
the wheel of management.''
   He said Brezhnev ``cultivated with almost childlike simplicity
the accessories of his cult.''
   He said Brezhnev was a ``master of compromise'' who knew how to
place his supporters in the middle and high levels of the party and
government apparatus.
   Those surrounding Brezhnev ``thirsted only for one thing _ that
this person would live forever _ that's how good things were for
them,'' Burlatsky said.
   He said that Brezhnev was considered a weak and transitional
figure by other party leaders who wanted to get rid of Khrushchev
because of his erratic policies.
   Khrushchev's ouster was orchestrated not by Brezhnev or
conservative party ideology chief Mikhail Suslov, but by former KGB
chief Alexander Shelepin, he said.
   Shelepin led a group that plotted against Khrushchev in meetings
in football stadiums and other unlikely places, he said.
   In a key move, Shelepin successfully changed Khrushchev's
personal guard when he was called back from vacation for the
Central Committee meeting at which he was replaced. That tipped
Khrushchev off, and he tried to stop the flight taking him to
Moscow, but he could not, Burlatsky said.
   Burlatsky said a speech by Alexei Adzhubei, Khrushchev's
son-in-law and editor of the government newspaper Izvestia, served
as impetus to call the meeting.
   He said Adzhubei suggested that Moscow saw no great problems
preventing reunification of East and West Germany. ``The leaders of
... (Communist East Germany) quickly expressed their indignation to
their Soviet colleagues, and this served as the spark that lit the
flame.''
   Burlatsky said Brezhnev was in debt to Khrushchev for advancing
his party career, with Brezhnev moving up steadily in the Ukrainian
party apparatus while Khrushchev was at its head.
   The journalist noted the two leaders' opposite approaches to
policy. He said Khrushchev was bold and took risks while Brezhnev
tried to minimize risk and was very cautious.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
