<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Kenya-Poachers,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Orders Park Rangers to Shoot Poachers on Sight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel arap Moi has ordered park
rangers to shoot poachers on sight, Nairobi newspapers reported
Wednesday.
   ``Officials should inform people about this so that innocent
wananchi (people) do not loiter in the game parks and be caught
unaware,'' Moi said.
   Moi's shoot-on-sight order Tuesday followed the government's
suspension of mining and prospecting in Kenya's 53 national parks
and reserves, a move aimed at stopping poachers who are decimating
this East African nation's elephant herd.
   Studies by the U.N. Environmental Program show that in the last
15 years, the elephant population has dropped 85 percent in Kenya.
An aerial survey in February of the vast Tsavo National Park in
southeastern Kenya found 5,363 elephants, down from an estimated
35,000 in that park alone in 1974.
