<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0772,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Tours Missile-Detection Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS three grafs to UPDATE with Albuquerque appearance, some
editing to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle said Wednesday that Soviet
test-launching of an SS-25 mobile intercontinental ballistic
missile showed the United States needs to develop mobile strategic
missiles, something he said would never happen if Democrat Michael
Dukakis is elected president.
   Quayle, the Republican vice presidential nominee who is a member
of the Senate Armed Services Committee, said he was told of the
test by officials of NORAD, the joint U.S.-Canada warning system.
The senator toured a NORAD facility earlier in the day.
   Quayle said he was told that the Soviets launched the SS-25 at
8:50 a.m. EDT from Plesetsk, aimed at Kamchatka, just across the
Bering Sea from Alaska. The Soviets informed the United States of
the launch, he said.
   The Soviets have two types of mobile ICBM missiles, the SS-25
and the SS-24.
   The United States does not presently have mobile
intercontinental ballistic missiles, although two such missiles _
the Midgetman and the Rail Mobile MX _ have been under development.
U.S. intercontinental ballistic missiles presently are in concrete
silos buried in the ground.
   Dukakis ``is opposing modernization of our land-based missile
force, while the Soviets are already ahead of us,'' Quayle said.
   ``The governor has already stated that he opposes flight testing
of our missiles so even if he wanted to develop a deterrent, his
flight test ban would prevent us from ensuring that the system
would work,'' Quayle said.
   ``Do we want someone with the governor's views sitting across
the negotiating table from Mr. (Mikhail) Gorbachev?'' he added.
   Dukakis, in a speech in Washington on Wednesday, called the MX,
which he opposes, a ``sitting duck.'' He said, ``The strategic
concept of the Midgetman is sound, but I question the value of
spending $40 billion or $50 billion for 500 additional land-based
missile warheads _ at three times the cost of the same number of
new submarine-based warheads.''
   It was a day in which Quayle continued his attack on Dukakis,
portraying him as weak on defense and foreign policy issues.
   The United State could never have achieved the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty ``if the nuclear freeze
advocated by Michael Dukakis had been adopted,'' Quayle said.
   ``The only thing he would have frozen in place was a dangerous,
destabilizing Soviet medium-range nuclear monopoly in Europe,''
Quayle said.
   Quayle spoke to the Denver Kiwanis-Rotary clubs, where several
hundred protesters staged a noisy demonstration as he arrived. They
carried signs reading ``Bush, Cocaine, Contra'' and ``A Vote for
Quayle is a Vote for Death.''
   In his speech, the second this week to hit Dukakis on defense,
Quayle said the Massachusetts governor did not understand the need
for such weapons as the MX and Midgetman missiles and for the Star
Wars space-based missile defense system.
   The proposed defense shield, said Quayle, ``is a moral, superior
way of defending America.''
   Bush, like the Soviets, understands the importance of a missile
defense system, Quayle said.
   ``George Bush doesn't need a primer on national security.
Neither do I,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle toured NORAD, the North American Aerospace Defense
Command center near Colorado Springs. He received a briefing on the
system, which provides a warning in the event of space, missile or
air attack on North America.
   The senator saw a simulated attack by the Soviets and ``how we
would handle that,'' said Gen. John Piotrowski, the NORAD commander.
   The demonstration took place in the steel buildings embedded
under 1,700 feet of granite at Cheyenne Mountain.
   The news media were barred from entering the NORAD complex,
Piotrowski said, because of a federal law which bars political
campaigning at military installations.
   At a rally later at a Colorado Springs airport hangar, Quayle
was heckled by demonstrators who held signs reading ``Students
Unite Against Bush-Quayle'' and who chanted, ``Where was Dan?'' as
he began to speak.
   Gesturing to the protesters, Quayle said, ``Some of those, they
keep walking around in circles. We have a message to talk about.
The people that they support, Michael Dukakis, he doesn't have a
message, he doesn't have any ideas. He doesn't know where to lead
this country.''
   ``He got on a tank, I saw the other day,'' Quayle said. ``Glad
he knows what one looks like.''
   The combination of heckling from the crowd and Dukakis-baiting
by Quayle continued at the New Mexico state fair in Alburquerque,
where Dukakis supporters chanting ``Go Home Quayle,'' shouted
throughout Quayle's speech.
   ``As you listen to this babble over here, you can't help but
think of the Dukakis positions,'' Quayle said. ``They have no
positions. They're loud but they don't have any ideas.
   ``I understand you have a balloon festival coming up the
governor of Massachusetts has a lot of hot air, why don't you
invite him?''
</TEXT>
