<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Jamaica 1st-LdWritethru a0795 09-14 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Jamaica, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0795,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Private Aid En Route to Hurricane Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with information on other relief efforts</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal and private groups announced Wednesday
that they have begun marshaling forces to send relief to victims of
Hurricane Gilbert in Jamaica, the Yucatan Peninsula of Mexico and
the Gulf Coast of the United States.
   The United States is $396,000 worth of relief supplies to
Jamaica, the Agency for International Development said. The
supplies include 360 rolls of plastic sheeting, 200 tents, 3,966
water jugs, 18 water tanks, 10 chain saw kits and 9,600 cotton
blankets.
   A portion of the assistance was flown by the military from a
U.S. stockpile in Panama on Wednesday.
   The American Red Cross also announced it had begun sending
emergency supplies to four hurricane ``watch'' districts being
established in Texas as Gilbert made its way toward the U.S. Gulf
Coast.
   The Red Cross said thousands of blankets, cots, comfort kits and
cleanup kits were on their way to Corpus Christi, Harlingen,
Houston and Beaumont, Texas. In addition, volunteers and staff
members have been sent to San Antonio, Texas, and Birmingham, Ala.
which have been established as staging areas for deployment after
the storm hits.
   The organization also said ``watch'' districts set up since last
week during Hurricane Florence in Baton Rouge and New Orleans, La.
were being maintained.
   Partners of the Americas, a group of 60 countries including the
United States and nations in Latin America and the Caribbean
announced it had set up a special relief fund to help the people of
Jamaica and Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula.
   The group is seeking cash donations to purchase ``roofing
materials, plastic sheeting, strong soaps, disinfectants,
mattresses, beds and bed linens,'' said William Reese, president of
the group which was established in 1964 as part of the Alliance for
Progress.
   The group is not in a position to accept clothing or food
donations, Reese said.
   Individuals interested in contributing to either relief effort
can do so through their local Red Cross chapter or send donations
to:
   _The American Red Cross, P.O. Box 37243, Washington, D.C. 20013
and
   _Partners of the Americas, Hurricane Gilbert Relief Fund, 1424 K
St., N.W., Suite 700, Washington, D.C. 20005.
</TEXT>
