<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0802 09-14 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0802,0761</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Leaders Reject Arafat Overtures; 20 Arabs Wounded</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-2 UPDATE casualties. PICKS up 3rd pvs, Masked
assailants ...; 3 grafs SUB for grafs 21-22 pvs, Troop gunfire . ..
to UPDATE with later casualties. PICKS up 23rd pvs, Assailants
dragged ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli leaders on Wednesday spurned the latest
overture by PLO leader Yasser Arafat, who used the Hebrew greeting
``Shana Tova'' to wish Israelis a happy new year on the Jewish
holiday.
   In the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, troops shot and
wounded 20 Palestinians, hospital officials said. The army
confirmed 13 casualties among demonstrators.
   Masked assailants in the West Bank city of Nablus stabbed to
death an Arab suspected of collaborating with Israel.
   Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization, used
the Hebrew greeting _ the equivalent of Happy New Year _ at a news
conference in Strasbourg, France, on Wednesday, a day after he
addressed Socialist members of the European Parliament.
   In his speech, Arafat said the PLO was working toward the
establishment of a Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, and accepted all U.N. resolutions, including 242 and 338
which recognize Israel's right to exist.
   Reaction by top Israelis was icy.
   ``It is a new year's blessing calling for the destruction of the
state of Israel,'' said Moshe Arens, head of the right-wing Likud
bloc's campaign for the Nov. 1 general elections.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin of the left-of-center Labor Party
told supporters at a campaign rally in Jerusalem that ``the PLO is
not a partner for talks.''
   ``Seven weeks have gone by since King Hussein'' of Jordan
announced he was cutting his links with the West Bank and handing
over responsibility to the PLO, said Rabin. ``The PLO is incapable
of taking up the challenge, even in words.''
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, Labor's leader, criticized
European Parliament legislators for receiving Arafat.
   ``All of sudden, they started one more time to fall in love with
the PLO,'' Peres told Israel radio from London, where he met on
Wednesday with British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   Peres said he was reassured by Mrs. Thatcher. He said she
``objects vigorously to the creation of a Palestinian state in
exile.''
   Palestinian leaders appeared split over Arafat's statements.
   Hathem Abu Ghazale, a prominent PLO supporter in the West Bank,
said, ``Arafat's visit is a Palestinian breakthrough in the
countries where the Zionist movement was born and later developed.''
   But deposed Gaza City Mayor Rashad Shawwa said Arafat was
``running around in empty circles.''
   PLO hardliners and Moslem fundamentalist groups oppose a
unilateral declaration of a Palestinian government-in-exile because
it would imply recognition of Israel.
   Israeli peace activist Abie Nathan, who defied Israeli law to
meet Arafat in Tunis this week, told Israel Television from
Strasbourg the PLO was ready to negotiate peace with Israel.
   ``I believe that today ... we are closer to peace than ever
before,'' Nathan said.
   Palestinian youths on Wednesday stoned Israeli troops and burned
tires in the Gaza Strip refugee camps of Khan Yunis and Shati.
   Troop gunfire wounded nine Palestinians in Khan Yunis and seven
in Shati, including two teen-agers who were in serious condition,
said Arab hospital officials. The army confirmed seven wounded in
Khan Yunis and three in Shati.
   In the West Bank village of Beit Lid near Tulkarem, soldiers
fired to disperse villagers resisting an army raid, an army
official said. Three Palestinians were wounded and several
Palestinians were arrested, he said.
   Another Palestinian was wounded in a clash in the West Bank
village Burquin near Nablus, hospital officials said.
   Assailants dragged 30-year-old Palestinian Adli Thalga from his
Nablus home and stabbed him to death. He allegedly collaborated
with Israeli authorities.
   Seven Palestinians accused of cooperating with Israel have been
killed the Palestinian rebellion began on Dec. 8 in the
Israeli-occupied territories. The uprising has claimed the lives of
265 Palestinians and six Israelis.
   Thalga was the fifth alleged collaborator to be killed in 10
days following a call from Palestinian uprising leaders to ``rid
ourselves of collaborators.''
   Rabin meanwhile attacked proposals raised by some Likud
politicians to annex large parts of the West Bank, saying it would
turn Israel into ``a racist, apartheid state.''
   ``Racism and Judaism don't go together,'' he said.
   But Rabin said Israel would not hand back all lands captured in
the 1967 Middle East war.
</TEXT>
