<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SierraFire-Firefighters     09-14 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sierra Fire-Firefighters,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crews Have It Lousy But Say They Love It</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRASS VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They sleep on the ground after 24
hours or more of potentially deadly work, gobble cold food when
they get the chance, and shower off layers of sweat-streaked dirt
every few days.
   But firefighters say they love their jobs.
   It's action: carving bare-earth control lines with shovels or
bulldozers, dousing flames with hoses, piloting helicopters that
drop water from buckets. It's better than some boring job, they
say, or just sitting around at a fire station.
   And, they add, their efforts are usually appreciated.
   A sign at an entrance to a firefighters' camp at the Nevada
County fairgrounds Wednesday said, ``We Love You Firefighters.''
Red hearts were plastered around the message to nearly 3,000
firefighters who began battling a huge blaze Sunday near this gold
country community 45 miles northeast of Sacramento.
   ``I'm going to make a career out of firefighting,'' said David
McLean, 25, who drives a fire engine during the summer for the
California Department of Forestry. ``I like the outdoors and I like
the action. I love it.''
   McLean and his crew of seasonal firefighters from El Dorado
County were among state forces from throughout central California
that first attacked the ``49er Fire,'' which burned more than
30,000 acres in four days, razing nearly 100 homes.
   ``We worked almost 40 hours straight, from Sunday morning to
Monday night. We ate C-rations when we had the time and finally got
our first hot meal after we were relieved and sent to fire camp,''
said McLean, who is a Santa Cruz carpenter in the off-season.
   ``Then I got my first shower in a couple days,'' he said.
``After that long, it's always the best shower of your life.''
   Like most others at the sprawling camp, McLean and his crew
bedded down in paper sleeping bags on the ground, with clothing for
pillows.
   Among those sprawled across the grass and draped on fire trucks
from state, federal and local agencies were plenty of female
firefighters.
   Forestry department seasonal firefighter Talley Tarris, 23, of
Sacramento, said she's often asked why a woman would want to battle
flames.
   ``I like being grimy and not sleeping,'' she said, laughing.
   ``We're one big happy family,'' Tarris added.
   Not everyone fighting fires has it as rough as the ground troops.
   The crews that operate helicopters, which carry water in buckets
to douse hot spots, were based next to the firefighters' camp but
slept 30 miles away in a motel so they would be properly rested.
   Even those crews don't always take advantage of the
comparatively posh arrangement, however.
   ``Sometimes it's more of a pain to go in (to a motel) than it's
worth,'' said pilot Jim Ramage of Redding. ``Then we just sleep on
the ground, too.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
