<HEAD>CBS' `48 Hours' Does Quick Switch to Live Show on Hurricane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS' weekly news show ``48 Hours'' is doing a
quick switch Thursday to live coverage of Hurricane Gilbert rather
than the previously planned taped report on infertility.
   The storm gave ``48 Hours'' a chance to do what it was
originally designed to do _ provide an instant prime-time platform
for a breaking news story.
   CBS News spokesman Tom Goodman said Dan Rather would anchor the
broadcast that will include reports from 14 correspondents
hurriedly dispatched to the Caribbean, where the storm has already
caused devastation and killed at least 11 people in Jamaica; to
Mexico, which was being battered by 160 mph winds on Wednesday; and
across the gulf coast areas of the United States, which were
bracing for the arrival of the storm, described as one of the
strongest ever.
   Eight correspondents were sent to Texas, including Harry Smith
to co-anchor ``CBS This Morning'' from Galveston, Goodman said.
</TEXT>
