<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Cousins     09-14 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Cousins,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retired Milwaukee Archbishop William Cousins Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Milwaukee Roman Catholic Archbishop
William Cousins died Wednesday from complications from pneumonia,
church officials said. He was 86.
   Cousins also had been suffering from brain cancer, said Gregory
Bell, spokesman for the archdiocese.
   ``Since coming to the archdiocese as his successor in 1977, I
have held William Cousins in highest esteem,'' said Archbishop
Rembert G. Weakland. ``His gentleness, humility and concern for
people have been an inspiration to all who knew him.
   Cousins, archbishop in Milwaukee from 1959 through 1977, died at
the St. Anne's Home for the Elderly, where he lived. He had been
hospitalized at St. Joseph's Hospital, where he was treated for
pneumonia until late last week.
   In mid-August, he fell at St. Anne's and injured his head. He
was hospitalized at that time and the brain tumor was discovered.
He later returned to St. Anne's, but was re-admitted when he
developed pneumonia Sept. 5.
   A native of Chicago, Cousins was auxilliary bishop there from
1949-52. He was bishop of Peoria, Ill. from 1952-59.
</TEXT>
