<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Arafat 1stLd-Writethru a0718 09-14 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arafat, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0718,0774</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Leader Wishes Israelis `Shana Tova'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with King
Hussein's comments. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO leader Yasser Arafat on Wednesday
wished Israel ``Happy New Year'' in Hebrew, but Israeli officials
dismissed it as a public relations ploy.
   Arafat also got a message from another quarter Wednesday _ King
Hussein of Jordan. Hussein said that since his kingdom cut ties
with the Israeli-occupied West Bank on July 30, it is up to the
Palestinians to solve their own problems and they have no one to
blame but themselves if they fail.
   Arafat, addressing Abie Nathan, a controversial Israeli radio
personality and peace crusader, said at a news conference earlier
Wednesday:
   ``I ask you to tell all Israelis and ... all Jews `Shana Tova'
on this occasion of the Jewish New Year.
   ``When I say Shana Tova, I mean ... in particular a peaceful New
Year,'' said the chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
``A peaceful New Year for all of our children, for all of our
peoples, for the whole of the Arab region.''
   Jews throughout the world at sundown Tuesday ended celebrations
ushering in Rosh Hashana, the Jewish new year.
   Speaking in Arabic through interpreters, Arafat addressed
reporters on the last day of a two-day visit to the European
Parliament at the invitation of the body's Socialist group.
   Arafat said the willingness of European and other governments to
recognize a provisional Palestinian government on the West Bank
would influence a decision to establish such a government.
   He urged the United States to be ``more fair'' towards the
Palestinians.
   ``The United States has to stand for justice and fairness and
should not just think of electoral considerations,'' he said.
   An Israeli Foreign Ministry official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Arafat's New Year greeting was a ``stunt.''
   ``It's very nice to say `Shana Tova' in front of a group of
journalists, but it would be more constructive if in his speech
yesterday there were some concrete change in policy,'' the official
said.
   He was referring to a meeting Tuesday in which Arafat told the
European Parliament's socialists that Jordan's decision to cut its
ties to the West Bank would pave the way for an independent
Palestinian state.
   Israeli officials reject such a state.
   Yossi Ahimeir, a spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir,
said Arafat's gesture would not change the right-wing Likud Party's
opposition to holding talks with the PLO.
   ``We will not be misled by the lip service of Mr. Arafat and
seeming gestures like wishing `Shana Tova' to our people,'' Ahimeir
said.
   Arafat said the Palestine National Council, the Palestinians'
parliament-in-exile, will make a final decision next month on a
provisional government or place the occupied territories under U.N.
trusteeship.
   King Hussein's remarks came during a taped interview with the
``World Monitor'' television program in London.
   In the interview, broadcast Wednesday and monitored in Boston,
Hussein said he did not believe a ``Jordanian option'' now existed
in dealing with the Palestinian question.
   The monarch said that while Jordan remained ``committed ... to
the cause of a just and durable peace ... as far as the Palestinian
dimension is concerned, the Palestinian problem is in the hands of
the Palestinians.''
   He said he hoped that the Israelis now ``would realize that
there has to be a facing of reality and ... come up with their
contribution for the establishment of a just and good peace in the
area.''
   Hussein said Jordan would attend an international Middle East
peace conference only if asked to do so by the PLO _ ``and we'll
have to look at it then.''
   When asked if he thought whether Arafat's organization was
moving in the right direction, Hussein replied, ``Well, there is
certainly no other quarter to blame if they fail to do so.''
   He said, ``The PLO claims to be the sole legitimate
representative (of the Palestinian people) and I believe it's going
to be up to it to prove that this is the case ... Ideally it should
be a simultaneous kind of recognition: Israel recognizing the
Palestinians and their rights on their soil, and ... the
Palestinians acting in a way that would recognize Israel's right to
exist on its soil.''
   He said that if the Palestinian uprising in the occupied lands
continues to a point when all hope is lost, ``then it's downhill
and into an abyss ... nobody can forecast what can happen.''
</TEXT>
