<1ST_LINE>u a AM-YokoResponse 1stLd-Writethru a0769 09-14 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yoko Response, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0769,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yoko Ono Repsonds to Goldman Book</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout, UPDATING with excerpts from interview; no
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yoko Ono, widow of slain rock star John Lennon,
dismissed author Albert Goldman's controversial version of the
couple's life together and apart as ``totally fiction'' Wednesday
in a nationally broadcast radio show.
   ``These people in this book are not us. It's not John and me,''
Ono said in her first broadcast comments on ``The Lives of John
Lennon'' biography. `` It's unfair he's been assaulted and can't
hit back.''
   The rare appearance Wednesday night by Ono was prompted by
Goldman's 719-page biography of the ex-Beatle which presents him as
an anorexic, bisexual, drug-addicted drunk who wanted to dump his
wife.
   Ono doesn't fare much better: Goldman presents her as a
gold-digger who snorted heroin up to the time of Lennon's death and
had several affairs while they were married. Goldman also charges
she was responsible for Paul McCartney's 1980 marijuana bust in
Japan and was just as intent on a divorce as Lennon.
   Ono denied virtually all of these charges, and countered through
taped interviews with Lennon friends and employees that Goldman's
book was based on unreliable sources and misquotes.
   ``For some reason this book is attempting to rob both John and I
of the basic human dignity that we're entitled to,'' she said
shortly after the broadcast opened with Lennon's song ``Gimme Some
Truth.''
   ``It's amazing that somebody took such a poetic license. I don't
see John in there. ... It's a very dramatically described
something, but it's not about John,'' said Ono. ``It's totally
fiction.''
   The one-hour broadcast was taped Aug. 28 at the Dakota, where
the Lennons lived _ and Yoko still lives _ in Manhattan. The
broadcast coincides with the book's official release date, which
was also on Wednesday.
   Lennon was fatally shot by Mark David Chapman outside the Dakota
on Dec. 8, 1980.
   The Ono interview was broadcast nationwide via the Westwood One
Network; spokeswoman Laurie Wilde said a total number of the
stations picking up the broadcast was not available.
   Appearing with Ono were Lennon's sons, Julian and Sean. Ono is
interviewed by long-time associate Elliot Mintz, described in
Goldman's book as a spy for Yoko.
   ``It is for one, very upsetting, but most of all it is lies,
untruths ... The whole thing is just sickening,'' said Julian, who
also denied Goldman's stories about Lennon as a terrifying father.
   Mintz read excerpts from the Goldman book to Yoko, who then
responded to the allegations made by the author point by point. She
denied Lennon was a homosexual; denied he was using drugs while
living at the Dakota with his son, Sean; denied he had become a
reclusive rock 'n' roll Howard Hughes.
   She did acknowledge having a heroin problem during the late
1970s, but rejected Goldman's assertion that she had a
$5,000-a-week habit.
   The book already has drawn angry responses from friends of
Lennon and Ono; McCartney, who denied one anecdote involving a
violent Lennon smashing a painting in Paul's home, has urged a
boycott of the book.
   After Ono's rebuttal, listeners were invited to dial 900
telephone numbers to vote on whether the Goldman book is an
accurate portrayal of the Lennons' life. Results were not expected
until Thursday.
   Goldman, who conducted more than 1,200 interviews for his Lennon
book, has previously written controversial biographies of comedian
Lenny Bruce and Elvis Presley.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880914-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 2255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     09-14 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Revival of `Blues in the Night' Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's hard to get through the night when your man
has done you wrong and then gone. So wail the three lonely ladies
of ``Blues in the Night,'' a minor musical meditation on the blues
that opened Wednesday at off-Broadway's Minetta Lane Theater.
   The show is a recast, slightly revised revival of the musical
revue that had a 53-performance run on Broadway in 1982. This new
version had some success in London before resurfacing in New York
with a cast that includes Brenda Pressley, Leilani Jones and, from
the British production, Carol Woods.
   Despite the classy performers, it's difficult to work up much
enthusiasm for the show. ``Blues in the Night'' is a strange,
anonymous musical with a one-note message and characters that
rarely connect with each other, much less the audience.
   Its women, worn down by men and by life, are identified only as
the lady from the road, the woman of the world and the girl with a
date. They occupy separate rooms in a cheap hotel in some unknown
city. The time is the late 1930s and the hour, of course, is after
midnight.
   The songs are distinctive, most of them well-known classics, but
the themes they express are basically the same. The numbers,
expertly played by a five-piece band perched above the hotel
setting, usually fall into two categories. There's the bluesy
lament for all those men who got away, and dirty, double-entendre
ditties like ``Kitchen Man'' or ``Take Me for a Buggy Ride,''
performed with gusto by the formidable Miss Woods.
   Each member of the cast _ including Lawrence Hamilton as the
evening's generic man _ gets a song or two in which they shine.
Miss Woods pretty much tears down the place with Bessie Smith's
``Wasted Life Blues,'' hitting an intensity that's rarely matched
by the rest of the production. The singer also sasses her way
through a vaudeville number called ``New Orleans Hop Scop Blues''
that demonstrates her Olympic-class sense of timing.
   As the all-purpose woman of the world, the cool Miss Pressley is
a revelation. A sleek, sexy songstress, she projects elegance and
high style. She can move too, particularly in the old Benny Goodman
number ``Stompin' at the Savoy'' and in a wild, defiant ``Take It
Right Back'' that concludes the first act.
   Miss Jones, as the stereotypical girl on a date, has a harder
time because she has the least interesting songs, particularly a
bland version of ``Willow Weep for Me.'' When she is allowed to
torch her material, particularly a song like ``Reckless Blues,''
the woman can sizzle.
   Hamilton's role is even less defined. He wanders in and out of
these melodic tribulations. Occasionally the performer even
comments on these down-and-out dames, particularly in a sardonic
number ``Wild Women Don't Have the Blues'' or on himself in a song
like Duke Ellington's ``I'm Just a Lucky So-and-So.''
   Sheldon Epps, who created and directed the show, has boxed the
musical into a corner. The songs pile on top of each other,
allowing for little emotional variation. Their sheer number gives
the evening the blues.
   ``Blues in the Night'' is best savored for the individual star
turns. Taken as a full evening of theater, the production proves to
be a tad wearyin'.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880914-0208 </DOCNO>
