<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StudentShot     09-14 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Student Shot,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pratt Institute Student Killed During Robbery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Victim's name cq as Wrappe and parents' name as Wrape.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-year-old artist from Arkansas was shot to
death Wednesday near the campus of an art institute in Brooklyn
where she came to study a week ago.
   Judith Anne Wrappe of Little Rock was shot at least once in the
chest as she struggled with a gunman who had demanded her purse
while she was walking home about 1 a.m., said police Deputy
Inspector Charles Prestia.
   Ms. Wrappe arrived in New York City last Wednesday and enrolled
for her first semester at the Pratt Institute to pursue a masters
degree in fine arts.
   The prestigious school's campus sits amid historic mansions,
renovated town houses and middle-class apartment towers, but it
also adjoins Bedford-Stuyvesant, a predominantly poor neighborhood
with a high rate of violent crime.
   Ms. Wrappe spent the summer with a brother in Washington, D.C.,
working three jobs to save money for school, her mother said.
   ``Judith was just pursuing her dream,'' of studying art in New
York, said her mother, Sue Wrape, in a tearful telephone interview.
   Ms. Wrappe, a 1987 Notre Dame graduate who spelled her name
differently from her parents, had just finished her first night
working as a waitress at a Manhattan restaurant, said manager Mark
Shay.
   Detectives believe she took the subway to Brooklyn and was one
block away from the apartment she had rented with three other
students when she was approached, Prestia said.
   ``There was some kind of a struggle between the fellow and the
victim, she had shouted out `Leave me alone,' when he fired one
shot, hit her in the chest, and escaped with the handbag,'' Prestia
said.
   During the commotion, a resident of a nearby building had yelled
out the window at the gunman to `Leave her alone,''' Prestia added.
``It was just shortly after that that he fired the shot.''
   The handbag was recovered nearby, and it was not known if
anything was taken.
   Shay said he hired the student artist Monday. During her first
shift, ``she did mention to someone here that it was a culture
shock moving from Arkansas to New York City,'' the restaurant
manager said.
   ``It's embarrassing as a New Yorker to have someone come from
out of state and meet an untimely death at a young age,'' Shay
said. ``It doesn't say much for New York City to the people of
Arkansas.''
   Ms. Wrappe is survived by her mother, and father, Jarrell V.
Wrape, and four brothers and a sister, who ranged in age from 22 to
32 years of age.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880914-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 2248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Hungary     09-14 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Hungary,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel, Hungary Agree To Restore Diplomatic Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel and Hungary agreed Wednesday to
gradually restore diplomatic ties that were severed 21 years ago by
the Eastern European nation, Israeli media reported.
   The agreement came after a meeting between Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Hungarian Prime Minister Karoly Grosz
in Budapest, Israel radio and television said.
   Shamir spokesman Yossi Ahimeir, reached at his Tel Aviv home,
refused comment on the reports. Shamir arrived in Budapest
Wednesday.
   Israel television said Shamir and Grosz agreed in principle to
the gradual restoration of ties, but did not set a timetable for
upgrading diplomatic representation.
   Hungary, along with all other Soviet bloc countries except
Romania, severed ties with Israel after the 1967 Middle East war in
which Israel captured lands of the bloc's Arab allies.
   In the past two years, the Soviet Union and some of its allies
sought improved relations with Israel. Israel and the Soviet Union
have exchanged consular delegations.
   Israel and Hungary resumed low-level diplomatic ties last year,
and opened interest sections, the lowest form of diplomatic
representation, in Budapest and Tel Aviv in March.
   In May, Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres made a surprise
visit to Hungary, and said the Hungarian government wanted to
expand economic ties with the Jewish state. In 1986, trade between
the two countries totaled about $22 million.
   Imre Miklos, Hungary's state secretary for church affairs, made
a five-day visit to Israel last week and met with Shamir.
   After his return to Hungary, Miklos said Shamir ``reinforced
Israel's interest in further developing relations with Hungary and
said my visit reflected an ongoing improvement in Hungarian-Israeli
relations.''
   He added, ``He (Shamir) could see no reason to prevent the
development of relations in all fields, including the diplomatic
one.''
   Shamir's private two-day tour of Hungary is the first visit by
an Israeli prime minister to a Soviet bloc country other than
Romania since 1967.
   On Thursday, Shamir, head of the right-wing Likud bloc, was
scheduled to meet with Jewish leaders and visit a synagogue in
Budapest. About 80,000 Jews live in Hungary and about 240,000 Jews
of Hungarian origin live in Israel.
   Also Wednesday, Lt. Gen. Sidney Thomas Weinstein, U.S. deputy
chief of staff, ended a three-day unofficial visit to Hungary to
discuss ways to improve military cooperation between the two
countries, Hungarian state television reported.
   Weinstein, reportedly the highest-ranking American army officer
to visit the Warsaw Pact country, held talks with Lt. Gen. Ferenc
Szucs, deputy chief of staff of the Hungarian People's Army and met
with Lt. Gen. Jozsef Pacsek, chief of staff and deputy defense
minister, the report said.
   According to Hungarian television, Weinstein ``inquired about
the Hungarian defense doctrine and (conferred on) possibilities to
further develop ties between the armies of the two countries.''
   ``With the political improvement between (Hungary and the United
States) possibilities have opened up for better (military) ties''
the television report said, without further elaboration.
</TEXT>
