<2ND_LINE>AM-Delaware Recount, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0738,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Recount Continues in Delaware's Senate Primary Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with comments from both sides,
recount likely to continue until early morning; picks up 4th graf:
`The recount ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW CASTLE, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo remained in the lead
by a slim margin Wednesday as the recount continued of ballots cast
in Delaware's Democratic U.S. Senate primary race.
   New Castle County election officials said they would announce
results Thursday.
   ``It's a very tedious process, step-by-step, vote-by-vote,''
said Jack Markell, Woo's deputy campaign manager and a recount
observer. He said he expected the counting of ballots to go into
the early morning.
   Woo's opponent, Samuel S. Beard, was unavailable for comment,
said staff member aide Nancy Leonard.
   ``He's out,'' Ms. Leonard said. ``And I hope he's having a good
time.''
   After recounts in Delaware's other two counties, results did not
change from earlier certified ballots that gave Woo an 88-vote lead
over Beard.
   The recount was requested by both candidates on Monday after it
was discovered a clerical error gave Beard 2,800 votes too many.
   Beard had claimed victory after Saturday's primary, but found
himself trailing after the mistake was found and votes were counted
from nine precincts that had not reported immediately after the
polls closed.
   Woo and Beard are seeking the party's nomination for the right
to challenge Republican Sen. William V. Roth Jr. in the November
election. Roth did not have a primary challenger.
   Beard thought he had won with 22,418 votes to Woo's 19,624.
   By Monday night, the unofficial statewide tally showed Beard
with 20,133 to Woo's 20,221.
   The 2,800-vote mistake occurred in the 23rd representative
district in New Castle County, where about 280 Democrats are
registered. Beard received 28 votes there, but the votes were
recorded as 2,828 in the computer at the county's department of
elections, according to the county elections director.
   Woo, 51, is a physics professor at the University of Delaware,
and was elected elected lieutenant governor four years ago. Beard,
49, has been chairman for job creation commissions under the past
four presidents.
</TEXT>
