<2ND_LINE>AM-Scenic Byways, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0835,260</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: CORRECTS spelling of Kancamagus</NOTE>
<HEAD>Nine Picturesque Roads Added to Scenic Byways System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Forest Service announced Wednesday
the addition of ``nine picturesque roads'' to a scenic byways
system in the national forests.
   Chief F. Dale Robertson said the designations cover 560 miles of
highways in seven states. The scenic byways system was established
with the announcement on July 25 of a 26-mile stretch of U.S.
Highway 64 in southeastern Tennessee in the Cherokee National
Forest.
   The nine new designations include:
   _Arizona. White Mountains Scenic Highway through 123 miles in
the Apache-Sitgreaves National Forest in eastern Arizona.
   Apache Trail, 78 miles along state Highway 88 on the Tonto
National Forest, less than 30 miles from Phoenix.
   Coronado Trail, 123 miles of U.S. Highway 666 from Clifton to
Springerville through the Sitgreaves National Forest.
   _California. Carson Pass Highway, 59 miles on state Highway 88
from Dew Drop to Woodfords through the Eldorado and Toiyabe
national forests in northern California.
   _New Hampshire. Kancamagus Highway, 28 miles on state Highway
112 through the White Mountain National Forest from Conway to
Lincoln.
   _New Mexico. Sandia Crest Road, 11 miles on state Highway 536
through the Cibola National Forest in central New Mexico.
   _Utah. Ashley National Forest, 45 miles on U.S. Highway 191 and
state Highway 44 from Vernal to Manila.
   Logan Canyon Highway, 39 miles on U.S. Highway 89 from Logan to
Bear Lake.
   _Wyoming. Snowy Range Highway, 29 miles on state Highway 130
through the Medicine Bow National Forest in southeastern Wyoming.
</TEXT>
