<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MinisterCharged     09-14 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minister Charged,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fraud Charges Against Preacher Who Helped Set up Gang Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister who helped arrange meetings
of street gang members aimed at ending violence was accused in a
warrant Wednesday of masterminding a plan to take out $125,000 in
fraudulent student loans.
   The Rev. James Stern of Tabernacle of Faith Baptist Church in
south-central Los Angeles was charged with 15 counts of grand
theft, 13 counts of forgery, and one count of conspiracy to defraud.
   Stern, 24, who helped arrange two much-publicized gang ``summit
meetings'' this summer, didn't respond to a telephone request for
comment.
   Seven others charged in the case are accused of taking out
student loans and turning the money over to Stern, who promised
them $3,000 each, District Attorney's spokesman Andy Reynolds said
Wednesday.
   A criminal complaint filed Tuesday accused Stern of arranging a
scheme to take out government-insured student loans from a Bank of
America branch in Pasadena, Reynolds said.
   Checks from the bank, purportedly for tuition at the University
of Sound Art in Hollywood, were deposited into an account for an
allegedly phony business opened by Stern at another bank, Reynolds
said.
   Checks totaling nearly $36,000 and bearing forged signatures
from the Hollywood trade school were deposited in that account, the
spokesman said.
   Other participants also were recruited and the total potential
loss to the Bank of America and the California Student Loan
Commission was $125,000, Reynolds said.
</TEXT>
