<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With Republicans unanimously opposed, the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee voted 10-9 on Wednesday to
approve legislation imposing a trade embargo on white-ruled South
Africa and requiring the withdrawal of U.S. business investment.
   Democrats applauded the action as a blow against South Africa's
apartheid system of forced racial separation, but said they hoped
the measure would enjoy stronger Republican support when it is put
to a vote in the full Senate.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., called on Republican
presidential candidate George Bush to reverse course and support
the sanctions bill, a similar version of which has been passed by
the House.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEMIPALATINSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The land heaved and windows broke
more than two miles away Wednesday when the Soviet Union detonated
a underground nuclear bomb for the first American experts to
witness a Soviet nuclear blast.
   The Americans stood in a chilly wind on the barren test site at
the Forward Command Post Semipalatinsk Polygon about 1,700 miles
southeast of Moscow in the republic of Kazakhstan.
   The wind blew the Soviet and American flags in the direction of
the test range, far from the nearest settlement on the steppes of
Soviet Central Asia and a four-hour bus ride from the city of
Semipalatinsk.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush has seized the advantage in the
early stages of the fall presidential race, delineating the key
campaign issues and boxing his opponent into a defensive corner.
But he'd best not rest, pollsters say.
   The very factors that allowed Bush to turn the tables on Michael
Dukakis make his current lead a precarious one, poll analysts said
Wednesday. Though Bush is ahead, they said, voters' choices remain
unusually tentative.
   ``It's all very volatile. It's still to be won or lost,'' said
Humphrey Taylor, president of Louis Harris & Associates. ``Even if
Bush was to go 10 or 12 points ahead, it would not mean he is
certain to win by any means.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit showed the
biggest improvement in almost six years in July, a dramatic 28
percent narrowing that reflected a big decline in Americans'
appetite for foreign goods, the government reported Wednesday.
   The Commerce Department said the difference between what the
United States imports and what it sells abroad shrank to $9.53
billion in July, down $3.6 billion from a June deficit of $13.22
billion.
   The Reagan administration lost no time hailing the huge decline
as proof that the administration's economic strategy of fighting
soaring trade deficits with a devaluation of the dollar was paying
off.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Confessed hijacker Mohammed Ali
Hamadi denied Wednesday that he headed the 1985 TWA hijacking that
claimed the life of a U.S. Navy diver and kept 39 Americans captive
for 17 days.
   Hamadi on Wednesday also accused witnesses of giving false
testimony after some said he gloated over the killing of an
American passenger.
   ``The testimony very often deviates far from the truth,'' Hamadi
told the court. ``I was not the leader of the commando.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swedish doctor who has transplanted brain
cells from aborted human fetuses to patients with Parkinson's
disease said Wednesday the procedure is so promising it would be
unethical not to make it available to desperately ill people.
   Dr. Lars Olson, professor of neurobiology at Karolinska
Institute in Stockholm and one of the few people in the world to
have transplanted human fetal tissue, also told a National
Institutes of Health advisory committee the technique has been used
in Mexico, China, England and Cuba.
   There are no known cases of fetal tissue being transplanted as a
treatment for Parkinson's disease in the United States, but several
animal studies have suggested the procedure can be effective.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New devices that automatically deliver
heart-starting electrical jolts and can be operated with little
training could save many of the 400,000 Americans who die each year
of cardiac arrest, according to a new report.
   The machines are sophisticated versions of the defibrillators
that doctors and paramedics have used for decades, but so automated
that they are much easier to use.
   When attached to the chest, the device will check the victim's
heart and deliver a shock if it finds he has suffered cardiac
arrest, a disastrous interruption in the heart's blood-pumping
rhythm. If given soon enough, the shock almost always restarts the
stalled heart.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Wednesday upheld the partial
merger of the Detroit Free Press and The Detroit News under a joint
operating agreement approved last month by then-Attorney General
Edwin Meese III.
   U.S. District Judge George Revercomb rejected contentions by a
group of Detroit advertisers and readers that the morning Free
Press, owned by Knight-Ridder Inc., was not a failing newspaper
entitled to antitrust exemptions under the 1970 Newspaper
Preservation Act.
   The judge said he would allow a month-old court order
temporarily blocking the deal to expire at 7:15 p.m. on Saturday _
a delay that could give opponents time to appeal the ruling to a
federal appeals court here.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five months after lawmakers ousted Gov. Evan
Mecham from office, voters have given him a measure of vengeance by
rejecting seven Republican legislators who helped impeach and
convict him.
   ``We stand at the dawn of a great awakening in Arizona,'' Mecham
supporter Jerry Gillespie said Tuesday night after defeating Senate
President Carl Kunasek in the GOP primary by 6,548 votes to 5,610
votes. ``The people of this state have begun the process of
regaining control of their state government.''
   But the results of the voting hardly constituted a sweep by the
pro-Mecham forces. Republicans who opposed him had little
difficulty gaining nomination in areas outside of his traditional
strongholds of rural Arizona and some parts of suburban Phoenix.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Utilities that contracted with the
Washington Public Power Supply System purposely misled bond buyers
about the need for two nuclear power plants and never intended to
make good on their $2.25 billion bond debts, a lawyer argued
Wednesday.
   Official statements made to entice investors to buy WPPSS bonds
contained ``a number of false promises,'' attorney Tom Barr said in
the plaintiffs' opening statement. He represents Chemical Bank of
New York, which has sued on behalf of 24,000 bond buyers.
   ``We claim, and we will prove that these false statements were
made fraudulently ... and negligently,'' Barr said.
