<2ND_LINE>PM-Star Hounds-Paparazzi, ADV 21,0126</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, Sept. 21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Fellini Film Was Source of Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Star Hounds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The term paparazzi comes from a private joke by
film director Federico Fellini.
   Paparazzo was the name of an aggressive celebrity photographer
in Fellini's 1959 film ``La Dolce Vita.'' But according to the
Random House Dictionary of the English Language, the famed Italian
moviemaker found the Italian name in the 1901 English novel ``By
the Ionian Sea,'' by George Giffing, which Fellini read while
making ``La Dolce Vita.''
   In the book, Mr. Paparazzo is an innkeeper. There is no Italian
word ``paparazzo,'' and the common plural for the photographers,
paparazzi, was invented.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Sept. 21</NOTE>
