<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionToday ADV16   09-14 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, ADV 16,0771</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Sept. 16, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Southern Baptist Moderates Huddle on Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Restraint tempered desperate words at a strategy
session of Southern Baptist moderates about ``where we go'' in a
denomination now run by fundamentalists.
   ``We are Baptists in a denomination that has stopped being
Baptist,'' said Kirby Godsey, president of Mercer University in
Macon, Ga.
   The 900 moderate leaders of the coalition, the Southern Baptist
Alliance, made no move at their meeting in Nashville, Tenn., last
weekend to quit the 14.7-million-member denomination, although some
speculated it eventually could happen.
   For the time being, however, participants took lesser measures,
launching such independent projects as alternative Sunday school
lessons and theological education. They keenly lamented the control
achieved by fundamentalists over the denomination, the country's
largest Protestant body.
   It ``is wounded and just may be mortally wounded,'' said the
Rev. Randall Lolley of Raleigh, N.C.
   The Rev. Tom Grace of St. John's Baptist Church, Charlotte,
N.C., said, ``We now exist in a state of grief, grief over loss of
our mother denomination.''
   Its historic principles ``are in eclipse,'' Godsey said. ``In
the midst of these dreadful and frightening shadows of
denominational eclipse we huddle together to find reassurance and
light enough to sustain us.''
   The three-day meeting was called after fundamentalists last June
won denominational rule for the 10th straight year.
   They insist on a literal view of the Bible as ``inerrant'' _
free of error historically, scientifically and religiously.
Moderates allow for diverse interpretations.
   The fundamentalist wing gradually has gained sway over church
institutions through the appointive powers of a succession of
fundamentalist presidents, the latest being the Rev. Jerry Vines of
Jacksonville, Fla.
   Sizing up the present status of moderates, the Rev. Cecil
Sherman of Fort Worth, Texas, told the Nashville meeting, ``We have
been put out of the house. The game goes on, but we don't get to
play.''
   The alliance has 36,460 members, including individuals and
member churches, in 38 states.
   Its board voted to publish independent adult Sunday school
lessons beginning in January, for those dissatisfied with materials
put out by the denominational Sunday School Board.
   The alliance also decided to support a House of Baptist studies
at Duke University, a Methodist institution in Durham, N.C., and a
Divinity School at Lake Forest University in Winston Salem, N.C.
   The moderates alloted $30,000 to support various causes
purportedly spurned by the fundamentalist administration, such as
peace making, housing for the poor, women in ministry and the
doctrine of priesthood of the believer.
   Moderates criticized several recent denominational actions under
fundamentalist control, including:
   _ The Home Mission Board's prohibition of support to female
pastors or divorced persons as missionaries.
   _ The foreign mission board's dismissal of a missionary, the
Rev. Michael Willett, accusing him of ``doctrinal ambiguity'' for
not holding a literalistic view of some miracles.
   _ A funding cut for the Baptist Joint Committee on Public
Affairs, a religious liberty watchdog agency in Washington
involving eight Baptist denominations.
   _ Tightened control over the Southeastern Baptist Theological
Seminary in Wake Forest, N.C., resulting in resignations of the
president, most top administrators and some faculty.
   The alliance's interim executive director, the Rev. Alan Neely,
a professor at Princeton University, said the organization is not
planning a new denomination but also is not ruling out that
possibility.
   ``The future is uncertain,'' he said. ``The alliance will remain
active in its support for Baptist principles and the Baptist
heritage of freedom until what we perceive as designed,
concentrated, calculated oppression is relieved.
   ``We are simply trying to provide an arena for people who have
been selected out, prevented, prohibited, blackballed by those in
power to have a place to stand and can have some free air to
breathe.''
   A straw poll at the meeting found 90 percent of the participants
favored some change in relation to the denomination's ``cooperative
program'' through which various agencies are financed.
   Several particpants favored continued support for that unified
budget, but also creation of foundations to finance causes not
backed by the denomination but deemed important to moderates.
   Others favored ``designated giving'' only to chosen
denominational programs, with moderates putting other funds in
escrow until fundamentalists agree to political changes in bylaws
that enable factional control.
   The proposals were to be considered at an alliance board meeting
scheduled for Nov. 28-29 in Charlotte, N.C.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Sept. 16</NOTE>
