<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The deficit in the broadest measure of U.S.
trade narrowed sharply from April through June as overseas sales of
American merchandise surged to a record high, the government says.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that the deficit in the
current account shrank to $33.3 billion in the second quarter,
compared with a first quarter imbalance of $36.9 billion.
   But the report also said America suffered its first deficit in
three decades in the trade category which includes investment
earnings.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Finance Committee unanimously has
endorsed Treasury Secretary-designate Nicholas F. Brady, who said
he expects diminishing U.S. trade deficits and continued
international coordination of exchange rates.
   The committee voted 15-0 Tuesday to recommend Brady's
confirmation by the full Senate after quizzing the Wall Street
investment banker and former senator for less than two hours. Most
questions focused on trade and other international economic issues,
and the federal budget deficit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of First Nationwide Bank has
complained to a congressional panel that his institution should not
have been frozen out of negotiations in the largest-ever government
rescue of a savings association.
   Robert E. Lackovic, president of the San Francisco-based First
Nationwide, told the House Energy and Commerce oversight
subcommittee, Tuesday that federal regulators cannot be sure they
got the best deal in the rescue of American Savings and Loan
Association of Stockton, Calif.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board announced Sept. 5 it was
providing $2 billion in government assistance to the Robert M. Bass
Group of Fort Worth, Texas, to acquire American, the nation's
largest insolvent S&L.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans spent $449 million more than normal
last month to keep their cool, the government says.
   The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration said
August's steamy weather raised the national electricity bill to
nearly $4.3 billion.
   The average residential electric bill came to $104 in August,
$11 more than normal, according to the monthly report issued
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kroger Co. is considering a $3.77 billion
restructuring plan, but says the proposal is not designed
specifically to ward off a possible hostile takeover by Herbert and
Robert Haft.
   Kroger, one of the nation's largest grocery chains, said Tuesday
it was asking its board of directors to approve a plan that would
plunge the Cincinnati-based company deeply into debt but keep it
publicly owned. Kroger has 1,300 supermarkets and other operations
in 29 states.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine personal computer makers have declared
their technical independence from International Business Machines
Corp., with a new standard for how information will be passed
around inside their machines.
   Analysts said Tuesday's announcement of the new ``bus,'' or data
pathway, killed for good the lingering idea that IBM would control
the standards for the next generation of personal computers.
   ``It's IBM and the rest of us,'' said William Krause, chairman
and chief executive of 3Com Corp., which makes communications
software for machines made by both IBM and its rivals.
</TEXT>
