<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest automaker, General Motors
Corp., says low gasoline prices and consumer preference for
high-powered luxury autos means less fuel-efficient cars should be
allowed.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration heard comment
Tuesday on a proposed rule that would set the corporate average
fuel economy standards for cars at between 26.5 miles per gallon
and 27.5 mpg.
   Without the new rule, the standard would revert to the 27.5 mpg
Congress enacted in 1975.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer-products giant Colgate-Palmolive Co.
has accepted a management-led buyout of its Kendall Health Care
subsidiary in a deal that values the business at around $1.1
billion.
   Under the agreement announced Tuesday, Colgate will receive $910
million in cash and $50 million worth of debentures from a company
formed by Kendall management and the investment banking firm
Clayton & Dublier.
   Colgate also said it would retain certain Kendall assets,
including real estate and some overseas non-health care consumer
products businesses.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of Polaroid Corp. has asked
stockholders to defer consideration of a hostile tender offer by
Shamrock Acquisition III Inc. until Polaroid issues its own
recommendation sometime before Sept. 22.
   Shamrock, based in Burbank, Calif., has offered to buy Polaroid
for $42 a share. The bid values Polaroid at about $2.6 billion.
   The Polaroid board, which made its latest recommendation on
Tuesday, previously had rejected as inadequate an unsolicited offer
from Shamrock that would have paid $40 a share plus a share plus 40
percent of the eventual award in Polaroid's patent infringement
lawsuit against Eastman Kodak Co.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts has slipped from first place to
10th in the past year among states with the lowest unemployment
rates, while Vermont has emerged as the best job provider for its
residents, according to a new report.
   Vermont had an unemployment rate of 2.3 percent in July, the
Bureau of Labor Statistics said Tuesday.
   Massachusetts' unemployment rate rose to 3.6 percent in July, a
full percentage point more than a year ago when it had the lowest
joblessness.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State governments were more than $265 billion
in debt last year, an all-time high, the Census Bureau says.
   State government debt at the end of fiscal 1987 totaled $265.7
billion, up from $247.7 billion a year earlier, the bureau reported
Tuesday in its annual analysis of state government finances.
</TEXT>
