<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0105EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FoodPreservation     09-14 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Food Preservation,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rutgers Researcher Develops New Way Of Determining Shelf Life Of
Food</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A professor at Rutgers University has
developed what the school says is a faster way of measuring food
deterioration, which could reduce the need for preservatives and
help cut food manufacturing costs.
   The method combines previously known scientific tools with
computer technology and lets researchers measure food shelf life
within hours, compared with the weeks or years it used to take,
school officials said Tuesday.
   Rutgers has applied for a patent for the process, which can be
applied to dried goods such as cookies, fruit, breakfast cereal,
instant coffee and milk powder, said Myron Solberg, director of
Rutgers' Center for Advanced Food Technology.
   The roots of the process date to more than 10 years ago, when
Seymour Gilbert, an internationally known food-packaging expert and
long-time Rutgers professor, found a way of measuring how food
absorbs potential carcinogens from packaging. His findings were
applied worldwide.
   He began using the same technology five years ago to find out
how food breaks down, and since then has been working on the
problem with a team of almost 20 graduate students.
   The key to determining shelf life is discovering how the water
interacts with food, he said.
   Gilbert, 74, illustrates his case with the bagel, which turns
hard after a few days but regains its softness when toasted. The
starch and proteins push out the water and crystalize, hardening
the food, but heating the bagel reverses the process, he said.
   ``This is part of the research I've been doing, to see how the
water redistributed itself,'' he said.
   The technique _ known as inverse gas chromatography _
essentially measures a product's potential for absorbing and losing
water.
   Samples are put in a chromatography column, a sensitive
instrument that measures how the water interacts with the food, and
a computer is used to quickly analyze the resulting data.
   ``It's a kind of tool for the development of new products and
also to do quality control on existing products,'' Solberg said.
   By knowing how long food will last, manufacturers can offer
consumers fresher products and reduce costs and waste. They also
may be able to reduce the use of preservatives, Rutgers researchers
say.
   ``It won't eliminate the need for preservatives but it will give
a better feel for when a preservative is needed,'' Solberg said.
   The accuracy of current methods of determining shelf life
varies, scientists say. Methods range from putting items on a shelf
and waiting several years to see how long they last to accelerating
the aging process by raising the temperature.
   ``My method works in standard temperatures but I use very small
amounts of material and an apparatus that's very sensitive so I can
measure very small rates of change,'' Gilbert said.
   In the United States alone, millions of dollars worth of food
are lost to spoilage each year, said Robert Buchanan at the U.S.
Department of Agriculture's research center in Philadelphia.
   Other scientists declined to comment on Gilbert's technique on
the grounds that they did not have enough information.
   ``I've never heard of anything like this before,'' said Kevin
Hicks, another USDA research leader in Philadelphia. ``It sounds
very original. It also sounds very difficult, but perhaps
promising.''
   Fergus M. Clydesdale, head of the Department of Food Science and
Nutrition at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, said ``I
think it's an interesting application (of the technology) but it
isn't going to change the color of the sky.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880914-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Kroger     09-14 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kroger,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nation's Biggest Grocery Chain Braced Against Takeover Threats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kroger Co., the nation's largest grocery
chain, has proposed a $3.8 billion restructuring plan to shield
itself against any hostile takeover bids.
   The Cincinnati-based company said Tuesday it was considering a
plan that would make Kroger an unattractive takeover target by
raising its stock price, loading it up with new debt, placing 20
percent of its shares under control of its employees and selling
off parts of the company.
   The proposal followed news that the Haft family of Maryland
received federal antitrust clearance to acquire Kroger stock and
pushed Kroger shares sharply higher.
   Kroger stock soared by $11.75 a share to $51.25 in heavy trading
Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Under the restructuring, shareholders would get a one-time cash
dividend of $40 per share and would receive long-term bonds worth
another $8 a share, while retaining their Kroger common stock.
   Based on its 78.57 million common shares outstanding, it would
cost about $3.15 billion to pay the dividends. Kroger also would
have to borrow another $630 million to cover the bonds.
   ``By continuing as an independent company, the interests of our
employees, customers and the communities in which we operate would
also be protected,'' said Kroger Chairman Lyle Everingham.
   Kroger's directors will meet ``in the very near future'' to vote
on the plan, company representative Paul Bernish said.
   Directors met in emergency session Friday to prepare the
protection plan only hours after the Federal Trade Commission told
the Hafts they could buy Kroger stock without violating anti-trust
laws.
   The Hafts have launched a number of major raids against grocery
companies and other retailers, including unsuccessful but
profitable hostile bids for Safeway, Supermarkets General and Stop
n' Shop. It was not known how much Kroger stock the Hafts own,
although they must disclose when they acquire 5 percent or more of
the company's outstanding shares.
   The FTC clearance was the first official sign of the Hafts'
interest in Kroger, although Kroger stock has has traded heavily
over the past five months amid rumors the Hafts and other potential
acquirers were interested in the company. Representatives of the
Hafts declined to comment.
   Kroger reported sales of almost $18 billion in 1987. It operates
1,317 supermarkets nationwide as well as 900 convenience stores,
and employs 170,000 people.
   Kroger said it will repay the debt incurred in the restructuring
using cash flow from operations, reducing expenses and selling
assets. In a 1986 restructuring, Kroger sold its chain of SupeRx
retail drugstores, and Kroger has worked since July to sell off its
unprofitable chain of Florida Choice supermarkets and liquor stores
in Florida.
   Analysts said the proposed restructuring, if undertaken,
probably would be enough to scare off any would-be hostile buyers.
   The dividend portion of the plan alone would cost $377 million a
year in interest, assuming a rate of 12 percent, estimated William
Flyg, vice president of Big Bear Inc., the Columbus, Ohio-based
grocery chain that competes with Kroger in Columbus. That would
exceed Kroger's 1987 pre-tax income of $315.6 million.
   Kroger could raise between $800 million and $900 million from
asset sales, said Gary M. Giblen, vice president of the investment
firm of Rotan-Mosle Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
