<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru f0005 09-14 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0005,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>July Deficit Lowest in Nearly Four Years, Dollar Jumps</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout to UPDATE with trade report, market
reaction. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today reported the lowest monthly trade deficit
in nearly four years, inciting a hectic rally in the dollar, easing
interest rates in the credit markets and boosting the Republican
presidential campaign.
   The Commerce Department said the merchandise trade deficit
shrank to $9.5 billion in July, the lowest monthly imbalance since
December 1984 and substantially better than many economists had
predicted.
   The 28 percent improvement reflected a small increase in exports
and a big decline in imports.
   It was certain to cheer Republican presidential candidate George
Bush, who has been trying to deflect charges from Democrat Michael
Dukakis that the nation's soaring deficits reflect major flaws in
the Reagan economic program.
   But the Commerce Department also revised upward its June deficit
figure to $13.2 billion from $12.5 billion, which would be the
biggest gap since the February shortfall of $14.4 billion.
   Money traders scrambled to buy dollars after today's report was
released, sending the currency sharply higher in value against the
West German mark and Japanese yen.
   In the bond market, a sensitive indicator of inflation and the
economy's direction, the key 30-year Treasury bond rose more than
$7.50 per $1,000 in face amount and its yield fell to 8.98 percent
from 8.99 percent late Tuesday.
   Bond traders were primarily reacting to the big shrinkage in
imports, which suggested the economy may be slowing down and
thereby easing fears of inflation.
   The trade report was issued prior to the opening bell on Wall
Street, but stock traders already had assumed there would be good
news today and drove prices up late Tuesday, encouraged by remarks
from Treasury secretary designate Nicholas F. Brady.
   Brady told a Senate confirmation hearing that he expects the
trade deficit to decline at a ``surprisingly fast'' pace over the
next few years.
   In addition, the Commerce Department said Tuesday that the
deficit in the current account, the broadest measure of U.S. trade,
shrank to $33.3 billion in the second quarter, a 9.8 percent
improvement from a first quarter imbalance of $36.9 billion.
   It was the biggest quarterly improvement since a 20.1 percent
drop in the final three months of last year. The current account
covers trade in merchandise as well as trade in services, which
primarily reflect the flow of investment earnings between countries.
   In other markets Tuesday, oil prices advanced, driven by a rise
in wholesale gasoline prices, which soared on news that refineries
and oil platforms were threatened by a hurricane approaching the
Gulf of Mexico.
   The contract for October delivery of West Texas Intermediate,
the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, rose 7 cents to settle at $14.56
a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery closed up 1.19
cents at 43.81 cents a gallon.
   Elsewhere, the government released a state-by-state report on
unemployment in which Vermont emerged as the best job provider for
its residents. Massachusetts slipped from first place to 10th in
the past year among states with the lowest unemployment rates.
   Vermont posted an unemployment rate of 2.3 percent in July, with
just 6,900 of its workers lacking jobs, the Bureau of Labor
Statistics said.
   Massachusetts' unemployment rate, meanwhile, rose to 3.6 percent
in July, a full percentage point higher than the same month a year
ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880914-0238 </DOCNO>
