<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Federated     09-14 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retail Chain Reports Second Quarterly Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federated Department Stores Inc., suffering
sluggish sales and still recovering from the high cost of the
Campeau Corp. takeover, reported a $100 million loss in the second
quarter.
   A representative of the Toronto-based Campeau said Tuesday the
loss was due to continuing weak retail sales and the costs
associated with its $8.8 billion takeover of Federated last May.
   Federated's second-quarter loss compares with $30 million in
earnings, or 32 cents a share, in the same period last year.
   For the period ended July 30, Federated reported in a Securities
and Exchange Commission filing it had interest costs of $132.1
million related to Campeau's hostile takeover of the retailer. Its
sales in the period dropped to $970.5 million from $2.4 billion in
the year-ago period, the company said.
   Campeau said previously that costs associated with Federated's
unsuccessful takeover fight contributed to a $128 million loss at
Federated in the first quarter.
   Despite the lower overall sales, three of Federated's divisions
posted increases in revenue, while two reported declines, due
mainly to ``mediocre ready-to-wear sales,'' the company said.
   Bloomingdales showed a .7 percent increase in sales during the
period, Atlanta-based Rich's gained .8 percent and Miami-based
Burdine's advanced 1.5 percent.
   Sales declined .3 percent at Cincinnati-based Lazarus and were
down 2.3 percent at Brooklyn-based Abraham & Straus, Federated said.
   Campeau has agreed to sell Federated's Filene's and Foley's
divisions to May Department Stores for $1.5 billion, and the former
I. Magnin and Bullock's-Bullocks Wilshire, which were sold to R.H.
Macy & Co. for $1.1 billion.
   Last week Campeau agreed to sell Federated's 76-store Gold
Circle discount chain for $325 million.
   Campeau's other retailing unit, Allied Stores Corp., lost $107
million in the second quarter ended July 30, compared with a loss
of $44 million in the same period last year, the company said.
   The latest period included a charge of $10 million on the sale
of Brooks Brothers and a charge of $17 million representing the
company's indirect share in Federated's loss for the period.
</TEXT>
