<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0020,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with dollar activity after trade
report. Picks up 10th graf pvs, Gold opened ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar soared against major foreign currencies
in Europe Wednesday after the U.S. government reported a
larger-than-expected drop in the country's July trade deficit.
   Gold prices rose slightly in the morning.
   The dollar jumped immediately after the Commerce Department said
the U.S. merchandise trade gap narrowed to $9.5 billion in July
from a revised $13.2 billion in June. The department previously
reported the June deficit as $12.5 billion.
   The markets had expected a July trade shortfall of about $11.2
billion.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6822 by late afternoon
after the trade report was released. That compared with $1.6915 at
midmorning and $1.6965 Tuesday.
   Other dollar rates after the trade report was released, with
midmorning rates in parentheses, and compared with late Tuesday,
were: 1.8702 (1.8520) West German marks, up from 1.8470; 1.5760
(1.5605) Swiss francs, up from 1.5600; 6.3640 (6.3020) French
francs, up from 6.2935; 2.1106 (2.0892) Dutch guilders, up from
2.0845; 1,392.00 (1,381.75) Italian lire, up from 1,380.50; and
1.2263 (1.2265) Canadian dollars, down from 1.2307.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.38 yen to close at 133.45 yen.
   Later, in London, the dollar was quoted at 134.40 yen after the
trade report and 133.45 yen before.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $421.90 a troy ounce,
and at mid-morning the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $421.90. Both bid prices were up from the
$420.00 bid late Tuesday.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $421.45 an ounce, up slightly from
$421.00 bid late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 76 cents to close at a bid of
$423.45 an ounce.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.49 a troy
ounce, up from Tuesday's $6.46.
</TEXT>
