<2ND_LINE>PM-Du Pont CEO,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woolard Succeeds Heckert at Du Pont</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edgar S. Woolard Jr., president and
chief operating officer of Du Pont Co., was named to succeed Edgar
S. Woolard Jr. as chairman and chief executive officer, the
chemical giant announced today.
   Woolard, who has been at his current position since March 1,
1987, will take the helm when Heckert retires after Du Pont's
annual meeting in April 1989.
   The mandatory retirement age for CEOs at Du Pont is 65; Heckert
turns 65 in January.
   Du Pont also announced that its board of directors elected
Elwood P. Blanchard Jr., an executive vice president, vice chairman
effective Oct. 1.
   Heckert described Woolard as ``an exceedingly competent
businessman, familiar with all aspects of Du Pont's operations, as
well as a determined and inspiring leader.''
   Woolard, 54, joined Du Pont in 1957 as an industrial engineer at
the Kinston, N.C., plant. He held a succession of manufacturing and
marketing positions in the fibers business, eventually serving as
general manager and later vice president.
   In 1983, he became an executive vice president, with
responsibillity for what are now Du Pont's agricultural products,
medical products, imaging systems and electronics businesses.
</TEXT>
