<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OilPrices 1stLd-Writethru f0006 09-14 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0006,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Firm In Latest Session; Gas Higher On Hurricane
Worries</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with today's trading, details; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices surged in early trading today
on a string of bullish factors, including news that a hurricane
threatens U.S. crude production along the Gulf of Mexico coast.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the October contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, was
quoted 57 cents higher at $15.12 a 42-gallon barrel shortly after
the market opened, from Tuesday's settlement price of $14.56.
   Contracts had traded between $14.33 a barrel and $14.70 a barrel
Tuesday after Monday's whiplash session in which prices dropped to
a near two-year low of $13.75 before rebounding to settle at $14.49.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery zoomed 1.94
cents a gallon in early trading to 45.80 cents from Tuesday's close
of 43.81 cents a gallon.
   The October wholesale heating oil contract also was up sharply,
trading about 1.22 cents a gallon higher than its close of 41.83
cents a gallon on Tuesday.
   ``This could be one of the wildest trading days with all the
news,'' said Peter Beutel, assistant director of Elders Futures
Inc. in New York.
   Analysts said today's market was continuing the bullish
sentiment started Tuesday on concerns that refineries and oil
platforms were being evacuated in anticipation of the approaching
storm.
   ``If the hurricane hits the Gulf coast, there's concern about
short-term gasoline supplies,'' said Chris McCormack, an energy
analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Analysts said that although Hurricane Gilbert had not damaged
the Gulf oil fields, between 600,000 and 800,000 gallons a day of
gasoline could be lost if production was halted to wait out the
storm.
   Meanwhile, this morning's market also reacted strongly to an
announcement by OPEC Secretary General Subroto that the cartel's
pricing committee had set a meeting date of Sept. 25-26.
   The announcement generates hope that the 13-member Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries will call for a full meeting of
the cartel to set production limits and curb the ouput that has
flooded world oil markets and eroded prices, analysts said.
   Meanwhile, oil brokers were saying this week that the recent dip
in oil prices had not affected retail prices yet but by winter
consumers could realize some benefits at the pump.
   ``If we see another $2 slide in (oil) prices, then consumer
gasoline prices could be expected to go 7 to 8 cents lower when
it's all over _ by Thanksgiving,'' said Stephen Smith, an analyst
with Bear Stearns & Co.
   Other oil brokers said that if crude prices remained between the
$13.50 and $15.50 levels in the next several weeks, retail gasoline
prices could decline by about 2 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
