<2ND_LINE>BC-Obit-Mitchell,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former GM Design Vice President Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROYAL OAK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William L. Mitchell, a former General
Motors Corp. vice president who played a major role in designing
the Corvette and other GM cars, has died at age 76.
   Mitchell died Monday at William Beaumont Hospital. He retired in
July 1977 after working for GM for 42 years.
   Mitchell became vice president in charge of design in 1958 and
was responsible for the No. 1 automaker's design of various models,
including the 1963 Corvette, the 1970 Camaro and the 1977 Impala.
   Mitchell joined GM in 1935 and within a year became chief
designer for the Cadillac studio. In 1954, he was named director of
styling, a post he held until being named vice president.
   Survivors include his wife, Marian, three daughters and four
grandchildren.
   A funeral service has been scheduled for Friday.
</TEXT>
