<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet11am     09-14 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0309</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gained ground today in a
lukewarm response to better-than-expected news on international
trade.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up about 15 points in
the early going, showed a 4.98 gain at 2,088.02 by 11 a.m. on Wall
Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 697 up, 481 down and
532 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 65.64 million shares at
midmorning.
   The Commerce Department reported this morning that the nation's
trade deficit shrank to $9.53 billion in July from a revised gap of
$13.22 billion the month before.
   Wall Street analysts had generally been looking for a July
figure in the $11 billion to $11.5 billion range.
   Of particular note, brokers said, was a substantial drop in
imports. That was taken as a sign that the momentum of the domestic
economy was slowing in response to recent credit-tightening by the
Federal Reserve.
   A moderation of economic growth would presumably allow the Fed
to pursue a less restrictive credit policy, encouraging steady to
lower interest rates.
   The dollar rose in foreign exchange following the trade report,
and interest rates fell in the credit markets.
   But stock traders shied away from bidding up stocks
aggressively, suggesting that the market was still not over its
late-summer malaise.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Philip Morris rose { to 97 and
Coca-Cola added \ to 42], while International Business Machines
dropped } to 114\, and General Electric was down [ at 42\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .18 to 151.33. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .49 at 297.28.
</TEXT>
