<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-FuelEconomy 1stLd-Writethru   09-14 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fuel Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0016,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Says Public Wants Larger, More Powerful Cars</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout. Also moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The public wants larger, more powerful cars,
and tighter fuel economy standards would result in lost jobs,
General Motors Corp. said today in a federal hearing on the
gasoline mileage rules.
   ``This regulation flies against the basic forces of economics,''
said Richard Klimisch, GM's environmental activities executive
director. ``The consumer is reacting to gasoline prices which are
lower than anyone expected, so the consumer does not rank fuel
economy as a top priority.''
   Environmentalists, also testifying at the hearing, said in a
news conference Tuesday that looser fuel-economy standards would
contribute to environmental damage, including a warming of the
global climate.
   The hearing by the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration was taking public comment on a proposal to set the
corporate average fuel economy, or CAFE, standard at 26.5 miles per
gallon to 27.5 mpg.
   Without the new rule, the standard would revert to the 27.5 mpg
voted by Congress in 1975. It has been set at 26 mpg since 1986
under an exception allowed by NHTSA.
   The fuel-economy law, adopted to reduce imported petroleum
consumption at a time of rapidly rising prices, sets a maximum
level of fuel consumption each automaker's fleet of passenger cars,
on average, must meet.
   GM's customers choose cars in part based on gasoline prices, and
with the price at the pump running below $1 per gallon in much of
the nation, car buyers see little value in features that save fuel,
Klimisch said.
   Should the standard be placed at 27.5 mpg, GM would be forced to
cut back on large-car production at its Arlington, Texas, plant at
a cost of 60,000 jobs to GM and its suppliers in 1989 and 110,000
jobs in 1990, Klimisch said.
   Car buyers, faced with a shortage of higher-powered GM cars,
would buy from foreign automakers, buy light trucks that come under
different standards or drive older, less fuel-efficient cars
longer, Klimisch said.
   Eventually, GM might be forced to increase the percentage of
foreign-made parts in its cars to meet the demands of the
marketplace, he said.
   The automaker estimates it might be able to meet a standard of
about 27.1 mpg without job losses, but to make sure of that, in
light of the uncertainties of sales forecasts and test results, it
needs a standard of 26.7 mpg or less, he said.
   A coalition of 20 environmental groups called for stiffening of
the standards to avoid contributing to global warming.
   ``If you liked this summer's heat and droughts, you'll love the
results of this policy,'' said Thomas B. Stoel Jr., international
program director of the Natural Resources Defense Council. ``In
view of what the scientists are telling us about global warming, it
is hard to imagine a more irresponsible proposal.''
   Researchers have predicted that manmade emissions of carbon
dioxide in the atmosphere will raise the average global temperature
significantly during the next century, causing changes in weather
patterns, crop growth and increased sea levels from polar melting.
   Carbon dioxide tends to trap heat in the atmosphere rather than
allowing it to radiate back into space, a phenomenon called the
``greenhouse effect.''
   Automobiles account for about 25 percent of U.S. emissions of
carbon dioxide, Stoel said.
   ``If the U.S. auto fleet could be brought up to an average of 45
mpg by the year 2005, this one action would reduce U.S. carbon
dioxide emissions by about 15 percent,'' he said.
   Loosening the standard from 27.5 mpg to 26 mpg would increase
carbon dioxide emissions over the estimated 106,000-mile life of
each affected car by about 1.6 tons or 4 percent, according to
figures presented by Energy Conservation Coalition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880914-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Mexico-CopperMine Adv19   09-14 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mexico-Copper Mine, Adv 19,0780</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Sept. 19 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Historic Mexican Mine Back on the Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The copper-mining town of Cananea has
come to symbolize the birth of Mexico's nationalist spirit in the
82 years since a bloody strike pitted Mexican workers against an
American mine owner.
   Today a new generation of Cananea miners says a government plan
to return the nationalized, but debt-ridden copper company to the
private sector is like selling a historical landmark.
   ``This is a national patrimony. We feel it in our souls,'' said
Joaquin Quijano Salazar, general secretary of National Miners Union
Section 65, representing 3,000 workers at Cananea, 25 miles south
of the Arizona border in Sonora state.
   Under a plan to reduce government subsidies and help Mexico
overcome its severe economic crisis, the administration of
President Miguel de la Madrid has sold many nonessential
state-owned companies, most of them money losers.
   The sale of the Cananea mine would be by far the biggest
transfer undertaken, but it now appears a final decision will be up
to Carlos Salinas de Gortari, due to take office as president in
December.
   Since the failure of a $910 million bid by Protexa, based in
this northern industrial city, the development bank handling the
sale said the government has received no new offers.
   In a written response to a list of questions directed to its
Mexico City headquarters, the National Financiera bank said Cananea
now could be sold as a package deal along with another Sonora
copper mining operation, Mexicana del Cobre.
   Unofficial reports say the government will ask for $2 billion
for the two mines, but Quijano said that the union opposes the sale.
   ``They can sell a company, but they can't sell workers,'' he
said, adding that some potential buyers want to purchase the mine
without the union contract.
   The Cananea Consolidated Copper Co. was founded by American
entrepeneur William C. Greene in 1899.
   According to ``The Labor Struggle in Cananea 1906,'' published
by the Sonora state government, Greene ran the mine as an American
fiefdom.
   ``The Mexican workers at Cananea were discontented because of
the inequalities that existed between them and the foreign workers
at the same company ... They also found themselves restricted,
almost without exception, to the most arduous and worst paid
jobs,'' the book said.
   On June 1, 1906, 2,000 Mexican miners rallying under the slogan
``Five pesos (then $10) for eight hours work'' went on strike.
   On June 2, according to the book, ``North Americans barricaded
in the main offices ... fired indiscriminately at the Mexicans.''
   Mexican police and soldiers aided by Arizona rangers put down
the rebellion June 5 and jailed its surviving leaders.
   Jose Luis Trueva, a writer who is compiling a history of the
Cananea labor movement, said estimates of the death toll range from
11 to more than 100, including Americans.
   The Mexican dead are remembered throughout Mexico each Labor Day
with shouts of, ``We will not forget the martyrs of Cananea.''
   Although at least 25 labor strikes broke out between 1905 and
1908, the Cananea strike often is credited with sparking the
Mexican labor movement and with helping to launch the Mexican
Revolution of 1910.
   In Cananea, a town of 25,000 people today, a local junior high
school is named ``The Martyrs of 1906'' and two monuments stand in
memory of those who died.
   The Mexican government, which has controlled the operations
since the 1970s, launched a multimillion-dollar expansion project
before the onset of the economic crisis in 1982, said company
spokesman Roberto Rojas.
   Those expenditures, steady devaluations in the peso and the low
price of copper on the international market helped put Cananea's
total debt at the equivalent of $1 billion today, according to
company figures published in the August national business magazine
Expansion.
   But now the improvements are complete, the price of copper is
back up over $1 a pound and Cananea's sales are soaring.
   In 1987 the company had net earnings of $23.3 million on sales
of $186.5 million, a 300 percent increase from the year before,
according to Expansion.
   Rojas estimated production this year at 125,652 metric tons of
pure copper.
   Quijano said the government has treated workers better than any
of the private owners, who he said ``carried off everything and
left us nothing.''
   Said Quijano, ``Now that it's making money they want to sell it.
We hope they don't find any buyers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Sept. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
