<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Ameritech-ADRSale     09-14 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ameritech-ADR Sale,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ameritech Plans to Sell Computer Software Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ameritech says it has agreed to sell Applied Data
Research, its computer software subsidiary, for $170 million, or
about $45 million less than it paid for the unit two years ago.
   Ameritech said Tuesday that Computer Associates International of
Garden City, N.Y., which was one of several firms that looked into
buying ADR, has agreed to buy the software unit.
   Two years ago, Ameritech paid $215 million for ADR and poured
millions of dollars into research and development. The software
unit is believed to have lost money in 1986 and 1987.
   ADR is a major supplier of computer software to the Army and Air
Force.
   If it follows its pattern in other acquisitions, Computer
Associates will make large staff cuts at ADR, which has between
1,600 and 1,700 employees, industry analysts said.
   Computer Associates officials said they had not yet decided what
to do.
   ``We have very little product overlap with ADR, so we might not
do that much,'' said Michael Fisher, senior vice president at
Computer Associates. ``I'm not going to say we won't. We will do
what makes sense.''
   Ameritech had been rumored to be negotiating to sell ADR to
Fujitsu Inc., a Japanese company.
   Computer Associates, a leading software company, had sales of
$709 million last year, and has spent more than $1 billion since
1982 to acquire other firms.
</TEXT>
