<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ChaseMove 1stLd-Writethru   09-14 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chase Move, 1st Ld-Writethru,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Chase Planning Partial Pullout From Big Apple</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvx, Chase officials ..., with 3 grafs to
UPDATE with Chase comment. Picks up 5th graf pvs, Chase's corporate
...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chase Manhattan Corp., one of the nation's
largest bank holding companies, may move nearly a third of its
16,000 employees from its New York headquarters to New Jersey,
according to a report published Wednesday.
   The Wall Street Journal, quoting unnamed real estate and banking
sources, said Chase Chairman Williard C. Butcher favors building a
1.5-milion-square-foot facility in Jersey City, N.J., to house
operations and technical employees.
   His recommendations are expected to be made at a Sept. 21 board
meeting, the sources said.
   Chase spokesman Steven Rautenberg said Wednesday that the bank
``has been looking for alternate sites for our back office but we
haven't reached a decision yet.''
   ``We're looking ... in New York as well as New Jersey,'' he said.
   New York Deputy Mayor Alair Townsend said Wednesday that the
city was aware of Chase's proposals to relocate and was making a
last-ditch effort to convince them to stay.
   Chase's corporate headquarters still would remain in New York's
financial district, the Journal said.
   ``We've been talking with Chase for well over a year ... We're
still having discussions with them,'' said Ms. Townsend, the city's
deputy mayor for finance and economic development.
   She said she planned to deliver some final information on
possible alternate sites in Brooklyn.
   But the Journal story said that Chase and lawyers from the
Lefrak organization, which is developing a complex in Jersey City,
already have agreed on major terms.
   After J.C. Penney and Mobil Oil Co. moved their respective
headquarters out of New York, the city initiated an agressive
campaign, complete with tax breaks and energy savings, to halt
corporate defections.
   The city sued American Telephone & Telegraph Co. to keep it from
moving some employees to New Jersey and convinced NBC to remain in
New York by offering an estimated $100 million tax savings over 35
years.
</TEXT>
