<DOCNO> AP880914-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Trade-Japan-US Bjt   09-14 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade-Japan-US, Bjt,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Export Drive: Try It, You'll Like It</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American business is picking up a strong message:
You can sell to Japan. It may not be easy, but it's not impossible.
   Washington is heavily promoting an export drive as a major
component of the Reagan administration's strategy to reduce the
U.S. trade deficit, especially with Japan, which had a $60 billion
surplus in trade with the United States last year.
   The dollar's drop over the past three years has helped by making
Japanese goods more expensive to buy in the United States, but if
the Japanese do not buy more U.S.-made products, the U.S. deficit
will never disappear.
   U.S. Commerce Secretary C. William Verity led executives of 25
American consumer-products companies to Japan over the past week to
promote their entry into the Japanese market. The trip appears to
have met with some success.
   ``The experience has been very enlightening, to say the least,''
Norman Jacobs, vice president of Eastpak, said of his look at the
fashion luggage market in Tokyo.
   ``We never really intended to get into exporting in this stage
of our development,'' he said, describing his Boston-based
company's growth as averaging 35 percent a year for 11 years while
concentrating mostly on the U.S. market for fashionable bags.
   Jacobs said his company had noticed some Japanese travelers had
bought Eastpak goods and then reordered.
   ``We thought at first we were selling because of style but were
over-priced,'' he said. But after spending a few days looking at
the market in Tokyo, he said, ``I was very surprised to find we are
very price-competitive.''
   The Verity-led mission was Jacobs' first trip to Japan, he said.
``This has opened up a brand new horizon to us, and we're going to
be back as often as it takes.''
   Jacobs' reaction to Japanese price levels is typical of
first-time American visitors. Calculated in today's devalued
dollars, everything is expensive here. But the Japanese are used to
current prices in yen, since this country has negligible inflation,
and many people have incomes high enough to sustain luxury buying
by U.S. standards.
   At a meeting with reporters last weekend, Verity said he was
leading the trade mission to alert more American businesses to the
opportunity in exporting. American companies are not oriented to
the world market because they think they are doing well enough in
the big U.S. market, he said.
   ``If you feel we're hand-holding, you're right,'' Verity said.
   He said he hoped to see the U.S. trade deficit down 15 percent
to 20 percent in 1988. ``That is what our export-promotion program
is all about,'' he said, predicting that in the coming years the
U.S. economy will be driven by exports.
   Some significant improvement in trade has already been
registered, according to the latest figures released by the U.S.
government. The Commerce Department said Wednesday that the U.S.
merchandise trade deficit shrank to $9.5 billion in July, the
lowest monthly imbalance since December 1984.
   The dramatic 28 percent improvement in the trade deficit
reflected a small increase in exports and a big decline in imports.
   Verity said he was disappointed that U.S. construction companies
had not shown much interest in the opening that Washington
bargained hard to win on major construction projects in Japan. But
he predicted they would jump into the market when they saw Japanese
contracts going to other foreign countries.
   During Verity's week-long mission, the Harry Winston jewelry
firm opened a shop in central Tokyo and Winnebago Industries,
makers of recreational vehicles, got a lavish promotional party for
its linkup with Mitsubishi Corp., which will market
Iowa-manufactured Winnebago vehicles in Japan.
   Other companies on the mission had meetings with potential
Japanese distributors and sought openings for products ranging from
furniture and sporting goods to yachts, processed foods and pet
foods.
   The U.S. Embassy in Tokyo says recent trade promotions have
succeeded beyond expectations.
   Suzanne Hale of the embassy's agriculture trade office said a
U.S. food show this summer drew 6,000 visitors when 3,000 to 4,000
had been expected. Sales made at the show totaled $7.5 million and
exhibitors projected sales would increase by $133 million in the
coming year as a result of the show, she said.
</TEXT>
