<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0030,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with new figures, comment.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished higher Wednesday on the
London Stock Exchange as the market shrugged off the report of a
narrowing of the U.S. trade deficit in July.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index rose 8.8
points, or 0.5 percent, to 1,765.1.
   Volume was 394.6 million shares, compared with 369.2 million
shares traded Tuesday.
   The U.S. trade deficit shrank to $9.53 billion in July from a
revised $13.34 billion gap in June. Many analysts had been looking
for a deficit of about $11.5 billion for July.
   Experts said London shares failed to react to the U.S. trade
news because there are still grave concerns facing the British
economy, particularly its own trade deficit problem.
   ``The subdued response to the figures can only be attributed to
the fact that institutional sentiment remains unenthusiastic
towards the U.K. market,'' one analyst said.
   Paul Harrison, a director at County NatWest WoodMac in London,
said interest rate concerns continue to weigh on the British market.
   ``There were some worries in the back of people's minds that
with the dollar surging and sterling under pressure, there might be
another round of interest rate increases to lift the pound,'' he
said.
   Several market watchers said traders in London found it
disturbing that Wall Street did not sustain an advance on the trade
figures.
   In New Yorrk, the Dow Jones industrial average was up only 2.31
points to 2,085.35 by the close of trading in London.
   In London, the Financial Times 30-share index rose 6.7 points to
1,416.5. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 4.7 points to
998.61.
</TEXT>
