<HEAD>Dollar Jumps In Europe On Trade Figures, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AM version from New York expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Improved U.S. trade figures pushed the dollar
sharply higher in active trading in Europe Wednesday, but the
currency was prevented from rising further by fear of central bank
intervention.
   Gold prices also rose.
   The dollar inched up in the morning and was trading at about
1.8550 West German marks when the Commerce Department announced
that the U.S. trade deficit in July was $9.5 billion, considerably
narrower than the $11 billion to $12 billion gap that the market
had been expecting.
   The dollar shot up almost two pfennigs and then subsided
slightly to about 1.8700 marks before rising again late in the day.
   Dealers said the dollar's rise was curtailed by fear that the
central banks would seek to knock the currency down. Those fears
were followed by unconfirmed reports later in New York that the
Federal Reserve had stepped in to sell dollars.
   In London, the dollar soared against the British pound. It cost
$1.6750 to buy one pound, cheaper than late Tuesday's $1.6965.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
1.8783 West German marks, up from 1.8470; 1.5835 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5600; 6.3915 French francs, up from 6.2935; 2.1155 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.0845; 1,399.50 Italian lire, up from 1,380.50;
and 1.2223 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2307.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar rose 0.38 Japanese yen to close at 133.45 yen. Later in
London it gained further to 134.55 yen.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $421.75 a troy ounce,
compared with $420.00 bid late Tuesday. In Zurich, gold rose to
$421.50 from $421.00 bid late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 76 cents to close at a bid of
$423.45.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.53 a troy ounce, compared
with Tuesday's $6.46.
</TEXT>
