<FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 1435EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Puttnam-Films     09-14 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puttnam-Films,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Film Producer Forms Joint Venture With Warner Brothers, Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British film producer David Puttnam said Wednesday
he has formed a four-year joint venture with Warner Brothers Inc.
and other international investors to back his next six major
feature films.
   The announcement came about a year after Puttnam, who has
produced such films as ``The Killing Fields'' and ``Chariots of
Fire,'' resigned as chairman and chief executive of Coca-Cola Co.'s
Columbia Pictures after completing only 15 months of a three-year
contract.
   Puttnam, 47, left the studio after Coca-Cola merged Columbia
Pictures with Tri-Star Pictures and brought Victor Kaufman in as
president and chief executive of the combined operation.
   During his brief tenure in Hollywood, Puttnam reportedly clashed
with members of the entertainment industry establishment.
   In addition to Warner Brothers and Puttnam's own company Enigma
Productions, the partners in the joint venture are Fujisankei
Communications, Japan's largest mass communications company;
British Satellite Broadcasting and County NatWest Ventures, the
venture capital unit of National Westminster Bank PLC.
   At a news conference, Puttnam refused to disclose the exact size
of each partner's stake, saying only that ``We regard ourselves as
equal partners.''
   He will produce the films through Enigma, which will have a
production fund of $50 million in addition to income it makes from
its films.
   The venture intends to make movies aimed at a broad
international audience.
   ``We all share a perspective which tells us that films can and
should be made for the international marketplace,'' said Terry
Semel, president of Warner Brothers, which is based in Burbank,
Calif.
   Asked if he would continue his efforts to cut production costs,
which proved unpopular in Hollywood, Puttnam said, ``One thing I've
learned is to try and resist ideologies.''
   The producer said he intends to cast ``the best people for the
best films as possible.''
   Warner Brothers' Semel said, ``He can make hit films with both
unknown and known filmmakers.''
   Puttnam said he expects the venture to release its first film in
the autumn of 1990.
   The venture's movies will be distributed worldwide by Warner
Brothers with two exceptions. Fujisankei will be responsible for
video and television distribution in Japan and British Satellite
Broadcasting has acquired the British satellite television rights.
   The Fujisankei group includes the Fuji television network and
the Sankei Shimbun newspapers and publishing companies.
</TEXT>
