<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mostly Higher On Hurricane Fears, Export Demand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly higher
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade on new export demand and
speculation that Hurricane Gilbert posed a threat to crops,
analysts said.
   Analysts said Gilbert's record-high winds and heavy rain were
not likely to cause serious damage to soybean crops in Louisiana
and Mississippi since few of those fields are near the Gulf Coast.
   But storms spawned by the hurricane could play havoc with corn
and soybean crops in the Midwest, where a summer drought has
weakened the stalks of many plants, analysts said.
   Corn also benefitted from Tuesday's news that the Soviet Union
had purchased 350,000 metric tons of U.S. corn from private
exporters, said Walter Spilka, a grain-market analyst in New York
with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Wheat futures were supported by reports that Morocco and Jordan
had bid for U.S. wheat, Spilka said.
   ``The wheat market is acting very well and adding exports adds
strength to it,'' he said.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 3 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.12 a bushel; corn was {
cent lower to { cent higher with September at $2.85 a bushel; oats
were } cent to 3 cents higher with September at $2.68 a bushel;
soybeans were 5 cents lower to 5 cents higher with September at
$8.81 a bushel.
</TEXT>
