<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-14 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Jumps on Trade Data, Gold Slightly Weaker in New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Money traders scrambled to buy dollars Wednesday
after the government announced the sharpest trade-deficit drop in
nearly six years, driving up the currency's value despite Federal
Reserve intervention.
   Gold prices declined marginally in late U.S. trading after
rising abroad. Republic National Bank in New York quoted bullion at
$429.80 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down 10 cents from the same
time Tuesday.
   Currency-market analysts said the Commerce Department's report
that the July trade deficit narrowed to $9.5 billion in July, about
$3 billion below expectations, incited a wild dollar buying spree
that overwhelmed central-bank attempts to moderate the rise through
small bursts of dollar selling.
   ``They just plummeted the foreign currencies against the
dollar,'' said Kenneth Jakubzak, fund director for managed accounts
at First Commercial Financial Group Inc, a Chicago-based currency
futures trading concern. ``There was some Fed selling of dollars,
but traders just ignored it.''
   The 28 percent June-to-July deficit decrease was the biggest
improvement since a 35.7 percent narrowing in September 1982. It
gave the country the lowest monthly imbalance since December 1984,
when the deficit was $8 billion.
   Traders interpreted the Commerce Department report as a strong
signal that America's appetite for imports is waning, thereby
reducing inflation prospects and strengthening the relative worth
of the dollar vs. other currencies.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.38 Japanese yen to close at 133.45
yen. Later in London it gained further to 134.55 yen. By the time
trading closed in New York the dollar fetched 134.27 yen, vs.
133.37 yen late Tuesday.
   The dollar soared against the British pound in London, where
sterling fetched $1.6750, vs. $1.6965 late Tuesday. Later in New
York sterling was quoted at $1.6793, cheaper than its $1.6941 level
late Tuesday.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York compared with levels late
Tuesday: 1.8770 West German marks, up from 1.8534; 1.5817 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5608; 1.2241 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2283;
6.3875 French francs, up from 6.2950; and 1,398.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,383.50.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Tuesday:
1.8783 West German marks, up from 1.8470; 1.5835 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5600; 6.3915 French francs, up from 6.2935; 2.1155 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.0845; 1,399.50 Italian lire, up from 1,380.50;
and 1.2223 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2307.
   Gold rose in London to $421.75 a troy ounce, compared with
$420.00 late Tuesday. In Zurich, gold rose to $421.50 from $421.00,
and in Hong Kong it rose 76 cents to $423.45.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
fell 20 cents to $421.30.
   Silver rose on the London market to $6.53 a troy ounce vs. $6.46
Tuesday. On the New York Comex, silver for current delivery fetched
$6.489, up 1.2 cents.
</TEXT>
