<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Soviet-Advertising     09-14 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Advertising,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Advertising Firm Agrees on Joint Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. advertising company Young & Rubicam Inc.
and a Soviet government agency said Wednesday they had agreed on a
joint project to help Soviet and Western companies reach each
other's markets.
   The joint venture is expected to begin work here next January
with a staff of six, including two Americans.
   The announcement came in Soviet media reports in Moscow and in
an announcement released in New York where Young & Rubicam is based.
   ``Dozens of new Soviet exporters which entered the world market
clearly lack experience in promoting their goods, knowledge of the
commercial situation,'' Yuri Deomidov, head of the Soviet
organization Vneshtorgreklama, said in remarks reported by the Tass
news agency.
   ``The joint venture with Young & Rubicam ... will help them to
explore the market and will provide top-class advertising
services,'' he said.
   The Soviet government newspaper Izvestia said the Soviet
organization also will provide similar services to Western firms
trying to crack the Soviet market.
   ``If earlier it was enough for them to have several reliable
contacts in the Foreign Trade Ministry to strike a deal, now they
have to choose among hundreds of Soviet enterprises and foreign
trade firms,'' Deomidov said.
   Young & Rubicam said the new venture will be owned and managed
jointly with a board of directors having equal representation from
each partner.
   The Soviet organization will own 51 percent of the venture while
Young & Rubicam will own 49 percent, the statement said.
   Alex Kroll, chairman and chief executive of Young & Rubicam,
said a number of the agency's clients ``are already deeply involved
in developing joint enterprises with their Soviet industrial
counterparts.''
   ``We are delighted that we will be able to maintain our
tradition of prroviding service wherever our clients choose to do
business,'' he said.
   The privately-held Young & Rubicam is one of the world's largest
advertising companies with billings of $4.9 billion in 1987,
according to the trade journal Advertising Age.
</TEXT>
