<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CBSBoard     09-14 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBS Board,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Preston Robert Tisch Joins Brother on CBS Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businessman Preston Robert Tisch has been
elected to the board of CBS Inc., where he joins his brother, CBS
chief executive Laurence A. Tisch, the communications giant
announced Wednesday.
   Preston Tisch, better known as Bob, stepped down in March after
serving 19 months as U.S. Postmaster General. It had been
speculated widely that he eventually would join the CBS board.
   The Tisch brothers already have considerable economic ties.
   They serve as co-chief executives of Loews Corp., a tobacco,
real estate, insurance and hotel conglomerate that is CBS's biggest
shareholder. In addition, Preston is president and Laurence is
chairman of Loews.
   Preston's election to the CBS board at a regular board meeting
was announced by William S. Paley, the CBS founder and chairman.
   In a statement, Paley was quoted as saying the new board member
has ``broad experience in business and public affairs and he should
be a most valuable addition to the company.''
   His election boosts membership on the board to 14 from 13.
   The CBS board has operated with 13 members since September 1986
when Thomas P. Wyman was ousted as chairman and chief executive
following a dramatic boardroom battle.
   At that time, the board made Laurence Tisch acting chief
executive and Paley became acting chairman. Four months later, the
board deleted the word ``acting'' from their job titles.
   Under Tisch, CBS has trimmed costs, sold its magazine and
records divisions and seen its television network fall to third
place last season for the first time in the prime time ratings.
   Tisch has installed new executives at the head of the CBS
broadcasting and news operations and has vowed to put the network
back on top in the ratings.
</TEXT>
